David? Give David a hand.

00:05:26.510 --> 00:05:34.070
[ Applause ]

00:05:34.070 --> 00:05:37.010
&gt;&gt; David D. Hall: My remarks
are not about my favorite poem

00:05:37.010 --> 00:05:40.890
but about a -- mostly
about a favorite novel,

00:05:40.890 --> 00:05:45.920
although as you will see shortly,
not everyone's favorite novel.

00:05:47.060 --> 00:05:53.990
In 1851, a young man named Charles
Holbrook, very much a Yankee,

00:05:53.990 --> 00:06:00.500 position:56%
very much a native of Massachusetts,
graduated from Williams College.

00:06:00.500 --> 00:06:02.840
During the closing months

00:06:02.840 --> 00:06:06.920 position:56%
of his college career he had worried
a good deal about his future.

00:06:06.920 --> 00:06:09.230
Should he enter the ministry

00:06:09.230 --> 00:06:13.170
or perhaps start out
as a school teacher?

00:06:13.170 --> 00:06:16.300
A few months after
graduating he noted

00:06:16.300 --> 00:06:19.310
in a pocket diary he had been
keeping and would continue

00:06:19.310 --> 00:06:23.860
to keep during the experiences
I'm about to describe, that --

00:06:23.860 --> 00:06:26.370
and this is very characteristic
of recent college graduates,

00:06:26.370 --> 00:06:28.390
that he had been thinking
of happy days at college

00:06:28.390 --> 00:06:32.160
and wished almost they
were not ended.

00:06:32.160 --> 00:06:36.560
Several days later he received a
letter informing him that a planter

00:06:36.560 --> 00:06:42.840
in North Carolina was seeking
someone to instruct his children.

00:06:42.840 --> 00:06:47.700
Lacking, it seems, any other offer
of employment and, as he put it,

00:06:47.700 --> 00:06:52.740
tired of working on the family
farm, Charles, though unsympathetic

00:06:52.740 --> 00:06:54.810
to the institution
of slavery as we know

00:06:54.810 --> 00:06:58.510
from various entries,
accepted this offer.

00:06:58.510 --> 00:07:04.730
And in February 1852 traveled the
long way down to Rockingham County,

00:07:04.730 --> 00:07:09.060
North Carolina where he joined
the household of Thomas Galloway,

00:07:09.060 --> 00:07:14.110
a substantial planter who owns
some 30 slaves and whose children,

00:07:14.110 --> 00:07:15.920
together with those of a brother,

00:07:15.920 --> 00:07:19.330
become the new teacher's
responsibility.

00:07:20.340 --> 00:07:26.760
Several months later on
October 1st a neighbor arrived,

00:07:26.760 --> 00:07:34.510
and now I quote the diary, from
New York bringing many presents

00:07:34.510 --> 00:07:39.150
and <i>Uncle Tom's Cabin </i>.

00:07:40.590 --> 00:07:47.670
Immediately Charles took hold of
this book and began to read it.

00:07:47.670 --> 00:07:51.540
October 1st, "I've been
reading the first volume

00:07:51.540 --> 00:07:56.340
of <i>Uncle Tom's </i>tonight and
am much interested in it."

00:07:56.340 --> 00:07:58.820
It was a two-volume work
when it was printed.

00:07:58.820 --> 00:08:02.340
The next day, October 2nd.

00:08:02.340 --> 00:08:07.010
"I have completed volume
one of <i>Uncle Tom's Cabin </i>.

00:08:07.010 --> 00:08:09.870
Became much interested in it.

00:08:09.870 --> 00:08:13.750
It relates some exciting scenes."

00:08:13.750 --> 00:08:15.650
October 3rd.

00:08:15.650 --> 00:08:17.780
"Read the sublime, the pathetic,

00:08:17.780 --> 00:08:19.600
and affecting description
of Eva's death."

00:08:19.600 --> 00:08:23.070
That's the little girl who dies,

00:08:23.070 --> 00:08:28.320
described at some considerable
length, just a long time to die.

00:08:28.320 --> 00:08:34.400
"Oh, there are some such children
even in this land of darkness.

00:08:34.400 --> 00:08:39.210
The tears rushed into my eyes as
I read about her peaceful death

00:08:39.210 --> 00:08:43.870
and resolve tonight
to be more devoted."

00:08:43.870 --> 00:08:45.410
October 4th.

00:08:45.410 --> 00:08:49.250
"Finished <i>Uncle Tom's Cabin</i>
this morning at recess.

00:08:49.250 --> 00:08:53.890
I believe it to be the most
interesting book I have ever read.

00:08:53.890 --> 00:08:56.290
Poor, old Uncle Tom.

00:08:56.290 --> 00:09:02.670
He has gone to meet little Eva
in the better spirit land."

00:09:02.670 --> 00:09:04.560
October 5th.

00:09:04.560 --> 00:09:07.040
"Read some of <i>Uncle
Tom's Cabin </i>to Sandy,"

00:09:07.040 --> 00:09:09.230
who happened to be
one of his pupils.

00:09:09.230 --> 00:09:11.840
"He says Edie's sister

00:09:11.840 --> 00:09:14.910
at Mr. Harris's was tied
to a tree and whipped!"

00:09:14.910 --> 00:09:17.120
Lots of exclamation points.

00:09:17.120 --> 00:09:18.710
"That the man struck her first

00:09:18.710 --> 00:09:20.320
in the forehead with
the tobacco stick!"

00:09:20.320 --> 00:09:22.890
More exclamation points.

00:09:22.890 --> 00:09:27.730
Then we learn from the diary
that this novel was passing

00:09:27.730 --> 00:09:32.460
into other hands on the plantation.

00:09:32.460 --> 00:09:34.760
October 14th.

00:09:34.760 --> 00:09:41.850
Mr. G. likes <i>Uncle Tom's
Cabin </i>but Mrs. G.,"

00:09:41.850 --> 00:09:45.180
Mrs. Galloway, "is
bitter against it."

00:09:45.180 --> 00:09:46.640
October 15th.

00:09:46.640 --> 00:09:49.830
"Great talk in the
house about Mrs. Stow.

00:09:49.830 --> 00:09:53.000
Mr. G. is honest, he says he
admires <i>Uncle Tom's Cabin </i>for its

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:55.560
true characters."

00:09:55.560 --> 00:09:57.800
October 16th.

00:09:57.800 --> 00:10:01.800
"Mr. Galloway says he will
burn <i>Uncle Tom's Cabin </i>.

00:10:01.800 --> 00:10:04.010
He has changed his mind on it.

00:10:04.010 --> 00:10:10.280
Mrs. G. thinks Mrs. Stow
is worse than Legree."

00:10:10.280 --> 00:10:16.750
Out of this sequence of reactions
recorded for us in a diary

00:10:16.750 --> 00:10:22.500 position:56%
that by chance has survived into our
own times, I and Barbara Sicherman,

00:10:22.500 --> 00:10:25.510
and Joan Rubin, and
others, many others,

00:10:25.510 --> 00:10:31.860
are helping to fashion a history
of reading in America that has

00:10:31.860 --> 00:10:37.720
to simplify two principle
objectives.

00:10:37.720 --> 00:10:42.120
The first is to understand the
text that readers encountered

00:10:42.120 --> 00:10:45.230
in past times as well
as in the present.

00:10:45.230 --> 00:10:51.180
And the second is to understand the
responses of readers themselves.

00:10:51.180 --> 00:10:57.220
And as we are constantly
rediscovering these two elements

00:10:57.220 --> 00:11:01.300
of a history of reading,
text on the one hand, readers

00:11:01.300 --> 00:11:09.390 position:56%
and their responses on the other are
confusingly ambiguous and complex

00:11:09.390 --> 00:11:13.890
as indeed as indicated by
these episodes narrated

00:11:13.890 --> 00:11:17.910
in the diary of Charles Holbrook.

00:11:17.910 --> 00:11:23.470
Texts most certainly imposed
themselves on readers.

00:11:23.470 --> 00:11:28.250
Like Charles Holbrook weeping
as he read <i>Uncle Tom's Cabin </i>,

00:11:28.250 --> 00:11:33.090
who among us has not been
captured, or swept away,

00:11:33.090 --> 00:11:37.820
or possessed by something
we have read?

00:11:37.820 --> 00:11:41.860
But on the other hand, who among
us has not been suspicious of,

00:11:41.860 --> 00:11:45.850
or found ourselves resisting
text that we encounter?

00:11:45.850 --> 00:11:47.760
A resistance summed
up in the truism,

00:11:47.760 --> 00:11:50.470
the merits of which are
demonstrated every day,

00:11:50.470 --> 00:11:53.420
don't believe everything you read.

00:11:53.420 --> 00:11:58.720
The history of reading is at once
therefore a history of agency,

00:11:58.720 --> 00:12:03.360
that is of readers as actors
choosing, appropriating, modifying,

00:12:03.360 --> 00:12:06.470
reworking in various
ways, and of texts.

00:12:06.470 --> 00:12:09.970
And by texts I mean all kinds
of texts, poems, and novels,

00:12:09.970 --> 00:12:13.900
and many other forms of
printed work or written work.

00:12:13.900 --> 00:12:17.900
Of texts or narratives structures
that impose themselves on us,

00:12:17.900 --> 00:12:20.830
that constrain in some
manner, that are free

00:12:20.830 --> 00:12:25.010
and that shape us in
some deep sense.

00:12:25.010 --> 00:12:28.930
Both aspects, agency and
constraint are evident

00:12:28.930 --> 00:12:32.350
on the Galloway Plantation
in October 1852,

00:12:32.350 --> 00:12:36.920
as the remarkable novel made its
way around this group of readers.

00:12:36.920 --> 00:12:39.940
Charles Holbrook, swept away --

00:12:39.940 --> 00:12:46.110
swept away by the power of this
story of mothers, white and black,

00:12:46.110 --> 00:12:52.900
who lose their children to
illness or to the social death

00:12:52.900 --> 00:12:58.140
that slavery causes as
it splits families apart.

00:12:58.140 --> 00:13:01.360
A story which the underlying
plot contrasts.

00:13:01.360 --> 00:13:07.170
An amoral world in which money
and men have all the power

00:13:07.170 --> 00:13:12.950
and do cruel things to
women, children, and slaves,

00:13:12.950 --> 00:13:21.530
as opposed to the moral power
of women who resist this world

00:13:21.530 --> 00:13:24.880
of men and their amoral ways.

00:13:24.880 --> 00:13:26.330 position:56%
And then there's still a deeper plot

00:13:26.330 --> 00:13:30.740
that Charles Holbrook surely
was captured by as well,

00:13:30.740 --> 00:13:34.030
a world that God seems to
have abandoned, the distant

00:13:34.030 --> 00:13:36.480
and caring God of the
old [inaudible] theology

00:13:36.480 --> 00:13:40.690
that Harriet Beecher Stowe herself
found so cold and unsatisfying.

00:13:40.690 --> 00:13:45.010
And then the redemptive action,
not of churches and ministers,

00:13:45.010 --> 00:13:50.950
but of women and innocent children
such as Eva, and of Christians

00:13:50.950 --> 00:13:54.150
such as Uncle Tom, who like Christ

00:13:54.150 --> 00:13:58.220
of whom he is a figure
-- or refigured as.

00:13:58.220 --> 00:14:03.090 position:56%
Who like Christ submits to suffering
even unto death and in doing

00:14:03.090 --> 00:14:08.650
so from her perspective challenges
and even triumphs over the forces

00:14:08.650 --> 00:14:11.990
of cruelty and amorality.

00:14:11.990 --> 00:14:16.370
Yet this of course is not the only
way to read <i>Uncle Tom's Cabin </i>.

00:14:16.370 --> 00:14:19.480
Like Mr. and Mrs. Galloway
southerners in the 1850's

00:14:19.480 --> 00:14:22.910
and even some northerners
were outraged by the novel

00:14:22.910 --> 00:14:26.380
and produced a rash of
fictional responses.

00:14:26.380 --> 00:14:32.780
Aunt Phyllis's cabin, or Uncle
Robin in his cabin in Virginia

00:14:32.780 --> 00:14:35.880
and Tom without one in Boston.

00:14:37.470 --> 00:14:41.560
That's effort to -- maybe
you already know this --

00:14:41.560 --> 00:14:45.990
that's an effort to reverse the
plot of <i>Uncle Tom's Cabin </i>and

00:14:45.990 --> 00:14:50.660
to suggest that wage slavery
in the North was far crueler

00:14:50.660 --> 00:14:55.330
than the paternal,
loving, domestic slavery --

00:14:55.330 --> 00:14:58.910
slave system in which the
planters, or the fathers

00:14:58.910 --> 00:15:01.780
and the planters wives, or the
mothers, and so forth and so on,

00:15:01.780 --> 00:15:05.510
to take the same domesticity idea
and make it work for the South.

00:15:05.510 --> 00:15:06.990
Incidentally an idea
that is referred

00:15:06.990 --> 00:15:10.560
to in <i>Uncle Tom's Cabin </i>where
little Eva at one point says,

00:15:10.560 --> 00:15:14.030
astonishingly enough when the
question raised is slavery moral

00:15:14.030 --> 00:15:15.930
or immoral, she says,
"Well slavery makes

00:15:15.930 --> 00:15:18.200
so many more around us to love."

00:15:18.200 --> 00:15:20.520
That's the domestic
ideology transformed

00:15:20.520 --> 00:15:22.340
into a defense of slavery.

00:15:22.340 --> 00:15:26.930
I suspect however that Mrs.
Galloway, who is clearly the one

00:15:26.930 --> 00:15:29.700
who detests the novel the most
was reacting to other threats

00:15:29.700 --> 00:15:33.250
in the novel, including for
example, the many examples --

00:15:33.250 --> 00:15:37.990
including the characters who are
black women serving as mistresses

00:15:37.990 --> 00:15:43.560
of white men and of white
women who are lazy, indolent,

00:15:43.560 --> 00:15:47.320
and really in some
sense anti-mothers.

00:15:47.320 --> 00:15:50.690 position:56%
Much later after the Second World
War certain African American readers

00:15:50.690 --> 00:15:53.960
would join the Galloway's
in resisting this text,

00:15:53.960 --> 00:15:57.870
at a point where it's theological
framework of suffering women

00:15:57.870 --> 00:16:01.950
and slaves as stand-ins for Christ
and of redemption occurring not

00:16:01.950 --> 00:16:06.160
by social revolution but by some
longer arc of God's providence,

00:16:06.160 --> 00:16:09.520
no longer made much sense.

00:16:09.520 --> 00:16:15.120
These readers refigured Uncle
Tom, not as an agent of salvation

00:16:15.120 --> 00:16:18.970
but as someone who
accommodated himself to a corrupt

00:16:18.970 --> 00:16:21.700
and amoral social system
and in doing

00:16:21.700 --> 00:16:26.740
so betrayed the possibilities
for direct resistance.

00:16:26.740 --> 00:16:30.570
Uncle Tom, the way we use
the term so often today.

00:16:30.570 --> 00:16:35.360
Still closer to our own days
feminist readers have resisted the

00:16:35.360 --> 00:16:39.310
idea and image of home as
this remarkably harmonious

00:16:39.310 --> 00:16:44.770
and benevolent place that's
still accepted and exalted

00:16:44.770 --> 00:16:48.060
as the proper place for woman.

00:16:48.060 --> 00:16:51.130
And feminist readers have also
resisted Stowe's arguments the way

00:16:51.130 --> 00:16:55.500
for woman to overturn an amoral
social system was through suffering

00:16:55.500 --> 00:17:01.100
and sacrifice in their
own distinctive sphere.

00:17:01.100 --> 00:17:06.160
In these readings and re-readings,
and I daresay mis-readings

00:17:06.160 --> 00:17:10.280
of <i>Uncle Tom's Cabin </i>lay
the concrete particulars

00:17:10.280 --> 00:17:12.270
of a history of reading in America.

00:17:12.270 --> 00:17:14.530
A history that as I have indicated,

00:17:14.530 --> 00:17:18.550
is structured around an ever
recurring tension between the power

00:17:18.550 --> 00:17:23.370
of text to impose themselves on us,
to enter into our very selfhood,

00:17:23.370 --> 00:17:26.660
and on the other, as in these
examples that I have given,

00:17:26.660 --> 00:17:31.500
the power of readers to
suspend belief to accept

00:17:31.500 --> 00:17:36.010
or reject the logic of the text.

00:17:36.010 --> 00:17:40.840
There is therefore no simple
answer to the question how was such

00:17:40.840 --> 00:17:47.860 position:56%
and such a book read in the past or
what does a particular text reading?

00:17:47.860 --> 00:17:51.250
The history of reading is a great
field to work in because it is

00:17:51.250 --> 00:17:54.650
so remarkably open-ended
as we attempt to do justice

00:17:54.650 --> 00:17:57.500
to the complexities both of text

00:17:57.500 --> 00:17:59.840
and of the responses
of those who read them.

00:17:59.840 --> 00:18:01.640
Thank you.

00:18:01.640 --> 00:18:07.910
[ Applause ]

00:18:07.910 --> 00:18:09.210
&gt;&gt; Barbara Sicherman: Thank you.

00:18:09.210 --> 00:18:13.090
Having been privileged to see
the videos last night I see this

00:18:13.090 --> 00:18:19.150
contribution to today's events
as the meeting of reading

00:18:19.150 --> 00:18:24.050
in two past lives, or at
least a segment of that.

00:18:25.370 --> 00:18:29.140
"Books are the dreams we would most
like to have," writes Victor Nell,

00:18:29.140 --> 00:18:31.250
author of <i>Lost in a Book </i>.

00:18:31.250 --> 00:18:33.630
"Like dreams," he continues,
"they have the power

00:18:33.630 --> 00:18:36.960
to change consciousness,
turning sadness to laughter,

00:18:36.960 --> 00:18:40.550
and the anxious introspection
to the relaxed contemplation

00:18:40.550 --> 00:18:42.810
of some other time and place."

00:18:42.810 --> 00:18:45.640
Nell focuses here on
reading as escape.

00:18:45.640 --> 00:18:48.820
A fitting concern for a book
subtitled, "The Psychology

00:18:48.820 --> 00:18:50.610
of Reading for Pleasure."

00:18:50.610 --> 00:18:53.200
No mention of nightmares here.

00:18:53.200 --> 00:18:56.000
By examining the stories of
reading of two women born

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:59.970
under quite different circumstances
in the late 19th Century I hope

00:18:59.970 --> 00:19:03.670
to show that reading not
only changes consciousness,

00:19:03.670 --> 00:19:07.180
but by doing so can
also change lives.

00:19:07.180 --> 00:19:10.300
M. Carey Thomas, later
president of Bryn Mawr College,

00:19:10.300 --> 00:19:13.610
grew up in upper middle class
privilege, tempered somewhat

00:19:13.610 --> 00:19:16.460
by the family's Quaker
heritage, which in theory

00:19:16.460 --> 00:19:19.460
at least banned theater,
music, and novels, though not,

00:19:19.460 --> 00:19:21.720
it should be noted, poetry.

00:19:21.720 --> 00:19:24.320
But Thomas had access to
the world's great literature

00:19:24.320 --> 00:19:27.140
through a neighboring uncle
and to more current fare

00:19:27.140 --> 00:19:29.960
at Baltimore's Mercantile Library.

00:19:29.960 --> 00:19:32.940
Reading was as necessary
to her as breathing.

00:19:32.940 --> 00:19:35.190
On returning from an
Adirondacks vacation

00:19:35.190 --> 00:19:38.380
in her early 20's she
headed for the local library

00:19:38.380 --> 00:19:40.780
where she read for
four days straight.

00:19:40.780 --> 00:19:46.170
"And the hours were like seconds,
it was like treading on air.

00:19:46.170 --> 00:19:51.890 position:56%
It is the purest happiness, the one
thing which no man taketh from you."

00:19:51.890 --> 00:19:55.320
For Thomas reading was also
a vehicle for articulating

00:19:55.320 --> 00:19:58.270
and thereby intensifying ambition.

00:19:58.270 --> 00:20:01.670
"The fact is," she proclaimed
at 14, "I don't care much

00:20:01.670 --> 00:20:05.980
for anything except dreaming about
being grand, and noble, and famous,

00:20:05.980 --> 00:20:08.070
but that I can never be."

00:20:08.070 --> 00:20:10.970
But even then she hoped
to show that the woman

00:20:10.970 --> 00:20:14.530
who has fought all the battles
of olden time over again,

00:20:14.530 --> 00:20:19.090
whilst reading the spirited pages
of Homer, Virgil, Herodotus,

00:20:19.090 --> 00:20:23.670
been carried away by Carlisle,
and mildly enchanted by Emerson.

00:20:23.670 --> 00:20:27.760
Is not any less like what God
really intended a woman to be,

00:20:27.760 --> 00:20:30.120
than the trifling ballroom
butterfly,

00:20:30.120 --> 00:20:33.410
an ignorant doll baby
which they admire.

00:20:33.410 --> 00:20:35.480
The passage reveals
the possibilities

00:20:35.480 --> 00:20:40.450
for female heroism Thomas found
in classic text and demonstrates

00:20:40.450 --> 00:20:44.900 position:56%
as well the reciprocal relationship
between her reading and her ambition

00:20:44.900 --> 00:20:48.920
for it concludes, "My greatest
ambition is to be an author,

00:20:48.920 --> 00:20:52.380
an essayist, an historian,
to write hardy, earnest,

00:20:52.380 --> 00:20:57.130
true books that may do their part
towards elevating the human race.

00:20:57.130 --> 00:20:58.620
The woman who could read herself

00:20:58.620 --> 00:21:01.770
into books might grow
up to write them."

00:21:01.770 --> 00:21:06.310
Toward this end Thomas engaged in a
wide variety of literary activities

00:21:06.310 --> 00:21:09.470
from the ages of 13
and 15, and later,

00:21:09.470 --> 00:21:11.620
but these are the ones
I'm going to discuss.

00:21:11.620 --> 00:21:15.380
In addition to starting a journal
she kept a commonplace book,

00:21:15.380 --> 00:21:18.260
a list of favorite poems,
which I should've brought,

00:21:18.260 --> 00:21:21.530
and lists of books she had
read or wanted to read.

00:21:21.530 --> 00:21:24.200
She also wrote poetry
and short stories

00:21:24.200 --> 00:21:26.330
and sent one of each Harpers.

00:21:26.330 --> 00:21:27.630
Both were rejected.

00:21:27.630 --> 00:21:30.610
She was 12, 13 at this time.

00:21:30.610 --> 00:21:34.300
Although Thomas was precocious
she claims to have learned to read

00:21:34.300 --> 00:21:38.470
by age three and she started
Greek in her early teens.

00:21:38.470 --> 00:21:41.520
These pursuits were
by no means unusual.

00:21:41.520 --> 00:21:43.250
Girls of her class were expected

00:21:43.250 --> 00:21:45.760
to cultivate literary
self-consciousness.

00:21:45.760 --> 00:21:49.460
Like Thomas they kept diaries,
wrote and recited poetry,

00:21:49.460 --> 00:21:52.420
read aloud together, and
aspired to authorship,

00:21:52.420 --> 00:21:56.910
then the most prestigious
career available to a woman.

00:21:56.910 --> 00:22:01.530
When Thomas began her journal
in 1870, at the age of 13,

00:22:01.530 --> 00:22:04.180
she did so in the persona
of Jo March,

00:22:04.180 --> 00:22:06.440
the heroine of <i>Little Women </i>.

00:22:06.440 --> 00:22:08.270
"Ain't gonna be sentimental.

00:22:08.270 --> 00:22:10.210
No, no, not for Joe.

00:22:10.210 --> 00:22:14.120
Not Joe." And I should explain,
the first Jo is Jo March,

00:22:14.120 --> 00:22:16.420
and the second is a J-O-E, Joe.

00:22:16.420 --> 00:22:19.670
So she's saying that
this is a female Joe

00:22:19.670 --> 00:22:22.270
that she's going to be like.

00:22:22.270 --> 00:22:26.540 position:56%
Emulating a literary character was a
common practice among young diarists

00:22:26.540 --> 00:22:28.860
as they attempted to
establish their own personal

00:22:28.860 --> 00:22:31.010
and literary identities.

00:22:31.010 --> 00:22:34.150
Like Thomas, Jo was
a tomboy, a bookworm,

00:22:34.150 --> 00:22:36.580
and eager to do something splendid.

00:22:36.580 --> 00:22:38.900
Most importantly she
was a successful author

00:22:38.900 --> 00:22:40.890
who was paid for her writing.

00:22:40.890 --> 00:22:46.860
Alcott [inaudible] appealed,
because as Jo, J-O, not Joe, J-O-E,

00:22:46.860 --> 00:22:50.800 position:56%
she demonstrated that women could
be writers and in other ways aspire.

00:22:50.800 --> 00:22:54.530
Years later when Thomas was
embarking on graduate study

00:22:54.530 --> 00:22:57.660
in Germany a childhood
friend who had joined her

00:22:57.660 --> 00:22:59.570
in adolescent roleplaying
which centered

00:22:59.570 --> 00:23:03.490
around <i>Little Women </i>reflected,
"Somehow today I went back

00:23:03.490 --> 00:23:07.310
to those early days when
our horizon was so limited,

00:23:07.310 --> 00:23:12.070
yet so full of light, and our
path laid as plain before us.

00:23:12.070 --> 00:23:18.650 position:56%
It all came of reading over Ms.
Alcott's books, now the quintessence

00:23:18.650 --> 00:23:21.520
of philistinism, then a Bible.

00:23:21.520 --> 00:23:25.960
Doesn't thee remember when to turn
out a Jo the height of ambition?"

00:23:25.960 --> 00:23:28.710
<i>Little Women </i>was only
the beginning of course.

00:23:28.710 --> 00:23:32.210
In early adolescence Thomas also
crossed gender boundaries reading

00:23:32.210 --> 00:23:36.490
herself as a Carlislian
hero a [inaudible] hero.

00:23:36.490 --> 00:23:41.330
Later a devotee of the romantic
poets, Shelly especially,

00:23:41.330 --> 00:23:46.220 position:56%
Thomas adopted a worldview mode of
reading that fostered self-creation.

00:23:46.220 --> 00:23:49.760
In her early 20's her ambitions
were reinforced by members

00:23:49.760 --> 00:23:53.640
of a feminist reading circle
who read and wrote and dreamed

00:23:53.640 --> 00:23:56.760
and schemed to advance the
[inaudible] women together.

00:23:56.760 --> 00:24:00.760
Their later achievements included
securing the admission of women

00:24:00.760 --> 00:24:03.350
to Johns Hopkins Medical School.

00:24:03.350 --> 00:24:05.430
Can I get some water?

00:24:05.430 --> 00:24:08.180
Thank you.

00:24:08.180 --> 00:24:13.400
A very different story is
that of Rose Gollup Cohen,

00:24:13.400 --> 00:24:17.290
who was born in the Russian
[inaudible] in 1880 and grew

00:24:17.290 --> 00:24:20.790
up in an old world
tradition where reading

00:24:20.790 --> 00:24:23.800
and storytelling both
centered on religion.

00:24:23.800 --> 00:24:26.830
Like other Jewish girls she
learned Yiddish, not Hebrew,

00:24:26.830 --> 00:24:30.290
the language of sacred
text was for men only.

00:24:30.290 --> 00:24:32.880
Neither her mother or
father could write.

00:24:32.880 --> 00:24:36.120
Coming to the United
States at the age of 12,

00:24:36.120 --> 00:24:39.290 position:56%
as the oldest child she went to work

00:24:39.290 --> 00:24:43.390
in a factory foreclosing the
possibility of further education.

00:24:43.390 --> 00:24:48.170
In her autobiography, <i>Out of
the Shadow </i>, published in 1918,

00:24:48.170 --> 00:24:51.860
Cohen narrates her progress from
marginal literacy in Yiddish

00:24:51.860 --> 00:24:54.700
to authorship in English,
a change accompanied

00:24:54.700 --> 00:24:57.000
by an awakening self-consciousness.

00:24:57.000 --> 00:25:00.670
Unused to reading in the new
land she initially had to spell

00:25:00.670 --> 00:25:03.670
out the words of the
neighbor's Yiddish book,

00:25:03.670 --> 00:25:07.970
astonished that it was not
about religion but just a story.

00:25:07.970 --> 00:25:12.210
She became a regular customer
at the soda water stand,

00:25:12.210 --> 00:25:14.980
borrowing books at
five cents a copy.

00:25:14.980 --> 00:25:17.910
She read the volumes,
mainly romances,

00:25:17.910 --> 00:25:20.520
to her mother and siblings.

00:25:20.520 --> 00:25:22.470
They transported her.

00:25:22.470 --> 00:25:25.290
"And I live now in
a wonderful world."

00:25:25.290 --> 00:25:29.100
She was alternately a beautiful
countess living in a palace

00:25:29.100 --> 00:25:31.820
and a beggar's daughter
singing in the street.

00:25:31.820 --> 00:25:34.420
Her encounter with <i>David
Copperfield </i>in the Yiddish

00:25:34.420 --> 00:25:37.110 position:56%
translation was of a different kind.

00:25:37.110 --> 00:25:41.370
Electrified by the title of
the first chapter, "I Am Born,"

00:25:41.370 --> 00:25:44.720
and by the intimate first-person
narrative, she was filled

00:25:44.720 --> 00:25:47.100 position:56%
with a strange feeling of happiness.

00:25:47.100 --> 00:25:48.880
"Someone was talking to me.

00:25:48.880 --> 00:25:51.200
I could almost hear the voice."

00:25:51.200 --> 00:25:55.640 position:56%
Cohen had no doubt that this story
was real, something she used to love

00:25:55.640 --> 00:25:58.440
to know and she did
not want to let it go.

00:25:58.440 --> 00:26:02.300
She and her family did not
read another book for a week.

00:26:02.300 --> 00:26:06.280
Another volume, part letters,
part diary, similarly appealed

00:26:06.280 --> 00:26:08.280
because of its intimate tone

00:26:08.280 --> 00:26:10.610
and precipitated her
first hesitant efforts

00:26:10.610 --> 00:26:13.050
at authorship in the
form of a diary.

00:26:13.050 --> 00:26:16.750
Though she had to rub out most
of the first night's labor one

00:26:16.750 --> 00:26:18.670
but bold sentence remained.

00:26:18.670 --> 00:26:19.970
"I hate the shop.

00:26:19.970 --> 00:26:21.270
I feel sick.

00:26:21.270 --> 00:26:22.570
I feel tired.

00:26:22.570 --> 00:26:24.620
I cannot see any meaning in life."

00:26:24.620 --> 00:26:27.050
By this time Cohen's
reading went beyond the stage

00:26:27.050 --> 00:26:28.800
of vicarious adventure.

00:26:28.800 --> 00:26:32.460
Books were now a springboard
for emotional communication.

00:26:32.460 --> 00:26:34.380
Reading the diary had
triggered the desire

00:26:34.380 --> 00:26:37.020
to express herself
in personal writing.

00:26:37.020 --> 00:26:40.850
Diary-keeping and self-awareness
were mutually reinforcing.

00:26:40.850 --> 00:26:44.320
The diary encouraged introspection,
but the desire to keep one

00:26:44.320 --> 00:26:47.720
and her rejection at this
time of an arranged marriage

00:26:47.720 --> 00:26:52.180
to an incompatible man symbolized
in Cohen's account by his lack

00:26:52.180 --> 00:26:54.750
of interest in reading,
signaled an already

00:26:54.750 --> 00:26:56.590
heightened self-consciousness.

00:26:56.590 --> 00:26:58.600
Like many immigrants
Cohen learned English

00:26:58.600 --> 00:27:00.560
through a series of intermediaries.

00:27:00.560 --> 00:27:03.410
Night school, settlement
houses, and libraries.

00:27:03.410 --> 00:27:05.660
Although, she encountered
these only after she'd been

00:27:05.660 --> 00:27:07.930
in the States for five years.

00:27:07.930 --> 00:27:09.550
She finally learned to read English

00:27:09.550 --> 00:27:13.950
from the Bible during a three-month
stay at Presbyterian Hospital.

00:27:13.950 --> 00:27:16.220 position:56%
But her achievement was problematic.

00:27:16.220 --> 00:27:19.000
The volume was a New
Testament and her reading

00:27:19.000 --> 00:27:21.600
in Gentile books enraged her father

00:27:21.600 --> 00:27:24.550
who threw one of them
out the window.

00:27:24.550 --> 00:27:27.500
These books came mainly from
the [inaudible] Free Library

00:27:27.500 --> 00:27:32.230
at the Educational Alliance, a
Jewish Settlement in New York

00:27:32.230 --> 00:27:36.540
where she had gone first
seeking a volume of Shakespeare.

00:27:36.540 --> 00:27:40.750
Unable to understand <i>Julius Caesar</i>
she requested an English book,

00:27:40.750 --> 00:27:43.750
like for a child, and was
rewarded with <i>Little Women </i>,

00:27:43.750 --> 00:27:47.700
which seems to have been the
iconic book for immigrants.

00:27:47.700 --> 00:27:51.740
As her skills improved Cohen
read widely, favoring Dickens,

00:27:51.740 --> 00:27:56.560
Longfellow's <i>The Day is Done </i>,
and Olive Schreiner's <i>Dreams </i>,

00:27:56.560 --> 00:27:58.520
a series of allegories,

00:27:58.520 --> 00:28:02.310
which I think influenced
her own writing style.

00:28:02.310 --> 00:28:05.540
Reading not to escape her
situation but to comprehend it,

00:28:05.540 --> 00:28:09.260
Cohen turned to Silas Marner
which a friend recommended

00:28:09.260 --> 00:28:12.300
when there was trouble at home.

00:28:12.300 --> 00:28:14.700
"It was so that I loved
best to read.

00:28:14.700 --> 00:28:18.150
When I could see a connection
between life and literature,

00:28:18.150 --> 00:28:21.450
literature to me was
as real as life.

00:28:21.450 --> 00:28:23.740
Literature was life.

00:28:23.740 --> 00:28:28.640
Many amusement that was within
my reach I gave up to read."

00:28:28.640 --> 00:28:32.970
Reading offered solace that made
her own situation easier to bear,

00:28:32.970 --> 00:28:36.940
elicited a sensibility that helped
her understand it, and provided her

00:28:36.940 --> 00:28:41.840
with a language into which she
could translate her own experience.

00:28:41.840 --> 00:28:45.620
What did she mean when she
declared that literature was life?

00:28:45.620 --> 00:28:46.960
That she lived in books rather

00:28:46.960 --> 00:28:49.200
than amidst her impoverished
surroundings?

00:28:49.200 --> 00:28:51.430
That literature made life bearable?

00:28:51.430 --> 00:28:53.200
That she could not live without it?

00:28:53.200 --> 00:28:54.940
Perhaps something of all of these.

00:28:54.940 --> 00:28:58.040
<i>Out of the Shadow </i>ends
on an ambiguous note,

00:28:58.040 --> 00:29:00.700
with Cohen still laboring
to write English.

00:29:00.700 --> 00:29:04.480
We know she succeeds because she
has written her autobiography.

00:29:04.480 --> 00:29:08.870
It begins with the line, "I
was born in a Russian village."

00:29:08.870 --> 00:29:11.130
Perhaps an unconscious
echo of the passage

00:29:11.130 --> 00:29:15.280
in <i>David Copperfield </i>that had
captivated her years before.

00:29:15.280 --> 00:29:18.190
Cohen went on to publish
several short pieces,

00:29:18.190 --> 00:29:21.240
one a story of Russian village
life was selected as one

00:29:21.240 --> 00:29:24.030
of the best stories of 1922.

00:29:24.030 --> 00:29:28.130
As she described the process of
creation, when the first pictures

00:29:28.130 --> 00:29:30.020
of the story came to her she fell

00:29:30.020 --> 00:29:32.740
into weeping with the
peasant mother.

00:29:32.740 --> 00:29:36.330
"I was no longer building a
story, I was living the life

00:29:36.330 --> 00:29:38.580
of my childhood over again."

00:29:38.580 --> 00:29:41.710
Perhaps the emotional intensity
of the creative act helps

00:29:41.710 --> 00:29:47.910
to explain why the editor of the
volume ranked Natalka's portion

00:29:47.910 --> 00:29:52.730
as one of the works that unite
genuine substance and artistic form

00:29:52.730 --> 00:29:55.830
in a closely woven
pattern with such sincerity

00:29:55.830 --> 00:30:00.060
that these stories may fairly claim
a position in American literature.

00:30:00.060 --> 00:30:03.220
It was an extraordinary achievement
for one who had struggled

00:30:03.220 --> 00:30:05.770
for literacy and who
had learned English

00:30:05.770 --> 00:30:07.070
on her own in her late teens.

00:30:07.070 --> 00:30:10.480
It also I think is an
interesting definition

00:30:10.480 --> 00:30:14.070
of what constitutes
American literature,

00:30:14.070 --> 00:30:17.190
since these were Russian stories.

00:30:17.190 --> 00:30:19.990
In different ways then
reading helped Thomas

00:30:19.990 --> 00:30:23.630 position:56%
and Cohen obtain more self-assertive
identities than were expected

00:30:23.630 --> 00:30:25.980
of women of their time and place.

00:30:25.980 --> 00:30:30.410
During adolescence both moved on
from reading and dreaming to trying

00:30:30.410 --> 00:30:34.090 position:56%
to realize their dreams in the first
instance by bringing them to life

00:30:34.090 --> 00:30:35.940
through the act of writing.

00:30:35.940 --> 00:30:37.910
I would argue then that reader --

00:30:37.910 --> 00:30:43.350 position:56%
reading, even pleasure reading bears
a more complex relationship to life

00:30:43.350 --> 00:30:46.270
than the one suggested
earlier by Victor Nell.

00:30:46.270 --> 00:30:50.680
The imaginative space
opened up by reading can,

00:30:50.680 --> 00:30:54.880
under the right circumstances
stimulate creativity

00:30:54.880 --> 00:30:57.340
and foster a reciprocal rather

00:30:57.340 --> 00:31:01.510
than a one-way relationship
between books and lives.

00:31:01.510 --> 00:31:07.080
[ Applause ]

00:31:07.080 --> 00:31:08.380
&gt;&gt; Joan Shelley Rubin: Thank you.

00:31:08.380 --> 00:31:11.120
After seeing the videos last night
several of us were tempted just

00:31:11.120 --> 00:31:13.380
to throw out our remarks for today

00:31:13.380 --> 00:31:17.240
and to let those stand
in all of their power.

00:31:17.240 --> 00:31:20.680
I guess I've been dissuaded
from that move.

00:31:20.680 --> 00:31:27.340 position:56%
But before I start my brief comments
I do want to just say that our idea

00:31:27.340 --> 00:31:29.170
as John Cole already indicated,

00:31:29.170 --> 00:31:33.380
was to connect the Favorite Poem
Project, to some of the work

00:31:33.380 --> 00:31:38.210
that we're doing in the History of
Reading to give the project a kind

00:31:38.210 --> 00:31:41.230
of historical context and also,

00:31:41.230 --> 00:31:45.690 position:56%
to indicate how much this project is
going to mean for us as historians.

00:31:45.690 --> 00:31:50.810
This is exactly what we wish
we had for readers in the past.

00:31:50.810 --> 00:31:55.830
I also want to thank all of the
participants in today's symposium,

00:31:55.830 --> 00:31:59.340
many of whom I personally
dragooned into being here.

00:31:59.340 --> 00:32:04.480
They have told me that they were
delighted to be there last night

00:32:04.480 --> 00:32:07.910
and also of course to carry
on the conversation with you

00:32:07.910 --> 00:32:13.290
but they already feel well paid
by what we saw last evening.

00:32:13.290 --> 00:32:18.330
Well, I began to look into the
history of poetry reading --

00:32:18.330 --> 00:32:23.300 position:56%
God now quite a few years ago and
when I began that undertaking I came

00:32:23.300 --> 00:32:28.770
across a comment that William Dean
Howells, the novelist but also

00:32:28.770 --> 00:32:32.180
at that time, this was 1902.

00:32:32.180 --> 00:32:38.020
Howells was occupying the editor's
easy chair at <i>Harper's </i>magazine,

00:32:38.020 --> 00:32:42.890
and I came across a comment that
he made after he polled his readers

00:32:42.890 --> 00:32:46.770
about whether or not they
believed that the United States was

00:32:46.770 --> 00:32:50.950
in the midst of a slump in poetry.

00:32:50.950 --> 00:32:54.330
There was no denying
Howells' acknowledged

00:32:54.330 --> 00:32:59.720
that the Anglo-American lords
of rhyme, as he called them,

00:32:59.720 --> 00:33:03.660
Longfellow, Whittier,
Bryant, Tennyson, Wordsworth,

00:33:03.660 --> 00:33:07.940
had passed from the
ranks of working poets.

00:33:07.940 --> 00:33:13.800
Some of the readers Howells
queried bemoaned this demise

00:33:13.800 --> 00:33:17.760
of the Anglo-American lords
of rhyme and they felt

00:33:17.760 --> 00:33:20.110
that there was a slump in poetry.

00:33:20.110 --> 00:33:23.380
Others insisted that the
genre was flourishing.

00:33:23.380 --> 00:33:27.090
But Howells himself made
a crucial observation

00:33:27.090 --> 00:33:31.190
when he remarked the really
interesting and important thing

00:33:31.190 --> 00:33:34.290
to find out would be
whether the love

00:33:34.290 --> 00:33:40.950
of poetry shares the apparent
decline of poetry itself.

00:33:40.950 --> 00:33:44.800 position:56%
Today no one would argue that poetry
is in a slump, quite the opposite.

00:33:44.800 --> 00:33:48.090
But in a sense the
Favorite Poem Project

00:33:48.090 --> 00:33:52.970
after almost 100 years gives
Howells his answer and that is

00:33:52.970 --> 00:33:56.410
because the poet laureate's
inquiry has followed

00:33:56.410 --> 00:34:02.600
through on Howells' instinct to
disconnect reading and writing.

00:34:02.600 --> 00:34:04.990
Those of us who have
been working in the field

00:34:04.990 --> 00:34:07.960
of print culture have
been attempting

00:34:07.960 --> 00:34:13.470 position:56%
to construct a literary history that
describes more than just a series

00:34:13.470 --> 00:34:19.090
of movements, romanticism,
realism, modernism, and so forth.

00:34:19.090 --> 00:34:24.620
And instead to separate at least
somewhat the history of reading

00:34:24.620 --> 00:34:27.120 position:56%
from the vicissitudes of production.

00:34:27.120 --> 00:34:34.060
In that way we hope to recover the
ideas and values of ordinary people

00:34:34.060 --> 00:34:38.200
and to understand how they have
made sense of their experience.

00:34:38.200 --> 00:34:42.800
So I got into this myself a
few years ago when it dawned

00:34:42.800 --> 00:34:46.020
on me that poetry was a genre.

00:34:46.020 --> 00:34:50.360
That because it was
both intimate and public

00:34:50.360 --> 00:34:57.050
at least gave us half a chance of
recovering both what people read

00:34:57.050 --> 00:35:04.270
and how and why they read the text
that they had chosen and the way

00:35:04.270 --> 00:35:08.040
that the text gave them both
agency and constrained them,

00:35:08.040 --> 00:35:11.150
as David Hall has remarked.

00:35:11.150 --> 00:35:17.970
I can remind you that in the
period roughly from 1880 to 1950,

00:35:17.970 --> 00:35:23.560
Americans routinely encountered
poems at school, in church,

00:35:23.560 --> 00:35:27.700
at family gatherings, at community
events, and even as it turns

00:35:27.700 --> 00:35:30.930
out for some, in summer camp.

00:35:30.930 --> 00:35:34.300
I want to share with you this
morning just a brief look at some

00:35:34.300 --> 00:35:36.270
of the lessons that I've learned

00:35:36.270 --> 00:35:39.680
by exploring poetry
read at those sites.

00:35:39.680 --> 00:35:43.250 position:56%
I've already hinted at the first
lesson but I want to make it clearer

00:35:43.250 --> 00:35:45.690
to you by giving you an example.

00:35:45.690 --> 00:35:49.610
None of us can talk, including
Robert Pinksy himself.

00:35:49.610 --> 00:35:51.790
Thank you.

00:35:51.790 --> 00:35:56.980
Okay, this is an example
from the autobiography

00:35:56.980 --> 00:36:01.660
of a man named Walter Locke,
who became editor of the Dayton,

00:36:01.660 --> 00:36:07.300
Ohio Daily News in 1927, but
who grew up in the 1890's.

00:36:07.300 --> 00:36:10.650
Locke developed eye
problems after, as he put it,

00:36:10.650 --> 00:36:14.010 position:56%
he delighted intemperately in books.

00:36:14.010 --> 00:36:17.700
He decided that the
way out of this was

00:36:17.700 --> 00:36:19.990
through poetry and
through memorizing.

00:36:19.990 --> 00:36:24.100
Longfellow, Whitman, and
later Sandburg, and Millay.

00:36:24.100 --> 00:36:28.500
This memorization and then
recitation of the poems

00:36:28.500 --> 00:36:34.500
to himself became what he
called a way to carry on a life.

00:36:34.500 --> 00:36:37.920
But Locke described his
pursuit of poetry in language

00:36:37.920 --> 00:36:42.280
that suggests the cultural
tensions surrounding the genre.

00:36:42.280 --> 00:36:47.570
He was aware, in his words that
the age was choosing between poetry

00:36:47.570 --> 00:36:51.740
and speed and it was
not choosing poetry.

00:36:51.740 --> 00:36:55.500
And so he saw himself
forging an alliance

00:36:55.500 --> 00:36:59.050
with the poets the
world was passing by.

00:36:59.050 --> 00:37:03.010
In addition he associated
reading with addiction,

00:37:03.010 --> 00:37:06.990
intoxicant effects, and indulgence.

00:37:06.990 --> 00:37:11.450
So poetry was for Locke
a guilty pleasure,

00:37:11.450 --> 00:37:18.280
a source of what he called
his secret, joy, and shame.

00:37:18.280 --> 00:37:21.690
Now most of us are not accustomed
to thinking of reading Longfellow

00:37:21.690 --> 00:37:27.660 position:56%
in the terms we usually reserve for
sex and so this is a jarring remark,

00:37:27.660 --> 00:37:30.750
his secret, joy, and shame.

00:37:30.750 --> 00:37:33.430 position:56%
But Locke's clandestine relationship

00:37:33.430 --> 00:37:35.590
to poetry is highly
instructive I think.

00:37:35.590 --> 00:37:41.320
First it points out the inadequacy
of depicting the early 20th Century

00:37:41.320 --> 00:37:43.700
as simply the period
when the beginnings

00:37:43.700 --> 00:37:47.980
of early modernism planted
the schoolroom poets.

00:37:47.980 --> 00:37:52.460
Not only is Longfellow's work
alive and well but Locke,

00:37:52.460 --> 00:37:56.300
as he goes on as reader,
assimilates Carl Sandburg --

00:37:56.300 --> 00:37:59.000
this is very interesting --
he assimilates Carl Sandburg,

00:37:59.000 --> 00:38:03.680
a poet of smoke and steel, to
what he imagines was the simpler,

00:38:03.680 --> 00:38:06.100
slower life of the 19th Century.

00:38:06.100 --> 00:38:10.240
So this is an instance of
that kind of appropriation

00:38:10.240 --> 00:38:12.100
or we might even say misreading

00:38:12.100 --> 00:38:16.220
because of his own needs
and predispositions.

00:38:16.220 --> 00:38:19.460
Furthermore these eclectic
texts survive

00:38:19.460 --> 00:38:24.590
in Locke's memory giving them
an ongoing life in culture long

00:38:24.590 --> 00:38:28.410
after he has put aside
the printed page.

00:38:28.410 --> 00:38:30.970
There's another reader in
the same period who talks

00:38:30.970 --> 00:38:34.540
about his secret shelf collection.

00:38:34.540 --> 00:38:37.750
The books that he really loved
even though he knew that he had

00:38:37.750 --> 00:38:41.240
to exhibit what he called an
intelligent social self and that

00:38:41.240 --> 00:38:43.360
to do that meant that
he wouldn't talk

00:38:43.360 --> 00:38:48.440
about Longfellow's most sentimental
poems or the battered old volume

00:38:48.440 --> 00:38:51.800
of Tennyson that he had
on his secret shelf.

00:38:51.800 --> 00:38:56.690
That remark reveals not only this
closet of affection for verse

00:38:56.690 --> 00:39:00.570
but also, incidentally, the
practice of rereading older works,

00:39:00.570 --> 00:39:03.090
this battered old volume
that he keeps coming back to.

00:39:03.090 --> 00:39:05.690
So these confessional accounts

00:39:05.690 --> 00:39:09.710
of these [inaudible] poetry
lovers thus illuminate

00:39:09.710 --> 00:39:14.070
for us how the history of reading
can elude both conventional

00:39:14.070 --> 00:39:18.050
categories of literary
scholarship such as modernism

00:39:18.050 --> 00:39:22.890
and customary measures of
distribution such as sales figures.

00:39:22.890 --> 00:39:28.390
The second lesson that I
discovered is that site matters,

00:39:28.390 --> 00:39:31.180
the setting in which
readers are reading matters.

00:39:31.180 --> 00:39:37.060
Text acquire values and functions
as a consequence of those settings.

00:39:37.060 --> 00:39:41.800
Here I want to give you an
example of the classrooms

00:39:41.800 --> 00:39:46.400
of progressive educators in
the 1920's, those teachers

00:39:46.400 --> 00:39:49.440
who experimented with new ways
of instructing their students.

00:39:49.440 --> 00:39:54.780
In one of those classrooms we
find that pupils are learning

00:39:54.780 --> 00:39:58.770
to approach Edna Saint Vincent
Millay's lyrics by striving

00:39:58.770 --> 00:40:04.380
for what one educator called
apprehension, not comprehension.

00:40:04.380 --> 00:40:07.310
It doesn't seem to me those
have to be mutually exclusive

00:40:07.310 --> 00:40:09.010
but they were in this formulation.

00:40:09.010 --> 00:40:13.320 position:56%
And so in that milieu the
progressive classroom reading Millay

00:40:13.320 --> 00:40:17.000
became the occasion for
submitting to feeling.

00:40:17.000 --> 00:40:19.730
We have this review
that one student wrote

00:40:19.730 --> 00:40:23.530
after reading <i>The Harp
Weaver </i>and other poems.

00:40:23.530 --> 00:40:25.740
"It is cruel to review it.

00:40:25.740 --> 00:40:27.420
It is too lovely.

00:40:27.420 --> 00:40:31.710
Nothing can be said
better than read it."

00:40:31.710 --> 00:40:33.010
Now -- right.

00:40:33.010 --> 00:40:37.260
So, actually that's
sort of akin to how some

00:40:37.260 --> 00:40:40.540
of us felt about speaking today.

00:40:40.540 --> 00:40:44.600
It's cruel for us to do this
kind of analytical presentation.

00:40:44.600 --> 00:40:49.070
Nevertheless, for cultural
historians who are inclined

00:40:49.070 --> 00:40:54.570
to regard the 1920's as an era
of tough-mindedness and sort

00:40:54.570 --> 00:40:56.480
of new-minded sensibility,

00:40:56.480 --> 00:40:58.870
that comment is a telling
counter example.

00:40:58.870 --> 00:41:01.960
That's a very romantic
approach to the text to submit

00:41:01.960 --> 00:41:03.460
to the feelings of the text.

00:41:03.460 --> 00:41:07.370 position:56%
And yet at roughly the same time, in
the 20's, there's also the example

00:41:07.370 --> 00:41:11.820
of a Methodist minister who was
given to incorporating poetry

00:41:11.820 --> 00:41:16.760
into his sermons and he pronounced
Millay's <i>Renascence </i>an account

00:41:16.760 --> 00:41:22.140
of what he called a good,
old-fashioned religious conversion,

00:41:24.000 --> 00:41:29.230
thereby yoking her rebellious
sexuality to conservative impulses.

00:41:29.230 --> 00:41:33.170
Right? Which also characterized
the culture of the interwar period.

00:41:33.170 --> 00:41:36.070
That is the conservative
impulses are also there

00:41:36.070 --> 00:41:38.110
in the culture of the
interwar period.

00:41:38.110 --> 00:41:42.840
Finally, for the journalist
Margaret Parton, reading Millay,

00:41:42.840 --> 00:41:46.250
this is somewhat later, became
a test of the relationship

00:41:46.250 --> 00:41:48.260
between father and daughter.

00:41:48.260 --> 00:41:51.140
In the early 1930's while
Parton was a student

00:41:51.140 --> 00:41:56.640
at Swarthmore College she grew
anxious that, in her words,

00:41:56.640 --> 00:41:59.970
she might, "Let down
her parents by failure."

00:41:59.970 --> 00:42:04.390
She wrote home, as she said, "To
prepare them for this possibility."

00:42:04.390 --> 00:42:07.090
And her father calmed
her down with a letter

00:42:07.090 --> 00:42:10.700 position:56%
that reveals how this family worked.

00:42:10.700 --> 00:42:14.580
He responded, "If when I handed you

00:42:14.580 --> 00:42:18.300
that little Edna Saint Vincent
Millay poem you had tossed off some

00:42:18.300 --> 00:42:21.440
flip crack, or had been insensitive

00:42:21.440 --> 00:42:25.720
to its quaint Elizabethan
charm I would have flunked you

00:42:25.720 --> 00:42:28.650 position:56%
in practical and applied aesthetics.

00:42:28.650 --> 00:42:31.770
And I would not have felt
the serenity and assurance

00:42:31.770 --> 00:42:36.090
which now I give you my
word I feel about you."

00:42:36.090 --> 00:42:41.440
She passed the test and the poem
certainly further strengthened the

00:42:41.440 --> 00:42:44.510
bond between Parton and her
father, though it is clear

00:42:44.510 --> 00:42:48.160
that there is a great deal
at stake in this reading.

00:42:48.160 --> 00:42:53.950
So at school, in church, at home,
Millay's poetry read according

00:42:53.950 --> 00:42:59.140 position:56%
to different rules, served different
psychological and cultural purposes

00:42:59.140 --> 00:43:00.620
which I think were integral

00:43:00.620 --> 00:43:03.740
to reader's understanding
of its meanings.

00:43:03.740 --> 00:43:08.220 position:56%
Furthermore, and I hope this isn't
too dismaying to the poets among us,

00:43:08.220 --> 00:43:12.660
sometimes the history of poetry
reading reveals that the content

00:43:12.660 --> 00:43:17.900
of a poem matters far less
than the act of reading of it.

00:43:17.900 --> 00:43:23.460
Readers queried about their use of
verse frequently report practices

00:43:23.460 --> 00:43:26.060
that we might call anesthetic.

00:43:26.060 --> 00:43:30.290
So, you know, in the dentist
chair, on an airplane,

00:43:30.290 --> 00:43:34.620 position:56%
and it doesn't really matter at
that point so much what the text is.

00:43:34.620 --> 00:43:39.780 position:56%
More subtlety in many
circumstances of reading the setting

00:43:39.780 --> 00:43:45.440
and the feelings that
the reader brought

00:43:45.440 --> 00:43:48.900
to that setting overshadow
the poet's form and language.

00:43:48.900 --> 00:43:50.850
So here I'll give you
just one example.

00:43:50.850 --> 00:43:55.240
This comes from a woman named Clara
Holloway who was a teenager growing

00:43:55.240 --> 00:44:00.830
up on the Iowa frontier in the
1880's and who grew despondent

00:44:00.830 --> 00:44:05.070
because her future husband,
Eddie Grossbeck, failed to show

00:44:05.070 --> 00:44:07.950
up for her 18th birthday party

00:44:07.950 --> 00:44:10.860
and she was actually
given to self-blame.

00:44:10.860 --> 00:44:12.560
It's quite an interesting diary.

00:44:12.560 --> 00:44:17.130
But at any rate a few days later
Eddie made amends by coughing

00:44:17.130 --> 00:44:19.830
up a book of Wordsworth poems.

00:44:19.830 --> 00:44:23.120
Clara found reading
Wordsworth enjoyable

00:44:23.120 --> 00:44:26.640
but of much more importance was
the symbolism of receiving a book

00:44:26.640 --> 00:44:30.550
of verse from a boy of whose
affections she was uncertain.

00:44:30.550 --> 00:44:32.500
She later actually married him.

00:44:32.500 --> 00:44:34.260
But as she remarked in what I take

00:44:34.260 --> 00:44:39.100
to be a wonderful 19th Century
expression, "I shall prize it

00:44:39.100 --> 00:44:44.890
for the givens sake more
than for anything else."

00:44:44.890 --> 00:44:47.870
If the historical record
reveals that the site

00:44:47.870 --> 00:44:50.590
of reading sometimes
imparted to text,

00:44:50.590 --> 00:44:52.600
meanings we might call
extraneous due

00:44:52.600 --> 00:44:56.680 position:56%
to their literary qualities however,
it is equally important to see

00:44:56.680 --> 00:45:00.360
that it also shows us how
the same poems linked readers

00:45:00.360 --> 00:45:03.890
who occupy different social
and economic circumstances.

00:45:03.890 --> 00:45:06.940
And here I am thinking not only of
the Millay example where it's safe

00:45:06.940 --> 00:45:11.970 position:56%
to say that all of the readers I
mentioned were middle class but also

00:45:11.970 --> 00:45:14.230
of instances involving
working class readers

00:45:14.230 --> 00:45:18.800
such as the ones Barbara Sicherman
has noted, and more affluent ones.

00:45:18.800 --> 00:45:23.240 position:56%
With the development of a relatively
standardized educational curriculum

00:45:23.240 --> 00:45:29.220 position:56%
by around 1900 virtually everybody
read Longfellow and Byron in school.

00:45:29.220 --> 00:45:33.690
And to associate such poems only
with middle class culture is

00:45:33.690 --> 00:45:38.340
to forget what one writer, a
man named Rollo Walter Brown,

00:45:38.340 --> 00:45:40.350 position:56%
recalled in his memoir about growing

00:45:40.350 --> 00:45:43.900
up in the clay mining
country of Ohio.

00:45:43.900 --> 00:45:47.310
Brown discovered Byron
and Longfellow

00:45:47.310 --> 00:45:50.600
in a cookbook his mother
had borrowed --

00:45:50.600 --> 00:45:52.450
printed that is in the cookbook,

00:45:52.450 --> 00:45:55.160
and this fact I think
underscores one thing.

00:45:55.160 --> 00:45:59.200
The multiple and pervasive
forms of printed verse assumed

00:45:59.200 --> 00:46:01.510
in the early 20th Century.

00:46:01.510 --> 00:46:05.880
Reading Byron over and over he
committed lines to memory until,

00:46:05.880 --> 00:46:12.220 position:56%
in his words, "I could drop back
over my heels against a pile of clay

00:46:12.220 --> 00:46:15.950
and recite to myself with
unvoiced eloquence these

00:46:15.950 --> 00:46:20.320
or any other poems I knew and
then sit up and rake the shovel

00:46:20.320 --> 00:46:24.590
across the gritty floor with
pandemonium of approval."

00:46:24.590 --> 00:46:30.940
In that way he transmuted his
experience of work into an occasion

00:46:30.940 --> 00:46:35.660
when he said he could sort out
the choice parts of a world

00:46:35.660 --> 00:46:41.150
that ran off everywhere from the
face of the clay until a splash

00:46:41.150 --> 00:46:45.180
of roof somewhere reminded
him, woke him up,

00:46:45.180 --> 00:46:47.810
that he was still in a clay mine.

00:46:47.810 --> 00:46:51.160
While Brown's poetry reading
permitted him a vision

00:46:51.160 --> 00:46:54.660
of what we might call upward
mobility, it does still seem

00:46:54.660 --> 00:46:59.610
to me a mistake to say that it was
not part of working class life,

00:46:59.610 --> 00:47:06.030
especially since his approach
to rereading is quite parallel

00:47:06.030 --> 00:47:09.440
to the way his father reads
religious periodicals,

00:47:09.440 --> 00:47:13.110
which is to say that he reads them
over and over half a dozen times.

00:47:13.110 --> 00:47:18.980
At the same time, Brown's class
did not restrict his access

00:47:18.980 --> 00:47:22.640
to the same text that his more
affluent contemporaries were

00:47:22.640 --> 00:47:27.130
memorizing in other
settings at the same time.

00:47:27.130 --> 00:47:33.080
So, to those lessons that poetry
reading exhibited sustained,

00:47:33.080 --> 00:47:38.260
if sometimes hidden, a clandestine
vitality, that sites mattered,

00:47:38.260 --> 00:47:43.360 position:56%
that in some respects class did not,
I just want to add a final lesson,

00:47:43.360 --> 00:47:48.010
a final point, and that is that
for American readers the figure

00:47:48.010 --> 00:47:52.360
of the poet has worn
a variety of guises.

00:47:52.360 --> 00:47:57.390
The representation of the poet
as seer and visionary has been

00:47:57.390 --> 00:48:00.650
and remains a powerful
idea, but it has coexisted

00:48:00.650 --> 00:48:03.560
