01:22:34.530 --> 01:22:36.370
We always had popular music.

01:22:36.370 --> 01:22:38.250
And there's always been music.

01:22:38.250 --> 01:22:41.210
But there is just a
dramatic explosion

01:22:41.210 --> 01:22:46.070
in the whole music industry
beginning in the 1890's.

01:22:46.070 --> 01:22:48.680
Tin Pan Alley starts in the 1890's.

01:22:48.680 --> 01:22:51.680
Mechanically reproduced
sound starts in the 1890's.

01:22:51.680 --> 01:22:55.020
The player piano goes
on the market in 1898.

01:22:55.020 --> 01:22:58.970 position:56%
Records which were around for a
while, really take off in the teens.

01:22:58.970 --> 01:23:00.400
The radio is there in the 20's.

01:23:00.400 --> 01:23:03.930
The jukebox is there
in the 20's and 30's.

01:23:03.930 --> 01:23:07.840
Poetry is a mix of
cadence and words.

01:23:07.840 --> 01:23:15.110
Music is a mix of cadence, words
often and melody and harmony.

01:23:15.110 --> 01:23:18.940
There are whole ranges of ways
that these pieces then interact

01:23:18.940 --> 01:23:22.470
but music is not the
same exactly as poetry.

01:23:22.470 --> 01:23:25.550
And always in music,
words are diminished

01:23:25.550 --> 01:23:30.380 position:56%
in at least some small measure by --
because some part of the response,

01:23:30.380 --> 01:23:33.640
some part of the oral
response is devoted

01:23:33.640 --> 01:23:36.790
to the melody, the
harmony, the beat.

01:23:36.790 --> 01:23:40.880 position:56%
Cadence too -- actually while
there's flexibility in both mediums,

01:23:40.880 --> 01:23:49.400 position:56%
cadence too has less -- cadence too
has less flexibility in music rhythm

01:23:49.400 --> 01:23:53.200
than in poetry where you can really
dramatically change the reading

01:23:53.200 --> 01:23:55.470
of a poem by just deciding
you're going

01:23:55.470 --> 01:24:01.590
to stop, pause, and make a point.

01:24:01.590 --> 01:24:05.110
You can do this at times with music
but especially in ensemble music

01:24:05.110 --> 01:24:09.550
and live ensemble music,
the flexibility is less.

01:24:09.550 --> 01:24:14.420 position:56%
To the extent that popular music
becomes so important in the culture,

01:24:14.420 --> 01:24:16.610
it pushes poetry and the form

01:24:16.610 --> 01:24:19.220
of poetic expression
to a different place.

01:24:19.220 --> 01:24:24.020
If music is one thing in the
popular music industry is one thing

01:24:24.020 --> 01:24:26.550
that changes, a second
thing that changes

01:24:26.550 --> 01:24:29.600
in those periods is different
attitudes towards words

01:24:29.600 --> 01:24:31.120
and performance.

01:24:31.120 --> 01:24:38.420
One, is the rise in a dramatic
way of the plain style of prose.

01:24:38.420 --> 01:24:43.110
Rhetoric falls off the
map between 1880 and 1930.

01:24:43.110 --> 01:24:48.420
It was the most important way that
people initially learned some talk

01:24:48.420 --> 01:24:51.570
about poetry in the
mid-19th Century.

01:24:51.570 --> 01:24:54.210
It was through rhetorics
and rhetoric classes

01:24:54.210 --> 01:24:57.950
in high schools as
well as in college.

01:24:57.950 --> 01:25:01.860
As rhetorics fade, as
formal rhetoric fades,

01:25:01.860 --> 01:25:05.890
what takes its place, literally
takes its place in the late 19th

01:25:05.890 --> 01:25:10.540
to early 20th Century, the rhetoric
class is freshman composition.

01:25:10.540 --> 01:25:13.930
And freshman composition
becomes ruthlessly devoted

01:25:13.930 --> 01:25:20.480
to straightforward, plain, solid,
clear, unaffected English prose.

01:25:20.480 --> 01:25:23.110
Strunk and White's <i>Elements
of Style </i>rmal, for instance,

01:25:23.110 --> 01:25:25.120
a book more -- I can't think

01:25:25.120 --> 01:25:29.070
of a book more ruthlessly
devoted to the plain style.

01:25:29.070 --> 01:25:34.760 position:56%
It is originally published by Strunk
alone in 1919 as one of the end

01:25:34.760 --> 01:25:39.380
of the first wave of these freshman
composition books which are meant

01:25:39.380 --> 01:25:42.020
to replace older rhetorics.

01:25:42.020 --> 01:25:47.070
If the plain style becomes one
thing that becomes a new norm,

01:25:47.070 --> 01:25:49.200
the second is conversation

01:25:49.200 --> 01:25:53.200
or conversational style
of public performance.

01:25:53.200 --> 01:25:55.980
If rhetoric falls off
the map, oratory,

01:25:55.980 --> 01:25:59.500
formal oratory falls
off the map as well.

01:25:59.500 --> 01:26:01.720
Oratory was a sister art to poetry.

01:26:01.720 --> 01:26:05.340
It was about words and
rhythm, words and cadence.

01:26:05.340 --> 01:26:07.680
By the 1920's, people
like H.L. Mencken

01:26:07.680 --> 01:26:10.710
and Walter Lippmann are
making fun of formal rhetoric.

01:26:10.710 --> 01:26:14.150
By the 1920's, Dale Carnegie
who's famous <i>How to Win Friends</i>

01:26:14.150 --> 01:26:16.300
<i>and Influence People</i>
which was published

01:26:16.300 --> 01:26:18.570
in '30 -- in '36, I believe.

01:26:18.570 --> 01:26:23.540 position:56%
But by the 1920's, he is already
making a fortune teaching people how

01:26:23.540 --> 01:26:27.950
to speak in the new way and he
keeps saying, "Don't be affected.

01:26:27.950 --> 01:26:29.250
Don't be formal.

01:26:29.250 --> 01:26:30.660
Don't be rhetorical.

01:26:30.660 --> 01:26:32.210
Be conversational."

01:26:32.210 --> 01:26:34.570
Even in music,

01:26:34.570 --> 01:26:40.260
the new conversational style
appeared with crooning.

01:26:40.260 --> 01:26:44.090
Males had to project
before the microphone.

01:26:44.090 --> 01:26:48.150
Males had to project and
they had to and it led

01:26:48.150 --> 01:26:53.430
to a more formal sounding
song style.

01:26:53.430 --> 01:26:57.360
Crooning allowed people to
be relaxed and conversational

01:26:57.360 --> 01:27:03.690
in the 1920's and 30's, someone
like, Rudy Vallee or Bing Crosby.

01:27:03.690 --> 01:27:05.670
And finally, of course, the person

01:27:05.670 --> 01:27:08.410
who masters the new
conversational style

01:27:08.410 --> 01:27:12.350
of public communication is Franklin
Delano Roosevelt whose fireside

01:27:12.350 --> 01:27:16.870
chats are have nothing to do with
the formal oratory but are meant

01:27:16.870 --> 01:27:19.280
through the radio to
convey the impression

01:27:19.280 --> 01:27:26.230
that here is someone conversing
with you in your living room.

01:27:26.230 --> 01:27:29.920
Poetry can respond by and
certainly you can think

01:27:29.920 --> 01:27:32.900
of William Carlos Williams
as one example.

01:27:32.900 --> 01:27:36.970
But to the extent that poetry
consists of charged words,

01:27:36.970 --> 01:27:38.490
and where the delight comes

01:27:38.490 --> 01:27:41.580
from language centrally
then the conversational

01:27:41.580 --> 01:27:46.860
and the plain style also placed
poetry some place outside

01:27:46.860 --> 01:27:52.790
where the mainstream of public
communication was heading.

01:27:52.790 --> 01:27:56.200
Poetry then becomes, as Joan
talks about, a secret pleasure,

01:27:56.200 --> 01:27:59.980
a guilty pleasure for
people by the 1920's.

01:27:59.980 --> 01:28:03.080
By the late 1920's, Edmund
Wilson is making the point,

01:28:03.080 --> 01:28:04.380
is making this point.

01:28:04.380 --> 01:28:06.340
In his <i>Is Verse A Dying Technique?</i>

01:28:06.340 --> 01:28:09.200
Wilson says basically
yes, it's dying.

01:28:09.200 --> 01:28:12.160
And in this essay, he
pointed to both music

01:28:12.160 --> 01:28:15.010
and prose as displacing poetry.

01:28:15.010 --> 01:28:18.150
"Don't trust the talk about the
different schools of poetry.

01:28:18.150 --> 01:28:20.160
Don't let that get in
the way," Wilson said.

01:28:20.160 --> 01:28:23.560
"The important thing is to
recognize, it seems to me,

01:28:23.560 --> 01:28:26.750
is that the literary technique
of verse which was once meant

01:28:26.750 --> 01:28:31.620
to serve many purposes, now
we as a rule, use prose."

01:28:31.620 --> 01:28:35.720
Wilson basically thought
that prose was being --

01:28:35.720 --> 01:28:38.170 position:56%
was replacing poetry and he thought,

01:28:38.170 --> 01:28:41.680
"For the prose was
equal to the task."

01:28:41.680 --> 01:28:44.800
Wilson basically had
a tin ear for poetry.

01:28:44.800 --> 01:28:49.090
He was not good on poetry and he
was not concerned that he thought

01:28:49.090 --> 01:28:51.600
that verse was a dying technique.

01:28:51.600 --> 01:28:55.390
Yet, as we've seen today,
as we've seen from --

01:28:55.390 --> 01:28:59.100 position:56%
as we've seen in the videos
yesterday, as you all know very well

01:28:59.100 --> 01:29:01.420
from your life experience
more than me,

01:29:01.420 --> 01:29:04.960
as my life experience
says, "Wilson was wrong.

01:29:04.960 --> 01:29:06.910
Verse wasn't a dying technique."

01:29:06.910 --> 01:29:11.620
And this leads to point number
two, poetry's role shifts.

01:29:11.620 --> 01:29:13.590
Consider the contrast with oratory.

01:29:13.590 --> 01:29:17.390
By 1930, oratory is gone.

01:29:17.390 --> 01:29:18.700
No one's studying it.

01:29:18.700 --> 01:29:20.000
No one's thinking about it.

01:29:20.000 --> 01:29:23.140
In 1880, both poetry
and oratory were listed

01:29:23.140 --> 01:29:25.960
in most conventional
lists of fine arts.

01:29:25.960 --> 01:29:27.420
They were fine arts.

01:29:27.420 --> 01:29:34.470
By 1930, oratory is a distant
remain, and poetry continues

01:29:34.470 --> 01:29:36.690
to be one of the fine arts.

01:29:36.690 --> 01:29:42.370
In 1942, another essay
on poetry was delivered,

01:29:42.370 --> 01:29:46.170
Wallace Stevens' is <i>The Noble
Write and the Sound of Words </i>.

01:29:46.170 --> 01:29:49.900
Stevens saw as much as Wilson
the triumph of the real.

01:29:49.900 --> 01:29:52.760
He knew that the modern
poet "cannot be both --

01:29:52.760 --> 01:29:56.620
cannot be too noble a writer, that
he cannot rise up loftily in helmet

01:29:56.620 --> 01:30:00.870
and armor or horse
of imposing bronze."

01:30:00.870 --> 01:30:02.500
Yet he still, unlike Wilson,

01:30:02.500 --> 01:30:04.890
he still thought that
poetry had a place.

01:30:04.890 --> 01:30:09.000
Poetry was the fruitful mediation
between imagination and reality.

01:30:09.000 --> 01:30:15.460
And imagination itself gave
nobility to the real for Stevens.

01:30:15.460 --> 01:30:17.720
It was contemplation.

01:30:17.720 --> 01:30:19.970
"It was a way," he
says in this article,

01:30:19.970 --> 01:30:22.940
"to step outside mass culture."

01:30:22.940 --> 01:30:26.170
And he says, it was not
social but personal.

01:30:26.170 --> 01:30:30.710
He makes this point several
times and he makes it firmly.

01:30:30.710 --> 01:30:33.420 position:56%
"The poet's role in short," he says,

01:30:33.420 --> 01:30:36.010
"is to help people
to live their lives."

01:30:36.010 --> 01:30:39.410
In that same paragraph he says,
"I might be expected to speak

01:30:39.410 --> 01:30:42.550
of the social, that is to say the
sociological or the political,

01:30:42.550 --> 01:30:47.300
that those political
obligations of the poet but,"

01:30:47.300 --> 01:30:52.140
Stevens says, "He has none."

01:30:52.140 --> 01:30:55.460
Stevens' essay, I'd like to
make two quick points about.

01:30:55.460 --> 01:30:59.470
One is in some way; it's suggesting
recognizing a shifting place

01:30:59.470 --> 01:31:02.430
for poetry in the culture.

01:31:02.430 --> 01:31:09.380
That is, poetry is not the
real legislature for humanity,

01:31:09.380 --> 01:31:13.210
for mankind, for whatever it
is, for the universe [laughter].

01:31:13.210 --> 01:31:15.780
Like I always forget
-- but poetry is --

01:31:15.780 --> 01:31:18.270
&gt;&gt; The unacknowledged
legislators of the world,

01:31:18.270 --> 01:31:19.570
[inaudible] of Shelley's
<i>Defense of Poetry </i>.

01:31:19.570 --> 01:31:20.870
&gt;&gt; Kenneth Cmiel: Yes,

01:31:20.870 --> 01:31:23.170
so it's unacknowledged
legislators of the world.

01:31:23.170 --> 01:31:25.410
In some way, he recognizes
that it's not going

01:31:25.410 --> 01:31:27.900
to be the unacknowledged
legislator of the world.

01:31:27.900 --> 01:31:32.100
And that if it's not having the
sort of dramatic civic force

01:31:32.100 --> 01:31:36.300 position:56%
that Shelley imagined, that it still
had a strong place in the culture.

01:31:36.300 --> 01:31:37.610
So that's point number one.

01:31:37.610 --> 01:31:40.750
And point number two is
that this role was personal.

01:31:40.750 --> 01:31:43.120
That poetry becomes
a form of wonder,

01:31:43.120 --> 01:31:45.160
reflection on ourselves
and condition.

01:31:45.160 --> 01:31:49.990
It is a moment of quiet
in a loud mass culture.

01:31:49.990 --> 01:31:54.910
And this, as I watched the
spectacular videos last night

01:31:54.910 --> 01:31:58.850
which actually confirmed my own
thoroughly unprofessional contact

01:31:58.850 --> 01:32:01.240
with poetry in the past few years,

01:32:01.240 --> 01:32:05.030
is what I saw most of
the reciters doing.

01:32:05.030 --> 01:32:08.080
Whether it is people reflecting
and thinking about suicides

01:32:08.080 --> 01:32:12.440
in South Boston, about being
a gay African-American male

01:32:12.440 --> 01:32:15.330
in Atlanta, I believe.

01:32:15.330 --> 01:32:18.580
Whether it was having a
daughter dying of cancer

01:32:18.580 --> 01:32:21.980
or whether it was simply
a meditation on a slug,

01:32:21.980 --> 01:32:24.800
these were people who were
talking about reflecting

01:32:24.800 --> 01:32:27.100
about their condition,
who were trying

01:32:27.100 --> 01:32:31.200
to bring some expression
to the wonders of life.

01:32:31.200 --> 01:32:34.940 position:56%
These were people where words worked
like a clearing in the forest,

01:32:34.940 --> 01:32:36.680
where light can peer
down allowing us

01:32:36.680 --> 01:32:39.910
to see what might have always
been there but hidden from us.

01:32:39.910 --> 01:32:43.760
This was poetry as a
sort of uncovering.

01:32:43.760 --> 01:32:47.160
This is a personal
quieter form of poetry,

01:32:47.160 --> 01:32:49.370
a sort of wonder and reflection.

01:32:49.370 --> 01:32:52.320
If you think about it this way
then Emily Dickinson becomes the

01:32:52.320 --> 01:32:55.310
paradigmatic first modern poet.

01:32:55.310 --> 01:32:59.630
Now, if this is where we said
what Stevens in the 1940's,

01:32:59.630 --> 01:33:03.470 position:56%
I want to briefly talk about --
mention for one second, the benefits

01:33:03.470 --> 01:33:06.180
and dangers and the
benefits are this is a moment

01:33:06.180 --> 01:33:08.340
of quiet in a loud culture.

01:33:08.340 --> 01:33:10.090
And I like loud cultures.

01:33:10.090 --> 01:33:12.530
I think loud cultures are fun.

01:33:12.530 --> 01:33:15.850
As one of my favorite poets
and great moralist of our time,

01:33:15.850 --> 01:33:21.190
the Cat in the Hat says, "These
things are fun and fun is good."

01:33:21.190 --> 01:33:22.490
I like the internet.

01:33:22.490 --> 01:33:23.790
I like music.

01:33:23.790 --> 01:33:25.090
I like it all.

01:33:25.090 --> 01:33:26.390
I like my kids when they like it.

01:33:26.390 --> 01:33:29.970
But at the same time, I must
say, that I come back to poetry

01:33:29.970 --> 01:33:35.770
because it is a moment of quiet
for me in a rather loud culture.

01:33:35.770 --> 01:33:38.910
But the danger is that it can
become -- it's the same thing,

01:33:38.910 --> 01:33:41.910
the quietness, that it could
become too quiet, too personal.

01:33:41.910 --> 01:33:46.360 position:56%
I do not like Archibald MacLeish's
lines that a poem should be palpable

01:33:46.360 --> 01:33:48.970
and mute as a globed fruit.

01:33:48.970 --> 01:33:53.020
I have mixed feeling about
Stevens' <i>Of Modern Poetry </i>which

01:33:53.020 --> 01:33:57.000 position:56%
in some ways is a wonderful
introduction to 20th Century poetry.

01:33:57.000 --> 01:34:01.070
But when Stevens speaks of "the
poem of the act of the mind,"

01:34:01.070 --> 01:34:05.380
or of words speaking "in the
delicatest ear of the mind,"

01:34:05.380 --> 01:34:09.210 position:56%
or if he speaks -- when he speaks
of the invisible audience listening,

01:34:09.210 --> 01:34:12.360
it seems too self-contained
and a little bit too quiet.

01:34:12.360 --> 01:34:15.080
Poetry is sound, as Stevens knew

01:34:15.080 --> 01:34:18.890
but did not always adequately
express, to my opinion.

01:34:18.890 --> 01:34:20.560
Too quiet, too personal.

01:34:20.560 --> 01:34:26.760 position:56%
If you look at the last 10 to 15
years and if you think of two things

01:34:26.760 --> 01:34:30.620
that -- I strike me as important
in the public culture of poetry,

01:34:30.620 --> 01:34:36.500
one being the poetry slam movement
and the second being this sort

01:34:36.500 --> 01:34:43.430
of affair and the work that
Robert Pinsky has done.

01:34:43.430 --> 01:34:45.460 position:56%
Both of those things, it strikes me,

01:34:45.460 --> 01:34:49.510
are trying to say we can't
let poetry be too private.

01:34:49.510 --> 01:34:52.070 position:56%
We can't let poetry be too personal.

01:34:52.070 --> 01:34:54.610
It has to be a blend.

01:34:54.610 --> 01:34:57.640
Stevens was close but he
didn't entirely get it right.

01:34:57.640 --> 01:35:02.720
You have to have a mix, lest it
become too private, too personal.

01:35:02.720 --> 01:35:04.530
Lest it become too many people

01:35:04.530 --> 01:35:07.570
like my six colleagues
who've never read a poem.

01:35:07.570 --> 01:35:09.370
Thanks.

01:35:09.370 --> 01:35:17.890
