01:57:54.710 --> 01:57:57.860 position:56%
Now, just a couple of quick remarks.

01:57:57.860 --> 01:58:02.730
I've been engaged in for
almost a decade in a book

01:58:02.730 --> 01:58:05.350
that I just finished about
Derek Walcott when I started,

01:58:05.350 --> 01:58:08.670
I knew nothing about the
Caribbean where he comes from.

01:58:08.670 --> 01:58:11.200
So I had to learn a lot.

01:58:11.200 --> 01:58:14.130
And that culture gives you a
kind of basis for comparison

01:58:14.130 --> 01:58:18.060
because there is a tradition
of verbal play and performance

01:58:18.060 --> 01:58:22.710
that is not necessarily
confined to educated people.

01:58:22.710 --> 01:58:28.480
And there are extravagant uses of
speech in things like the rants

01:58:28.480 --> 01:58:31.860
of the Midnight Robber
and Trinidad Carnival.

01:58:31.860 --> 01:58:36.870
Or you know, when I look
at the poetry slams,

01:58:36.870 --> 01:58:41.600 position:56%
I think of another Trinidad
Carnival convention, the Calypso War

01:58:41.600 --> 01:58:45.000
where the leading Calypsonians
improvise verses sometimes

01:58:45.000 --> 01:58:48.750
satirizing each other and whoever
makes the wittiest responses

01:58:48.750 --> 01:58:51.920
and gets the most applause
wins the Calypso War.

01:58:51.920 --> 01:58:55.830
So it has this competitive
edge as well.

01:58:55.830 --> 01:58:59.860
Walcott has said, "I come from a
society that likes big gestures."

01:58:59.860 --> 01:59:06.800
And I think we come from a
society where ever since the turn

01:59:06.800 --> 01:59:09.020
of the 20th Century
when the conventions

01:59:09.020 --> 01:59:13.520
of Victorian poetry were getting
kind of flyblown, we've been kind

01:59:13.520 --> 01:59:17.290
of walking backwards
away from big gestures.

01:59:17.290 --> 01:59:21.660
Ken's remark about the decline
of rhetoric and the replacement

01:59:21.660 --> 01:59:25.700 position:56%
of rhetoric classes with composition
classes that emphasize clarity

01:59:25.700 --> 01:59:31.210
and plainness rather than flourish,
I think is quite indicative.

01:59:31.210 --> 01:59:36.860
I think World War I really
did a lot to kill rhetoric.

01:59:36.860 --> 01:59:41.140
You know, people came back
from the war like Wilfred --

01:59:41.140 --> 01:59:43.200
well, Wilfred Owen didn't
come back from the war.

01:59:43.200 --> 01:59:47.320
But people who saw it would
look at the kinds of rah,

01:59:47.320 --> 01:59:52.640
rah war poems comparing it to
soccer or rugby written by people

01:59:52.640 --> 01:59:56.060
like Sir Henry Newbolt and
say, "What the hell is this?"

01:59:56.060 --> 02:00:00.060
and look for some way to register
the shock of that experience.

02:00:00.060 --> 02:00:06.990
We've had since then, you know, I
think another event that was bad

02:00:06.990 --> 02:00:11.350
for the faith of rhetoric was the
Vietnam War because of the kinds

02:00:11.350 --> 02:00:16.830
of very calculate uses of
language to manipulate the public

02:00:16.830 --> 02:00:19.140
that were used at that time.

02:00:19.140 --> 02:00:24.480
So you know, it's interesting
to me to see a society

02:00:24.480 --> 02:00:28.670
that somehow has come from a
different history where all

02:00:28.670 --> 02:00:31.550
of these inhibitions
against rhetoric and flourish

02:00:31.550 --> 02:00:34.860 position:56%
and bravado are not so much in place

02:00:34.860 --> 02:00:37.460
and it produces a different
kind of art.

02:00:37.460 --> 02:00:41.300
In closing, just a couple of
reflections about the slams

02:00:41.300 --> 02:00:43.840
in relation to what
I saw last night.

02:00:43.840 --> 02:00:47.490
What I liked about the slams
was the kind of possibility

02:00:47.490 --> 02:00:51.500
of openness and spontaneity.

02:00:51.500 --> 02:00:54.990 position:56%
Although in fact, many things are
heavily choreographed and rehearsed,

02:00:54.990 --> 02:00:58.840
you don't see too much of that
but potentially, it can be that.

02:00:58.840 --> 02:01:06.260
And the idea of coming not to some
kind of sanctimonious location

02:01:06.260 --> 02:01:10.500 position:56%
but to a bar, you know, it could be
a little bit more like an Irish pub,

02:01:10.500 --> 02:01:13.530
it would be better yet but
it's, you know, it's a bar.

02:01:13.530 --> 02:01:14.860
You're sitting in there in a bar.

02:01:14.860 --> 02:01:19.040
People are reading poetry and
if you like it, you can show it

02:01:19.040 --> 02:01:20.890
and if you don't like
it, you can show it.

02:01:20.890 --> 02:01:22.910
And that's nice.

02:01:22.910 --> 02:01:25.720
What I don't like, two things.

02:01:25.720 --> 02:01:28.630
The competitive aspect,
you know the aspect

02:01:28.630 --> 02:01:31.800
of it that's a little
too much like wrestling

02:01:31.800 --> 02:01:36.410
or professional sports
of other sorts.

02:01:36.410 --> 02:01:40.190
Blake said, "Among true poets,
there is no competition."

02:01:40.190 --> 02:01:43.650
And the speed of judgment,
that is on --

02:01:43.650 --> 02:01:48.270
here's a poem, what do you think?

02:01:48.270 --> 02:01:49.940
Clap, don't clap.

02:01:49.940 --> 02:01:52.220
If you're bored, go like this.

02:01:52.220 --> 02:01:57.110 position:56%
You know, it doesn't -- it says in
essence and this is the relationship

02:01:57.110 --> 02:01:59.890
to the poetry of self-flattery,

02:01:59.890 --> 02:02:03.100
I am the all competent
judge of this poem.

02:02:03.100 --> 02:02:04.540
I already know who I am.

02:02:04.540 --> 02:02:06.590
I already know what I want.

02:02:06.590 --> 02:02:10.040
This poem has nothing to tell
me that I don't already know.

02:02:10.040 --> 02:02:11.340
That I don't like.

02:02:11.340 --> 02:02:16.540
And it struck me in the
extraordinarily powerful videos

02:02:16.540 --> 02:02:17.840
of people from all walks

02:02:17.840 --> 02:02:21.330
of life presenting their
favorite poems last night,

02:02:21.330 --> 02:02:22.820
that they don't think like that.

02:02:22.820 --> 02:02:25.520
The construction worker who
loved <i>Song of Myself </i>said,

02:02:25.520 --> 02:02:27.820
"When I first read this, it
didn't make any sense to me.

02:02:27.820 --> 02:02:31.520
I couldn't follow it but
something caught my attention."

02:02:31.520 --> 02:02:35.660
And Whitman himself when he says,
"Failing to fetch me one place,

02:02:35.660 --> 02:02:38.530
you'll find me in another,
you know, keep encouraged."

02:02:38.530 --> 02:02:41.330
He says, "That seemed to be
directing me how to be patient

02:02:41.330 --> 02:02:43.800
with the poem, how to get it."

02:02:43.800 --> 02:02:47.890
The Jamaican immigrant
who loved <i>Nick</i>

02:02:47.890 --> 02:02:50.660
<i>and the Candlestick</i>
by Sylvia Platt says,

02:02:50.660 --> 02:02:53.200
