with it for a while.

02:03:09.680 --> 02:03:12.540
And that's what I think we're in
danger of being too impatient with.

02:03:12.540 --> 02:03:19.240
The poetry slam has too much in
common, I fear, with the rock video

02:03:19.240 --> 02:03:23.280
and with other sort of
short attention span forms.

02:03:23.280 --> 02:03:26.400
That's one problem with it.

02:03:26.400 --> 02:03:30.680
The other thing I noticed
last night was

02:03:30.680 --> 02:03:33.830
that there isn't the
ferociously anti-intellectual

02:03:33.830 --> 02:03:37.110
and anti-academic bias in most
of the respondents we heard

02:03:37.110 --> 02:03:41.310
from last night that seems to
be a kind of stock attitude

02:03:41.310 --> 02:03:42.610
which you must affect whether

02:03:42.610 --> 02:03:46.150
or not you actually
believe it or not at a slam.

02:03:46.150 --> 02:03:49.290
In other words, the
professor isn't the enemy.

02:03:49.290 --> 02:03:51.360
A lot of these people
said, "I first ran

02:03:51.360 --> 02:03:54.830
into this poem when
I went to school."

02:03:54.830 --> 02:03:59.110
I have the impression that
people come to poetry later

02:03:59.110 --> 02:04:04.250
than they did instead of being
read it by their parent's maybe

02:04:04.250 --> 02:04:06.800
or being made to memorize
it and recite it

02:04:06.800 --> 02:04:09.160
in grade school or in church.

02:04:09.160 --> 02:04:12.450
It's kind of terra incognito
until they get into college.

02:04:12.450 --> 02:04:15.730
And college is a kind of
door into this other thing.

02:04:15.730 --> 02:04:19.290
And some of these respondents
seemed very grateful for that.

02:04:19.290 --> 02:04:23.170
So while I don't want to
whitewash the literary academy

02:04:23.170 --> 02:04:27.040
and I'm well aware of its follies
and failings and my own sins

02:04:27.040 --> 02:04:32.250
in that regard, I think
it's refreshing to see

02:04:32.250 --> 02:04:37.440
that people don't necessarily have
this kind of stereotypical academic

02:04:37.440 --> 02:04:41.020
versus free spirit
notion of what poetry is.

02:04:41.020 --> 02:04:45.450
And I think the universities and
colleges are one of the places

02:04:45.450 --> 02:04:48.700
where poetry survives, where
people learn when they're young

02:04:48.700 --> 02:04:51.510
that they still want it for
the rest of their lives.

