more brilliant poems along

03:58:42.070 --> 03:58:46.040
with many others that are merely
competent, though it is rare

03:58:46.040 --> 03:58:49.980
to find many bad poems
in the better magazines.

03:58:49.980 --> 03:58:52.720
Of course, what seems
merely competent

03:58:52.720 --> 03:58:57.340
to one editor may seem considerably
better than that to another.

03:58:57.340 --> 03:59:00.060
But I would contend
that the proliferation

03:59:00.060 --> 03:59:04.400
of write-in programs all across
the country has raised the level

03:59:04.400 --> 03:59:08.590
of poetry generally so that the
average submission takes rather

03:59:08.590 --> 03:59:14.460
longer to reject than was
the case 25 or 30 years ago.

03:59:14.460 --> 03:59:17.730
I started 35 years ago,
so I've actually been able

03:59:17.730 --> 03:59:20.230
to watch this for some time.

03:59:20.230 --> 03:59:24.010
Writing programs cannot
make great poets,

03:59:24.010 --> 03:59:29.240 position:56%
but they can often help hard-working
poets to become serious writers

03:59:29.240 --> 03:59:33.160
who will produce creditable work.

03:59:33.160 --> 03:59:38.110
Number 10, the poetry scene
is diverse in ways that seem

03:59:38.110 --> 03:59:40.670
to most of us very healthy.

03:59:40.670 --> 03:59:45.520
At this moment no one school
dominates the leading magazines

03:59:45.520 --> 03:59:50.420
which rarely follow a predictable
party line in their selections

03:59:50.420 --> 03:59:54.090
so that the followers
of Ashbury and Bishop

03:59:54.090 --> 03:59:58.060
and Plath are not much better
represented than the followers

03:59:58.060 --> 04:00:02.340
of Adrienne Rich or C.K.
Williams or Louise Gluck.

04:00:02.340 --> 04:00:06.800
Adams Zagajewski, the Polish poet,
recently argued in an article

04:00:06.800 --> 04:00:11.190
in the <i>New Republic </i>that most
of the poetry out there is tepid,

04:00:11.190 --> 04:00:17.720 position:56%
ironic, and conversational, and has
no interest in high or final things.

04:00:17.720 --> 04:00:21.980
But I have a hard time applying
those derisory epithets to much

04:00:21.980 --> 04:00:26.080
of the work that I see in the
Salmagundi offices though,

04:00:26.080 --> 04:00:30.380
of course, tepid ironies
are always plentiful.

04:00:30.380 --> 04:00:35.830
Eleven, last one, so few
magazines any longer print

04:00:35.830 --> 04:00:41.370
or commission serious reviews of
poetry that most poets have ceased

04:00:41.370 --> 04:00:47.250 position:56%
to write them or, except where their
own work is concerned, to miss them.

04:00:47.250 --> 04:00:52.940
And, of course, even poets inclined
to regret the absence of steady,

04:00:52.940 --> 04:00:55.010
bracing criticism coming

04:00:55.010 --> 04:00:59.700
from first-rate poet critics
can easily console themselves

04:00:59.700 --> 04:01:02.400
for the loss by simply intoning --

04:01:02.400 --> 04:01:05.170
once or twice each
afternoon should be enough --

04:01:05.170 --> 04:01:09.020
the words "William
Logan," and giving thanks

04:01:09.020 --> 04:01:12.030
for William Logan's decision,
at least for the moment,

04:01:12.030 --> 04:01:16.840
not to offer a scathing
review of their latest work.

04:01:17.950 --> 04:01:19.930
That's Part One.

04:01:19.930 --> 04:01:23.030
Part Two is somewhat briefer.

04:01:23.030 --> 04:01:29.160
These are responses to questions
put to me on a phone by Mr. Cole.

04:01:29.160 --> 04:01:31.850
I'll tackle them in
very summary fashion.

04:01:31.850 --> 04:01:35.080
One, who writes poetry?

04:01:35.080 --> 04:01:38.290
Answer, just about anybody.

04:01:38.290 --> 04:01:41.300
And to judge from the
manuscripts coming

04:01:41.300 --> 04:01:45.450
into our little magazine
mailbox five days each week,

04:01:45.450 --> 04:01:47.270
just about everybody.

04:01:47.270 --> 04:01:53.600
At the Summer Writers Institute
I direct each summer our Poetry

04:01:53.600 --> 04:01:57.390
Workshops are filled with
people, some of whom live

04:01:57.390 --> 04:02:02.120
and breathe poetry, but also
with many others who are doctors,

04:02:02.120 --> 04:02:07.680
lawyers, musicians, businessmen,
social workers, and so on.

04:02:07.680 --> 04:02:10.820
Question Two, who certifies
for those

04:02:10.820 --> 04:02:15.060
who write poetry that
they are poets?

04:02:15.060 --> 04:02:18.820
This is hard to answer,
and no doubt most of those

04:02:18.820 --> 04:02:22.630
who write poetry just
know what they're doing

04:02:22.630 --> 04:02:27.430
and need no reassurance about
who they are when they write.

04:02:27.430 --> 04:02:31.350
Others less confident
will require, I suppose,

04:02:31.350 --> 04:02:36.390 position:56%
confirmation from some external
source, often an encouraging mentor,

04:02:36.390 --> 04:02:40.790
sometimes an encouraging
magazine editor willing

04:02:40.790 --> 04:02:42.850
to publish their work, and thereby

04:02:42.850 --> 04:02:47.590
to confer upon them I guess
what we call an identity.

04:02:47.590 --> 04:02:50.570
Whatever the means, many
people apparently believe

04:02:50.570 --> 04:02:55.490
that writing poetry confers upon
their lives some meaning or dignity

04:02:55.490 --> 04:02:58.610
or shape that is highly desirable.

04:02:58.610 --> 04:03:00.350
And I don't blame them.

04:03:00.350 --> 04:03:02.180
Three, last question.

04:03:02.180 --> 04:03:07.240
What is the poetry scene
today or what is it like?

04:03:07.240 --> 04:03:09.400
I've already indicated in Part One

04:03:09.400 --> 04:03:11.670
of this very brief
talk what the scene is

04:03:11.670 --> 04:03:17.210
like from the peculiar perspective
of a long-time magazine editor.

04:03:17.210 --> 04:03:20.500
But I'll add that the
scene can claim many,

04:03:20.500 --> 04:03:26.720 position:56%
many excellent poets whose work
appears in so many different places,

04:03:26.720 --> 04:03:31.440 position:56%
from so many different presses, that
it is no longer possible to suppose

04:03:31.440 --> 04:03:35.520
that only the commercial presses or
the national magazines will bring

04:03:35.520 --> 04:03:38.250
out really distinguished work,

04:03:38.250 --> 04:03:43.030
though things out there can seem
dark or difficult especially

04:03:43.030 --> 04:03:47.940
for poets trying to break into
print at the better magazines.

04:03:47.940 --> 04:03:51.420
There are many editors around
who are more than eager

04:03:51.420 --> 04:03:54.840
to discover new talent
and to promote it

04:03:54.840 --> 04:03:58.850
in the modest ways
available to most of them.

04:03:58.850 --> 04:04:04.450
Yes, the scene is crowded
with many voices, so many,

04:04:04.450 --> 04:04:09.330 position:56%
that it is impossible for most of us
to attend even to a small fraction

04:04:09.330 --> 04:04:14.160
of those many voices and, yes,
most of us will be very fortunate

04:04:14.160 --> 04:04:19.400
if we can find the time to love
and to master the new books coming

04:04:19.400 --> 04:04:24.020
out by Robert Pinsky or Louise
Gluck, or Seamus Heaney.

04:04:24.020 --> 04:04:32.300 position:56%
But some of us will continue to make
time for the grayer frailer voice

04:04:32.300 --> 04:04:36.750
of a poet like Carl Dennis,
the mordancies of a young poet

04:04:36.750 --> 04:04:41.050
like Danial Levin, or
the orchestral resonances

04:04:41.050 --> 04:04:46.110
of a strange anachronistic
poet named Herbert Morris.

04:04:46.110 --> 04:04:51.780
None of these three, with titles
presently available at Kramer Books

04:04:51.780 --> 04:04:56.120
or Politics and Prose where I
investigated the local scene

04:04:56.120 --> 04:05:01.420
on Monday morning, and did so
with those three names of persons

04:05:01.420 --> 04:05:04.740
with recent books in
print were not to be found

04:05:04.740 --> 04:05:09.800
in the rather nicely
stocked poetry sections.

04:05:09.800 --> 04:05:15.790
In short, though there is too
much poetry out there to take in,

04:05:15.790 --> 04:05:20.090
we can see that much of it
is admirable and compelling,

04:05:20.090 --> 04:05:24.480
sometimes even thrilling
or austerely beautiful.

04:05:24.480 --> 04:05:28.910
And though there is always reason
to complain about look-alikes

04:05:28.910 --> 04:05:33.330
and sound-alikes in the graduate
writing programs about the thinness

04:05:33.330 --> 04:05:38.050
of air and idea in many of
the well-made poems churned

04:05:38.050 --> 04:05:41.130
out in major MFA programs,

04:05:41.130 --> 04:05:45.600
we have only to remember how
much really good work there is

04:05:45.600 --> 04:05:48.860
that we haven't the time to master

04:05:48.860 --> 04:05:54.020 position:56%
and how consistently our best poets
have struggled to exceed themselves.

04:05:54.020 --> 04:05:59.670
We don't live in an age of
poetry, but we have more than two

04:05:59.670 --> 04:06:04.700
or three handfuls of poets
whose work may well be read

04:06:04.700 --> 04:06:08.450
and loved long after we are gone.

04:06:08.450 --> 04:06:10.250
Thank you.

04:06:10.250 --> 04:06:16.850
[ Applause ]

04:06:16.850 --> 04:06:21.290
&gt;&gt; Jerry W. Ward: I'd like
to thank Robert Pinsky,

04:06:21.290 --> 04:06:25.240
the Center for the Book,
and the Library of Congress,

04:06:25.240 --> 04:06:29.310 position:56%
and everyone else who was
responsible for having me come here.

04:06:29.310 --> 04:06:34.060
I must tell tales out of school.

04:06:34.060 --> 04:06:39.920
Last spring, Robert
Pinsky was in Mississippi,

04:06:39.920 --> 04:06:43.230
and we met for the first time.

04:06:43.230 --> 04:06:49.530
And I think we enjoyed the
meeting despite our disagreement

04:06:49.530 --> 04:06:52.260
about a few things.

04:06:52.260 --> 04:06:57.830
And most of my discussion today
is based upon that disagreement,

04:06:57.830 --> 04:07:02.540
which is a friendly one,
about the use of the Internet.

04:07:02.540 --> 04:07:05.270
So I decided that maybe
I ought to talk to you

04:07:05.270 --> 04:07:14.420
about my antiquated beliefs that
poetry still loves the page more

04:07:14.420 --> 04:07:21.910
than the screen or, as a kind
of subtitle for my remarks,

04:07:21.910 --> 04:07:26.540
it's what you have to say when
you ain't no spring chicken,

04:07:26.540 --> 04:07:34.150
as my poet friend [inaudible]
whom I was very pleased to publish

04:07:34.150 --> 04:07:40.620
in <i>Troubled Waters </i>said, and
having been here for the videos

04:07:40.620 --> 04:07:42.810
and having watched
the audience today

04:07:42.810 --> 04:07:49.980
and the way people are responding,
I just felt moved to read this.

04:07:49.980 --> 04:07:55.790
"I am as old as sin,
quiet as it's kept.

04:07:55.790 --> 04:08:01.880
As ancient as an exorcism
from paradise.

04:08:01.880 --> 04:08:08.830
I used to swing by my feet, make
a dance out of trees catching me.

04:08:08.830 --> 04:08:10.360
I used to stand on my hands

04:08:10.360 --> 04:08:15.660
and throw huge rocks
with the bow of my legs.

04:08:15.660 --> 04:08:20.350
I used to outrun daylight home
to a woman dressed in nightfall,

04:08:20.350 --> 04:08:24.840
older than the blues, older than
the grace of sitting years later

04:08:24.840 --> 04:08:29.470
on the porch of a rocking
chair poem.

04:08:29.470 --> 04:08:34.860
I used to turn my eyes
inside-out and cure a headache

04:08:34.860 --> 04:08:42.130
in a time before color 3D TV, in a
time before footprints on the moon,

04:08:42.130 --> 04:08:45.690
in a time before the wheel.

04:08:46.900 --> 04:08:54.130
Let me tell you of a time long
before Lucifer when the sky

04:08:54.130 --> 04:09:02.920
and the sea were the same, when
we could swim to the stars.

04:09:02.920 --> 04:09:06.900
I am slow dragging against
the walls of a cave,

04:09:06.900 --> 04:09:10.320
combing the wind with my hair.

04:09:10.320 --> 04:09:16.430
I wear a rainbow as my diaper
and a feather in my ear.

04:09:16.430 --> 04:09:19.720
I am tapdancing majestic waves,

04:09:19.720 --> 04:09:24.650
surfing for the rocky ground
where the tribe waits.

04:09:24.650 --> 04:09:28.800
They throw chains out to fetch me,

04:09:28.800 --> 04:09:33.610
pulling me in like old
age with open arms.

04:09:33.610 --> 04:09:40.200
They bite and growl a
song which welcomes me.

04:09:40.200 --> 04:09:48.690
Even then there was more to
the world than meets the eye."

04:09:49.890 --> 04:09:54.390
That's about the way I feel when
I talk about what's happening

04:09:54.390 --> 04:09:59.850
to poetry now, because no doubt
I belong to some ancient tribe

04:09:59.850 --> 04:10:07.760
of scriveners who were very much
put out when the craft they loved

04:10:07.760 --> 04:10:13.190
and the livelihood they depended
upon was undeniably diminished

04:10:13.190 --> 04:10:16.280
by the triumph of printing.

04:10:16.280 --> 04:10:21.470 position:56%
As a writer who has moved from
pencil and what we in the South used

04:10:21.470 --> 04:10:28.880
to call cornbread paper to pencil
and nice paper, through the manual

04:10:28.880 --> 04:10:34.740
and electric versions of the
typewriter, to a now shameless use

04:10:34.740 --> 04:10:41.500 position:56%
of the computer as a word processor,
I must admit that I have a kind

04:10:41.500 --> 04:10:47.830
of residual kinship with those
ancient makers of manuscripts.

04:10:47.830 --> 04:10:52.800
No, I do not want to return
to the use of pen and ink

04:10:52.800 --> 04:10:55.460
as a habitual mode of writing.

04:10:55.460 --> 04:10:57.930
My hand would cramp.

04:10:57.930 --> 04:11:01.130
But at certain stages
in composition,

04:11:01.130 --> 04:11:04.170
particularly when I
am writing poems,

04:11:04.170 --> 04:11:07.760
I must have the evolving
product on the page

04:11:07.760 --> 04:11:10.710
and not on the computer screen.

04:11:10.710 --> 04:11:14.970
I must have the paper in hand.

04:11:14.970 --> 04:11:21.530
The screen does not permit me to
touch the word as the page does.

04:11:21.530 --> 04:11:26.440
And as I remarked yesterday
after looking at the collection

04:11:26.440 --> 04:11:31.750
of treasures in a new exhibit
in the Jefferson Building,

04:11:31.750 --> 04:11:38.360
unless there was a paper there with
ancient printing on it I don't know

04:11:38.360 --> 04:11:45.550
that that particular magic
moment would happen for me.

04:11:45.550 --> 04:11:50.370
So in my creative projects
and in my creative responses,

04:11:50.370 --> 04:11:53.330
poetry still loves the page.

04:11:53.330 --> 04:11:56.020
And as a reader of poems,
I still want the look

04:11:56.020 --> 04:11:58.520
and feel of the printed page.

04:11:58.520 --> 04:12:02.360
My brain is not hardwired
in the intellectual

04:12:02.360 --> 04:12:06.340
and aesthetic acts it performs
for the e-book or the Palm book

04:12:06.340 --> 04:12:11.480
or whatever it's called, and
any other extremes in the future

04:12:11.480 --> 04:12:15.840
to which we will wind up as we
explore the full possibilities

04:12:15.840 --> 04:12:18.340
of hypertextuality.

04:12:18.340 --> 04:12:22.090 position:56%
By sheer habit I respond more warmly

04:12:22.090 --> 04:12:25.290
to <i>Dover Beach </i>in
a printed anthology

04:12:25.290 --> 04:12:29.250
than to the most handsome
presentation the electronic village

04:12:29.250 --> 04:12:31.770
at the University of Virginia
might be able to make.

04:12:31.770 --> 04:12:41.160
In 1992, Robert Coover wrote
a rather starting piece

04:12:41.160 --> 04:12:46.450
for the <i>New York Times</i>
called "The End of the Book."

04:12:46.450 --> 04:12:50.950
And I think what he had to
say is to be taken seriously.

04:12:50.950 --> 04:13:00.240
He contended -- or at least I
suppose he partially contended --

04:13:00.240 --> 04:13:05.200
that poets and publishers
cannot behave

04:13:05.200 --> 04:13:09.640
as if the electronic has not
changed how we communicate,

04:13:09.640 --> 04:13:14.850
conduct our daily affairs, enjoy
or suffer a quality of life.

04:13:14.850 --> 04:13:17.060
Indeed the revolution is well

04:13:17.060 --> 04:13:19.720
on the road toward changing
the cognitive functioning

04:13:19.720 --> 04:13:21.290
of the human brain.

04:13:21.290 --> 04:13:27.360 position:56%
We can't ignore either the unsettled
questions regarding intellectual

04:13:27.360 --> 04:13:32.030
property, copyright, and
something I learned recently

04:13:32.030 --> 04:13:39.010
which is called copyleft which
pertains only to the computer.

04:13:39.010 --> 04:13:42.570
Other entitlements
and most especially

04:13:42.570 --> 04:13:46.750
as the Authors Guild reminds
me, I have to be concerned

04:13:46.750 --> 04:13:51.440
about the recovery of
royalties from various misuses.

04:13:51.440 --> 04:13:54.870 position:56%
Writing from the vantage of fiction,

04:13:54.870 --> 04:13:58.420
Robert Coover really
humorously remarked,

04:13:58.420 --> 04:14:01.430
"You will often hear it said
that the print medium is a doomed

04:14:01.430 --> 04:14:04.420
and outdated technology,
a mere curiosity

04:14:04.420 --> 04:14:10.220 position:56%
of bygone days just [inaudible] to
be consigned forever to those dusty,

04:14:10.220 --> 04:14:16.930
unattended museums we
now call libraries.

04:14:16.930 --> 04:14:19.540
Indeed. The very proliferation
of books

04:14:19.540 --> 04:14:23.190
and other print-based media
is held to be a signal

04:14:23.190 --> 04:14:28.330
of its feverish moribundity,
the last futile grasp

04:14:28.330 --> 04:14:35.590
of a once vital form before it
finally passes away forever,

04:14:35.590 --> 04:14:37.340
dead as God."

04:14:37.340 --> 04:14:41.670
That's the end of Coover's
quotation.

04:14:41.670 --> 04:14:45.880
Coover has willing to face
the new world by experimenting

04:14:45.880 --> 04:14:50.690
with hyperspace at Brown University
in the creation of narrative

04:14:50.690 --> 04:14:54.580
that would free a writer
from the tyranny of the line.

04:14:54.580 --> 04:14:58.640
As he said, "Hypertext
reader and writer are said

04:14:58.640 --> 04:15:03.490
to become co-learners or co-writers
as it were, fellow travelers

04:15:03.490 --> 04:15:08.020
in the mapping and remapping
of textual and visual kinetic

04:15:08.020 --> 04:15:12.670
and aural components, all of
which are provided by what used

04:15:12.670 --> 04:15:17.210
to be called the author," unquote.

04:15:17.210 --> 04:15:19.050
The number of fiction
writers willing

04:15:19.050 --> 04:15:23.230
to go the whole nine yards
with hypertext is small.

04:15:23.230 --> 04:15:26.570
To my knowledge, the number
of poets willing to do

04:15:26.570 --> 04:15:30.890
so would be absolutely miniscule.

04:15:30.890 --> 04:15:35.000
We -- or at least I can
speak only for myself --

04:15:35.000 --> 04:15:41.360
we are reluctant to have co-poets
tamper with out creations except

04:15:41.360 --> 04:15:46.690
in workshops or by way of
private feedback solicited

04:15:46.690 --> 04:15:50.740 position:56%
from other writers or kindred souls.

04:15:50.740 --> 04:15:53.310
Such poems as are published
at various sites

04:15:53.310 --> 04:15:58.150
on the World Wide Web are
more or less imitations

04:15:58.150 --> 04:16:01.080
of what one finds on paper.

04:16:01.080 --> 04:16:06.580
And it is disappointing to me that
you can't even write marginal notes

04:16:06.580 --> 04:16:09.420
on the Web-published poem.

04:16:09.420 --> 04:16:14.260
It is probably pleasing
to the publishers

04:16:14.260 --> 04:16:18.830
of the amazingly popular
new translation

04:16:18.830 --> 04:16:23.330
of <i>Beowulf </i>that Seamus
Heaney did not opt

04:16:23.330 --> 04:16:27.120
to sell it by way of the Web.

04:16:27.120 --> 04:16:33.490
That book is selling well according
to the <i>New York Times </i>of 29 March.

04:16:33.490 --> 04:16:40.560
But maybe another edition of his
translation will include a CD

04:16:40.560 --> 04:16:45.850
or of him reading or of some
well-spoken print reading at --

04:16:45.850 --> 04:16:53.380
which will return it to its
natural context as poetry.

04:16:53.380 --> 04:16:54.930
The sales of this new version

04:16:54.930 --> 04:17:01.910 position:56%
of an old epic is probably one small
indicator that the book is not dead,

04:17:01.910 --> 04:17:06.450
the text lives, and will
live in new transformations.

04:17:06.450 --> 04:17:12.240
I do not think that we need
to do a hatchet job on poetry

04:17:12.240 --> 04:17:15.020 position:56%
and new technologies of publication.

04:17:15.020 --> 04:17:19.100
There is something to be
said about the positive good

04:17:19.100 --> 04:17:24.610
of getting people interested in
poetry by way of the Internet.

04:17:24.610 --> 04:17:28.300 position:56%
Robert Pinsky's project is probably,

04:17:28.300 --> 04:17:37.010
especially after last night's
cybercast, a very fine example

04:17:37.010 --> 04:17:42.760
of how you can use the Net to
reach a democratic audience.

04:17:42.760 --> 04:17:50.870
I think there's something very good
to be said about this because some

04:17:50.870 --> 04:17:55.570
of those materials will find
their way to the joys of print.

04:17:55.570 --> 04:18:01.000
Some of the people who find
things on the Net will again learn

04:18:01.000 --> 04:18:07.980
to enjoy the heft of a book in
hand and the turning of pages,

04:18:07.980 --> 04:18:10.770
rather than the clicking of mice.

04:18:10.770 --> 04:18:17.880
And I have to ask learned people
here, is the plural of mouse used

04:18:17.880 --> 04:18:24.710
as a computer instrument
"mice" or "mouses?"

04:18:24.710 --> 04:18:29.690
I really don't know, but I
would like an answer, please.

04:18:29.690 --> 04:18:35.920
The act of reading encourages
then a very active participation

04:18:35.920 --> 04:18:37.750
in one's literacy.

04:18:37.750 --> 04:18:41.620
The reading of a poem, as those
wonderful videos have shown us,

04:18:41.620 --> 04:18:46.360
shows that there is a very
active use of the voice,

04:18:46.360 --> 04:18:50.720
but also of various powers
of imagination in figuring

04:18:50.720 --> 04:18:55.460
out the meanings that emerge
from that kind of encounter

04:18:55.460 --> 04:18:58.760
which are quite different
and perhaps more blessed

04:18:58.760 --> 04:19:02.910
than the meanings that
ever occur in my classroom.

04:19:02.910 --> 04:19:06.610
For academic purposes I do not
object to preparing the text

04:19:06.610 --> 04:19:13.210
of poems so that students can
have access to links for now

04:19:13.210 --> 04:19:16.710
that can do what footnotes
and glosses

04:19:16.710 --> 04:19:19.450
in the old technology used to do.

04:19:19.450 --> 04:19:23.380
On the other hand, as a
teacher I always warn students

04:19:23.380 --> 04:19:25.160
about the dangers of thinking

04:19:25.160 --> 04:19:28.740
that somehow it's all
there in hyperspace.

04:19:28.740 --> 04:19:30.440
No, it is not.

04:19:30.440 --> 04:19:35.500
There is so much in the library in
print that awaits our discovery.

04:19:35.500 --> 04:19:41.960
The epiphany for me yesterday was,
my God, I'm over half a century old

04:19:41.960 --> 04:19:47.910
and I could spend another century
reading in the Library of Congress.

04:19:50.370 --> 04:19:59.320 position:56%
No, this new enthusiasm and wonder
for what a well-chosen configuration

04:19:59.320 --> 04:20:02.670
of words might contain
has this possibility

04:20:02.670 --> 04:20:06.250
of springing forth even
in the new technology.

04:20:06.250 --> 04:20:10.030
And the Library of Congress
website has done much

04:20:10.030 --> 04:20:15.040
to disseminate the possibilities
to hundreds of thousands

04:20:15.040 --> 04:20:19.540
of Americans who got there online.

04:20:20.840 --> 04:20:24.310
No doubt in the future things
will be very different.

04:20:24.310 --> 04:20:27.450
Surely there will be fewer
of us around to carry

04:20:27.450 --> 04:20:35.030
on a long-term love affair with the
poem manifested on paper in ink.

04:20:35.030 --> 04:20:41.970
Perhaps some century hence poets
will alienate their individuality

04:20:41.970 --> 04:20:44.970
for the good of the
commonwealth of poetry.

04:20:44.970 --> 04:20:50.530
Perhaps e-Lit-zines web-located
literary magazines will be all too

04:20:50.530 --> 04:20:56.000
commonplace and people will fashion
anthologies from electronic poems

04:20:56.000 --> 04:20:59.360
with real audio readings.

04:20:59.360 --> 04:21:04.350
Neither poets nor publishers can
stop the revolution involving the

04:21:04.350 --> 04:21:07.320
new management of boundless
centerless space

04:21:07.320 --> 04:21:13.680
and unlocked time or,
perhaps, unclocked time.

04:21:13.680 --> 04:21:19.050
But any conclusion that
poetry on the Internet is more

04:21:19.050 --> 04:21:23.570
than an interesting and
emerging set of possibilities is,

04:21:23.570 --> 04:21:30.080
as was the announcement about
Truman losing to Dewey, premature.

04:21:30.080 --> 04:21:36.510
The page still simply
loves the poem.

04:21:36.510 --> 04:21:45.600
[ Applause ]

04:21:45.600 --> 04:21:46.900
&gt;&gt; John Y. Cole: Thank you, Jerry.

04:21:46.900 --> 04:21:49.350
Our next speaker is Leslie Morris

04:21:49.350 --> 04:21:52.580
who will present another
perspective.

04:21:54.460 --> 04:21:55.760
Leslie.

04:21:55.760 --> 04:21:58.280
&gt;&gt; Leslie Morris: I should
probably begin by saying

04:21:58.280 --> 04:22:00.410
that I'm not a publisher.

04:22:00.410 --> 04:22:03.370
So I feel a little bit out
of place on this panel.

04:22:03.370 --> 04:22:07.730 position:56%
I'm an archivist and what I'm
interested in is what the publishers

04:22:07.730 --> 04:22:10.090
and the poets leave behind.

04:22:10.090 --> 04:22:14.620
And what I'm talking about
primarily today is my experience

04:22:14.620 --> 04:22:17.710
as an archivist with one
particular publisher,

04:22:17.710 --> 04:22:21.520
and that was New Directions
Publishing Company.

04:22:21.520 --> 04:22:25.160
The outline of the story
of James Lockland IV

04:22:25.160 --> 04:22:27.930
and his New Directions
Publishing Corporation is familiar

04:22:27.930 --> 04:22:31.050
to anyone interested
in 20th century poets.

04:22:31.050 --> 04:22:34.970
So I will only recap it
briefly here to set the scene.

04:22:34.970 --> 04:22:39.080 position:56%
Jay, as he was usually known, became
a publisher because he was told

04:22:39.080 --> 04:22:41.130
to become one by Ezra Pound.

04:22:41.130 --> 04:22:44.770
He had sought out Pound in
Italy, taking leave from Harvard

04:22:44.770 --> 04:22:49.020
in his sophomore year to
attend Pound's Ezuversity,

04:22:49.020 --> 04:22:51.950 position:56%
hoping in this way to become a poet.

04:22:51.950 --> 04:22:55.740
After several months with Pound,
Pound finally said to him,

04:22:55.740 --> 04:22:59.790
and I quote from Jay's
reminiscences of Pound here.

04:22:59.790 --> 04:23:01.560
"No, Jazz, it's hopeless.

04:23:01.560 --> 04:23:03.380 position:56%
You're never going to make a writer.

04:23:03.380 --> 04:23:06.520
No matter how hard you
try, you'll never make it.

04:23:06.520 --> 04:23:09.560
Go back to America and
do something useful.

04:23:09.560 --> 04:23:11.560
Go back and be a publisher.

04:23:11.560 --> 04:23:14.350
If you're a good boy your
parents will give you some money

04:23:14.350 --> 04:23:15.920
and you can bring out books.

04:23:15.920 --> 04:23:17.630
I'll get all my friends
to send you stuff."

04:23:17.630 --> 04:23:20.040
[ Laughter ]

04:23:20.040 --> 04:23:23.130
Lockland's family owned the
Pittsburgh steel company Jones

04:23:23.130 --> 04:23:27.220
and Lockland and Jay did not really
need to work to support himself.

04:23:27.220 --> 04:23:30.290
But following Pound's advice
he returned to Harvard

04:23:30.290 --> 04:23:33.770
and in 1936 while still
a student brought

04:23:33.770 --> 04:23:37.240
out his first New Directions book.

04:23:37.240 --> 04:23:40.780
Almost half of the titles that
New Directions has published have

04:23:40.780 --> 04:23:42.230
been poetry.

04:23:42.230 --> 04:23:45.010
Many poets who are now part
of the accepted mainstream

04:23:45.010 --> 04:23:48.070
of 20th century poetry had
their early work published

04:23:48.070 --> 04:23:51.860
in New Directions, in one of the
firm's annuals, or have been kept

04:23:51.860 --> 04:23:54.020
in print by New Directions,

04:23:54.020 --> 04:23:57.800
when other more commercial
publishers were not interested.

04:23:57.800 --> 04:24:00.340
To name only a few of the poets --

04:24:00.340 --> 04:24:03.910
Ezra Pound and William Carlos
Williams are foremost, of course.

04:24:03.910 --> 04:24:08.090
They are the two pillars upon which
the house of New Directions rests.

04:24:08.090 --> 04:24:11.940
Tennessee Williams, who was a
poet as well as a playwright,

04:24:11.940 --> 04:24:15.500
and New Directions has published
almost all of Williams' work.

04:24:15.500 --> 04:24:19.090
Dylan Thomas, Delmore
Schwartz, Kenneth Patchen,

04:24:19.090 --> 04:24:21.410
Thomas Merton, Lawrence
Ferlinghetti.

04:24:21.410 --> 04:24:26.700
<i>A Coney Island of the Mind </i>was one
of ND's biggest and best sellers.

04:24:26.700 --> 04:24:29.980
Denise Levertov, Elizabeth
Bishop, Gary Snyder,

04:24:29.980 --> 04:24:32.980
and the list could go on and on.

04:24:32.980 --> 04:24:35.950
New Directions was also
extremely important in bringing

04:24:35.950 --> 04:24:39.390
to an American public
translations of foreign writers,

04:24:39.390 --> 04:24:43.950
exposing American poets to the
traditions of French modernism

04:24:43.950 --> 04:24:48.120
such the work of the surrealist
Paul Eluard, and a Spanish

04:24:48.120 --> 04:24:51.990
and Latin American lyric in the
work of Federico Garcia Lorca,

04:24:51.990 --> 04:24:55.960
Pablo Neruda, and Octavio Paz.

04:24:55.960 --> 04:24:59.940 position:56%
When I read off the names of the
poets that New Directions published,

04:24:59.940 --> 04:25:02.930
you might be excused for
thinking that, of course,

04:25:02.930 --> 04:25:05.920
with such a list the firm
must have made some money.

04:25:05.920 --> 04:25:10.670
And, after all, it's still in
business today after 64 years.

04:25:10.670 --> 04:25:13.780
The fact is, however, that the
firm operated in the red for close

04:25:13.780 --> 04:25:18.100
to 40 years until the explosion
of courses in contemporary poetry

04:25:18.100 --> 04:25:22.340
in American universities
in the mid-1970s.

04:25:22.340 --> 04:25:25.820
Only New Directions had the
essential text still in print

04:25:25.820 --> 04:25:29.010
and so, finally, they
began to make profits.

04:25:29.010 --> 04:25:32.610 position:56%
Although often in the years the firm
did make a profit it would not have

04:25:32.610 --> 04:25:35.930
been in the black had its
publisher taken a salary.

04:25:35.930 --> 04:25:39.670
Life, even for successful poetry
publishers, can be marginal

04:25:39.670 --> 04:25:43.110
and it helps greatly to
be independently wealthy.

04:25:44.290 --> 04:25:46.330
Jay Lockland's publishing
philosophy was

04:25:46.330 --> 04:25:48.870
to publish only work that he liked.

04:25:48.870 --> 04:25:51.980
Jay was proud to say that
he'd turned down Rod McKuen

04:25:51.980 --> 04:25:56.340
who sold millions of books
because quote, "It's poetry, sure.

04:25:56.340 --> 04:26:01.170
I admit it's poetry, but it's not
a kind of poetry that I like."

04:26:01.170 --> 04:26:04.550
Because he didn't need to turn a
profit in order to support himself,

04:26:04.550 --> 04:26:09.490
he could, again, in his words,
quote, "do things I wanted to do

04:26:09.490 --> 04:26:10.860
without having to waste a lot

04:26:10.860 --> 04:26:14.220
of time publishing
junk to support them."

04:26:14.220 --> 04:26:16.840
Jay also subscribed
to a belief of Pounds

04:26:16.840 --> 04:26:20.660
that there was almost always
a time lag of 10 to 20 years

04:26:20.660 --> 04:26:23.340 position:56%
until a poet's work was appreciated.

04:26:23.340 --> 04:26:28.380 position:56%
Consequently, New Directions keeps
books in print for a very long time,

04:26:28.380 --> 04:26:30.950
waiting for that period
to end and to be ready

04:26:30.950 --> 04:26:34.510
to sell those books when it does.

04:26:34.510 --> 04:26:37.150
But I'm on this panel today
not simply to tell the story

04:26:37.150 --> 04:26:41.390 position:56%
of New Directions as a case study in
poetry publishing, but to speak also

04:26:41.390 --> 04:26:44.260
in my professional
capacity as an archivist.

04:26:44.260 --> 04:26:47.790
What does the written record left
behind by this company tell one

04:26:47.790 --> 04:26:51.590
about the relationships
between poets and publishers?

04:26:52.790 --> 04:26:55.700
One might expect that the proofs
and other production materials

04:26:55.700 --> 04:26:58.700
for the books of poetry New
Directions published would be

04:26:58.700 --> 04:27:02.140
extremely revealing of how
Jay worked with his authors.

04:27:02.140 --> 04:27:05.060
But, in point of fact, the
proofs tell one very little.

04:27:05.060 --> 04:27:08.570
For the most part Jay did
very little line editing

04:27:08.570 --> 04:27:12.220
for his writers largely because
most of them wouldn't stand for it.

04:27:12.220 --> 04:27:16.000
Can you imagine trying to
edit Pound or Williams?

04:27:16.000 --> 04:27:18.910
Instead, he invested
time and long letters,

04:27:18.910 --> 04:27:22.680
occasionally dispensing advice
or offering a point of view,

04:27:22.680 --> 04:27:25.410
but for the most part
simply being the facilitator

04:27:25.410 --> 04:27:28.000
of their creative work.

04:27:28.000 --> 04:27:32.290
Denise Levertov, a poet whom Jay
published early and often summed it

04:27:32.290 --> 04:27:36.930
up eloquently when she said,
"For over 20 years I have had

04:27:36.930 --> 04:27:40.140
in Jay a publisher who
has consistently affirmed

04:27:40.140 --> 04:27:43.500
and supported my development
through all its changes,

04:27:43.500 --> 04:27:46.690
a friend whose personal
kindness has been practically,

04:27:46.690 --> 04:27:49.150
as well as verbally, expressed.

04:27:49.150 --> 04:27:52.960
And in association with a
fellow poet, consistently fine

04:27:52.960 --> 04:27:58.490
and at the same time modest and
totally unselfserving" The letters

04:27:58.490 --> 04:28:00.450
between poet and publisher

04:28:00.450 --> 04:28:03.950
in the New Directions archive
are quite truly remarkable

04:28:03.950 --> 04:28:07.600
and repeatedly showed the
devotion, kindness, lack of ego,

04:28:07.600 --> 04:28:11.570
and passion for poetry
that Levertov mentions.

04:28:11.570 --> 04:28:14.890
Fortunately, Jay usually
kept carbons of his letters,

04:28:14.890 --> 04:28:20.370
so one can actually sit down and
read both sides of these exchanges.

04:28:20.370 --> 04:28:22.940
I find one of the central
pieces for understanding Jay

04:28:22.940 --> 04:28:24.650
as a publisher an exchange he had

04:28:24.650 --> 04:28:27.850
with William Carlos
Williams in 1937.

04:28:27.850 --> 04:28:29.600
Williams had just published
his novel,

04:28:29.600 --> 04:28:31.350
<i>White Mule </i>with New Directions

04:28:31.350 --> 04:28:35.310
and it had brought him some long
overdue recognition and success.

04:28:35.310 --> 04:28:39.530
But, as do many writers who become
successful with a small publisher,

04:28:39.530 --> 04:28:41.720
he was now thinking of
taking his next book

04:28:41.720 --> 04:28:44.150
to a more commercial publisher.

04:28:44.150 --> 04:28:49.220
Williams wrote to Jay, in part,
"Tentatively, I've been thinking

04:28:49.220 --> 04:28:52.510
that it might be wisest to approach
a regular commercial publisher

04:28:52.510 --> 04:28:55.110
concerning my next
book when it is ready.

04:28:55.110 --> 04:29:00.220 position:56%
Harcourt Brace once smiled at me and
Simon and Schuster grinned broadly.

04:29:00.220 --> 04:29:04.810
I'm just talking along, let it
go in one ear and out the other.

04:29:04.810 --> 04:29:08.300
I won't make a move
without a talk with you."

04:29:08.300 --> 04:29:11.720
Jay thought about this for 10
days and then wrote back --

04:29:11.720 --> 04:29:13.190
and just a reminder, at this point,

04:29:13.190 --> 04:29:17.020
Williams is 54 years old
and Jay is all of 23.

04:29:17.020 --> 04:29:22.030
"Dear Bill, you're thinking
that you want somebody else

04:29:22.030 --> 04:29:24.450
as a crisis in my life.

04:29:24.450 --> 04:29:27.240
I had thought that I was doing
all right in what I had taken

04:29:27.240 --> 04:29:30.680
up in what was probably
to be my lifework and now,

04:29:30.680 --> 04:29:33.510
if you doubt me, I don't know.

04:29:33.510 --> 04:29:35.900
You are the cornerstone
of New Directions,

04:29:35.900 --> 04:29:39.470
and if you left me I think I
wouldn't be able to go on with it.

04:29:39.470 --> 04:29:41.950
I have built my plans around you.

04:29:41.950 --> 04:29:44.990
You are my symbol of everything
that is good in writing,

04:29:44.990 --> 04:29:46.790
and if you go over to the enemy,

04:29:46.790 --> 04:29:49.510
I just don't know where
the hell I'm at.

04:29:49.510 --> 04:29:52.080
[ Laughter ]

04:29:52.080 --> 04:29:54.590
"Would they take the mule?

04:29:54.590 --> 04:29:57.160
Now that you have made
a success they want you.

04:29:57.160 --> 04:30:00.090
They think they can exploit you.

04:30:00.090 --> 04:30:01.550
"It isn't a case of publishers.

04:30:01.550 --> 04:30:04.970
It's a case of life and
death, or right and wrong,

04:30:04.970 --> 04:30:08.510
of good writers starving and
lousy writers going to Palm Beach.

04:30:08.510 --> 04:30:11.060
[ Laughter ]

04:30:11.060 --> 04:30:13.290
"Of course, I see the other side.

04:30:13.290 --> 04:30:14.950
I see that you need money.

04:30:14.950 --> 04:30:16.250
Well, if you will trust me

04:30:16.250 --> 04:30:18.980
for a little while I'll
see that you get that.

04:30:18.980 --> 04:30:21.060
You are different from their trade.

04:30:21.060 --> 04:30:23.750
You and literature
are not merchandise.

04:30:23.750 --> 04:30:25.620
They cannot fake you.

04:30:25.620 --> 04:30:27.420
Suppose your next book is too good

04:30:27.420 --> 04:30:30.380
and doesn't pay its
share in their overhead.

04:30:30.380 --> 04:30:34.060
Those fair-weather friends
will kick you right downstairs.

04:30:34.060 --> 04:30:35.640
They don't understand you.

04:30:35.640 --> 04:30:37.700 position:56%
They don't know what it's all about.

04:30:37.700 --> 04:30:40.790
They just want to exploit
your success.

04:30:40.790 --> 04:30:42.370
But you are free.

04:30:42.370 --> 04:30:44.510
You must do [background
laughter] what you want to do.

04:30:44.510 --> 04:30:47.740
[ Laughter ]

04:30:47.740 --> 04:30:49.610
What can I do for you?

04:30:49.610 --> 04:30:52.700
I can push you steadily
with the kind of people

04:30:52.700 --> 04:30:54.540
who are your proper audience.

04:30:54.540 --> 04:30:56.980
I can put out good books
for you irrespective

04:30:56.980 --> 04:30:58.790
of whether they pay their way.

04:30:58.790 --> 04:31:00.870
And if you think you are
losing money with me,

04:31:00.870 --> 04:31:02.490
I'll see that you get that.

04:31:02.490 --> 04:31:04.360
What are Simon and
Schuster offering you?

04:31:04.360 --> 04:31:06.920
I'll meet anything they put up.

04:31:06.920 --> 04:31:08.240
Why do I care?

04:31:08.240 --> 04:31:10.970
Because I know that I need
you in order to do anything

04:31:10.970 --> 04:31:13.130
for the young ones coming on.

04:31:13.130 --> 04:31:15.120
I can print their books for them.

04:31:15.120 --> 04:31:18.100
But unless the name New
Directions stands for something,

04:31:18.100 --> 04:31:20.260 position:56%
they'll have a hell of a row to hoe.

04:31:20.260 --> 04:31:23.500
With you, New Directions
does stand for something.

04:31:23.500 --> 04:31:26.690
And the people it prints
will get a start and a break.

04:31:26.690 --> 04:31:28.730
This is not just monkeyshine.

04:31:28.730 --> 04:31:31.150
It's the way the things work.

04:31:31.150 --> 04:31:35.730 position:56%
But, again, you are absolutely
free, and you must do what you want.

04:31:35.730 --> 04:31:37.030
You mustn't think of me --

04:31:37.030 --> 04:31:38.330
&gt;&gt; Right.

04:31:38.330 --> 04:31:39.630
&gt;&gt; Leslie Morris: -- "but
I think you should think

04:31:39.630 --> 04:31:41.340
of the other writers whom
New Directions made strong

04:31:41.340 --> 04:31:44.510
by you could on their feet.

04:31:44.510 --> 04:31:47.560
Well, think it all over
a while and let me know.

04:31:47.560 --> 04:31:51.030
Best, Jim."

04:31:51.030 --> 04:31:57.020
Williams wrote back
[laughter], "Dear Jim, so be it.

04:31:57.020 --> 04:31:59.270
I frankly didn't think
you were interested.

04:31:59.270 --> 04:32:00.570
Now it's different.

04:32:00.570 --> 04:32:03.930
We'll go ahead together, not
any faster than is reasonable,

04:32:03.930 --> 04:32:07.670
but just as far and as
persistently as we are able.

04:32:07.670 --> 04:32:09.240
It isn't that I need money now.

04:32:09.240 --> 04:32:10.780
That's not the point.

04:32:10.780 --> 04:32:14.160
My sole thought was that sometime
or other, in the near future,

04:32:14.160 --> 04:32:17.480
I ought to try to make some sort
of connection which would enable me

04:32:17.480 --> 04:32:20.260
to get some sort of
return from my writing.

04:32:20.260 --> 04:32:24.630
I agree that my chances are slim,
but I felt that I had to try.

04:32:24.630 --> 04:32:27.410
I'm convinced that my
best chances now lie

04:32:27.410 --> 04:32:30.430
with you, looked at quite coldly.

04:32:30.430 --> 04:32:32.800
Nor do I expect the impossible.

04:32:32.800 --> 04:32:34.100
It was impossible for me

04:32:34.100 --> 04:32:37.900
to know before this last letter
what your plans could be.

04:32:37.900 --> 04:32:40.060
It's noon now and I have to eat.

04:32:40.060 --> 04:32:41.930
Let me have your reactions.

04:32:41.930 --> 04:32:44.580
Sincerely yours, W.C. Williams."

04:32:44.580 --> 04:32:49.180
A second exchange, this
one between Dylan Thomas,

04:32:49.180 --> 04:32:52.510
another core New Direction
writer, and Jay.

04:32:52.510 --> 04:32:55.840
Thomas of course was
perpetually short of money.

04:32:55.840 --> 04:32:59.560
In this letter, written in 1938,
and shortly after the exchange

04:32:59.560 --> 04:33:01.490
with Williams I've just read,

04:33:01.490 --> 04:33:04.750
Thomas concludes a densely
written five-page letter

04:33:04.750 --> 04:33:10.360
in which he describes his poverty
in graphic detail as follows.

04:33:10.360 --> 04:33:14.210
"I apologize for this recital,
but every one of my hopes is based

04:33:14.210 --> 04:33:16.930
on the possibility that
New Directions may be able

04:33:16.930 --> 04:33:19.460
to give me an advance on royalties.

04:33:19.460 --> 04:33:23.630
It's extremely irregular, I know,
and must be very annoying to you.

04:33:23.630 --> 04:33:26.910
For this unavoidably miserable
letter I again apologize.

04:33:26.910 --> 04:33:32.420
I had hoped to write all this in a
business-like manner but I failed.

04:33:32.420 --> 04:33:35.100
I failed because, although I
know nothing about the business

04:33:35.100 --> 04:33:38.110
of publishing or the agreements
that can be made between publisher

04:33:38.110 --> 04:33:42.050
and author, I know enough to
realize that my most sincere appeal

04:33:42.050 --> 04:33:44.060
for an immediate advance
on the work you wish

04:33:44.060 --> 04:33:48.530
to publish is unorthodox
and possible insolent.

04:33:48.530 --> 04:33:52.490
I am sorry I had to write this, but
I am forced to do away with dignity

04:33:52.490 --> 04:33:55.580
and formality and ask
you this question.

04:33:55.580 --> 04:33:59.360
Can you, at once, give
me money for which

04:33:59.360 --> 04:34:03.870
in return I promise you all the
work I have done and will ever do?

04:34:03.870 --> 04:34:05.170
&gt;&gt; Whoo.

04:34:05.170 --> 04:34:09.180 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Leslie Morris: "I hope beyond
all things that you will answer me."

04:34:10.210 --> 04:34:13.120
Jay responded immediately.

04:34:13.120 --> 04:34:15.130
"Your letter had quite an
effect on me [laughter].

04:34:15.130 --> 04:34:19.770
When I got it in Paris I was
just on the point of going off

04:34:19.770 --> 04:34:21.920
to Spain to fight in the war.

04:34:21.920 --> 04:34:24.510
Then I thought about
your situation and --

04:34:24.510 --> 04:34:28.120
[ Laughter ]

04:34:28.120 --> 04:34:30.100
"-- then I thought about
your situation and that

04:34:30.100 --> 04:34:33.550
of two other young writers of mine
in America and I said, 'My, God.

04:34:33.550 --> 04:34:34.850
No, I can't do that.

04:34:34.850 --> 04:34:36.400
I've got a duty to do.'

04:34:36.400 --> 04:34:37.700
So I didn't go.

04:34:37.700 --> 04:34:41.990 position:56%
I can't get myself killed right now.

04:34:41.990 --> 04:34:45.860
As long as you stay good and write
the real thing you will never

04:34:45.860 --> 04:34:47.180
make money.

04:34:47.180 --> 04:34:48.680
I must tell you that.

04:34:48.680 --> 04:34:50.730
You must resign yourself to that.

04:34:50.730 --> 04:34:53.150
That is the state of
publishing today.

04:34:53.150 --> 04:34:56.290
But you can count on me
to do what I can for you.

04:34:56.290 --> 04:34:58.660
At this moment I have
almost no money at all.

04:34:58.660 --> 04:35:03.390
I'm living on $2 a day myself,
but in good times I have plenty.

04:35:03.390 --> 04:35:05.930
So I cannot promise you
very much right now.

04:35:05.930 --> 04:35:09.980
I can send you $20 now and
the same again next month.

04:35:09.980 --> 04:35:12.360
If business gets better,
I can do more for you.

04:35:12.360 --> 04:35:16.920
In the meantime, I'll do
my best to see you through.

04:35:16.920 --> 04:35:19.740
New Directions is the best
publisher for you in America

04:35:19.740 --> 04:35:21.910
because I fight for my books.

04:35:21.910 --> 04:35:25.150
None of the big houses will
fight for a poet these days.

04:35:25.150 --> 04:35:28.200
If they think he'll write a
novel, they'll play him along,

04:35:28.200 --> 04:35:30.930
but they won't fight
for him as a poet.

04:35:30.930 --> 04:35:33.410
I worry about you,
let me hear from you.

04:35:33.410 --> 04:35:37.980
Lockland. The correspondence
in the archive continues

04:35:37.980 --> 04:35:40.930
to be rich throughout Jay's
active involvement with the firm,

04:35:40.930 --> 04:35:43.160
even thought the telephone
was handy.

04:35:43.160 --> 04:35:46.620
It's my impression that perhaps
because he was a writer himself,

04:35:46.620 --> 04:35:48.100
he often wrote letters even

04:35:48.100 --> 04:35:52.520
when presumably a telephone
call would have been possible.

04:35:52.520 --> 04:35:54.910
But faced with such a
wealth of documentation

04:35:54.910 --> 04:35:58.550
in the New Direction's archive for
the poet and student interested

04:35:58.550 --> 04:36:02.770
in how writers write and how
writers survive as writers.

04:36:02.770 --> 04:36:06.460
I do lament the passing of the
tradition of letter writing.

04:36:06.460 --> 04:36:08.560
Certainly, much of the
author correspondence

04:36:08.560 --> 04:36:12.080
that I see these days is
not terribly revealing.

04:36:12.080 --> 04:36:15.440
The telephone has made serious end
roads [phonetic] in this record.

04:36:15.440 --> 04:36:19.800
Email does to me, at least offer
the possibility of reversing some

04:36:19.800 --> 04:36:23.960
of this loss, but only if poets
and editors keep their email

04:36:23.960 --> 04:36:27.130
and please not in electronic
form, but on good old paper,

04:36:27.130 --> 04:36:30.180
which at least we know
how to preserve.

04:36:30.180 --> 04:36:32.680 position:56%
I hope that this very brief overview

04:36:32.680 --> 04:36:36.510 position:56%
about New Direction's has given some
indication of a possible formula

04:36:36.510 --> 04:36:39.600
for eventual success as a
poetry publisher, although,

04:36:39.600 --> 04:36:42.850
to be honest I think that
Jay was nearly unique.

04:36:42.850 --> 04:36:45.950
He attracted and kept good
poets because he cared

04:36:45.950 --> 04:36:49.130
for the poet's interest
in every possible way.

04:36:49.130 --> 04:36:52.430
He also had the patience
to wait 10 to 20 years

04:36:52.430 --> 04:36:56.270
until the work was appreciated by
a broader public and to be ready

04:36:56.270 --> 04:37:00.160
with their books and
print when the call came.

04:37:00.160 --> 04:37:03.030
I also hope given that there
are publishers and poets

04:37:03.030 --> 04:37:05.350
in this audience, that you
will all think a little

04:37:05.350 --> 04:37:09.280
about future generations of
poets and student's of poetry.

04:37:09.280 --> 04:37:13.200
Keep your drafts, print out
your email, submit graciously

04:37:13.200 --> 04:37:15.300
to oral history interviews.

04:37:15.300 --> 04:37:17.380 position:56%
If you don't, yes, the printed books

04:37:17.380 --> 04:37:21.270
and your poetry may survive
for future generations.

04:37:21.270 --> 04:37:24.790
But those generations will have
lost the opportunity to appreciate

04:37:24.790 --> 04:37:28.130
that very personal passion for
poetry and the promulgation

04:37:28.130 --> 04:37:31.980
of poetry that comes through so
clearly in correspondence like that

04:37:31.980 --> 04:37:33.810
in the New Direction's archive.

04:37:33.810 --> 04:37:37.510 position:56%
And I think poetry and
scholarship will be poor without it.

04:37:37.510 --> 04:37:49.940
[ Applause ]

04:37:49.940 --> 04:37:51.400
&gt;&gt; John Y. Cole: Well
after listening to Leslie,

04:37:51.400 --> 04:37:55.440
how can one doubt the importance
of archives and the kind

04:37:55.440 --> 04:37:59.410 position:56%
of archive actually that [inaudible]
building as well for the future,

04:37:59.410 --> 04:38:03.080
which is an important part of
the endeavor, as well as efforts

04:38:03.080 --> 04:38:05.060
on the part of libraries
and archives

04:38:05.060 --> 04:38:09.810
to retain these important records
and copies of correspondence.

04:38:09.810 --> 04:38:14.750
Jack Shoemaker is a
experienced, passionate publisher.

04:38:14.750 --> 04:38:16.190
Jack --

04:38:16.190 --> 04:38:18.320
[ Audio Skips ]

04:38:18.320 --> 04:38:19.620
&gt;&gt; Jack Shoemaker: On
one of the first pieces

04:38:19.620 --> 04:38:24.450
of advice he gave me was, get
good advisors, listen to them

04:38:24.450 --> 04:38:26.500
and ignore everyone else.

04:38:26.500 --> 04:38:31.070
A writer that Leslie didn't mention
that Laughlin died in despair

04:38:31.070 --> 04:38:35.390
over the lack of reading --
readership for was Kenneth Rexroth.

04:38:35.390 --> 04:38:40.950
In the early days, it was
clearly Pounds influence

04:38:40.950 --> 04:38:44.930
that ran the engine
that was New Directions.

04:38:44.930 --> 04:38:48.320
Shortly thereafter, a woman named
Barbara Guess was really the French

04:38:48.320 --> 04:38:53.470
informant to New Directions,
but when Pound returned

04:38:53.470 --> 04:38:56.750
after the Bollingen
fiasco, returned to Italy

04:38:56.750 --> 04:38:59.880
and really entered a
prolonged period of silence.

04:38:59.880 --> 04:39:01.550
It was Rexroth who stepped forward

04:39:01.550 --> 04:39:04.570
and taught Jay pretty
much everything he knew

04:39:04.570 --> 04:39:07.030
about Chinese writing,
about Japanese poetry,

04:39:07.030 --> 04:39:11.410
turned him onto a whole
generation of poets that he --

04:39:11.410 --> 04:39:14.190
Jay was not familiar
with, and was I think,

04:39:14.190 --> 04:39:18.590
in a way that people have not
appreciated, absolutely central

04:39:18.590 --> 04:39:20.810
to what we now think
of as the Beat Scene

04:39:20.810 --> 04:39:25.690
or the San Francisco Renaissance
or the New York School of Poetry.

04:39:25.690 --> 04:39:28.250
I also want to take a
chance for a short --

04:39:28.250 --> 04:39:32.100
we just shipped Herbert
Morrison's new book,

04:39:32.100 --> 04:39:34.850
so you can make your
way to a Border's.

04:39:34.850 --> 04:39:37.550
Because of the tyranny
of chain bookstores,

04:39:37.550 --> 04:39:40.530
we can now know precisely when
our book will be in their hands.

04:39:40.530 --> 04:39:42.930
It's 17 days from the day
it leaves our warehouse,

04:39:42.930 --> 04:39:49.420
so it should be there this
weekend -- fabulous book.

04:39:49.420 --> 04:39:51.880
Well, John was very kind,
really what I said to him was

04:39:51.880 --> 04:39:53.980
that I didn't think I
was going to be here

04:39:53.980 --> 04:39:56.190 position:56%
and I didn't have very much time to
think about what I was going to say,

04:39:56.190 --> 04:40:00.670
so I was just going to talk
about myself or my career.

04:40:00.670 --> 04:40:02.970
And I'm most anxious because I
thought that's what we were going

04:40:02.970 --> 04:40:04.820
to do to really respond
to questions.

04:40:04.820 --> 04:40:07.860
I have many responses to
what's been said already.

04:40:07.860 --> 04:40:11.630 position:56%
But I will give you a brief
overview of how I got to where I am.

04:40:11.630 --> 04:40:14.850
I've been involved with publishing
and selling poetry for a long time.

04:40:14.850 --> 04:40:18.640
The first thing I published
in 1965 was a broadside

04:40:18.640 --> 04:40:22.430
of Gary Snyder poem,
<i>The Bed in the Sky </i>.

04:40:22.430 --> 04:40:26.060 position:56%
The first book I published through a
press associated with my book shop,

04:40:26.060 --> 04:40:29.650
we called ourselves, The Bookshop
for Poets then, was a book of poems

04:40:29.650 --> 04:40:33.530
by the Vietnamese monk Thich
Nhat Hanh, <i>The Cry of Vietnam </i>.

04:40:33.530 --> 04:40:39.100
In 1966, Tye as he was
known at that stage had a --

04:40:39.100 --> 04:40:45.130
a singular job, he was the last
person Zen monks saw before they

04:40:45.130 --> 04:40:46.430
burned themselves.

04:40:46.430 --> 04:40:50.660
For a few of us, the late '60s

04:40:50.660 --> 04:40:54.000
and early '70s were the golden
age of poetry publishing.

04:40:54.000 --> 04:40:56.020
The counter culture
was in full bloom,

04:40:56.020 --> 04:40:58.410
poets were among the
leading scholars,

04:40:58.410 --> 04:41:01.790 position:56%
philosophers, activists and leaders.

04:41:01.790 --> 04:41:04.990
Donald Allen's [inaudible] <i>The New
American Poetry </i>introduces us all

04:41:04.990 --> 04:41:09.230
to the work of Charles Olsen,
Robert Duncan, Denise Levertov,

04:41:09.230 --> 04:41:13.920
Gary Snyder, Allen Ginsberg,
Gregory Corso and a dozen others.

04:41:13.920 --> 04:41:16.330
As a book seller, I could
easily recall the excitement

04:41:16.330 --> 04:41:20.290
as people would hear about and
look forward to new books of poems.

04:41:20.290 --> 04:41:24.020
I had a waiting list of all
things, of more than 30 customers

04:41:24.020 --> 04:41:27.230
for the first volume of
Ed Dorn's <i>Gunslinger </i>.

04:41:27.230 --> 04:41:29.120
As longhairs moved
into the countryside,

04:41:29.120 --> 04:41:30.420
they took along their copies

04:41:30.420 --> 04:41:33.040
of <i>Rip Rap </i>and <i>Cottish </i>[assumed
spelling] and to this day some

04:41:33.040 --> 04:41:36.030
of the largest audiences
for poetry are found

04:41:36.030 --> 04:41:38.860
in these back country locations.

04:41:38.860 --> 04:41:41.680
This was the golden age too
of small press magazines

04:41:41.680 --> 04:41:44.180
and journals and books.

04:41:44.180 --> 04:41:46.800
One could have an entire session
of this conference on the history

04:41:46.800 --> 04:41:48.930
and demise of the small
press movement.

04:41:48.930 --> 04:41:51.110
But let me just say that
nothing has been seen

04:41:51.110 --> 04:41:56.050
since that even approximates the
vitality of the scene at that time.

04:41:56.050 --> 04:42:00.130
It was in a direct way, government
support that managed to kill it.

04:42:00.130 --> 04:42:03.390
It is hard to remember
sometimes how visible poets were

04:42:03.390 --> 04:42:05.630
and what impact they had then.

04:42:05.630 --> 04:42:07.770
Press proceeded by the moderns,

04:42:07.770 --> 04:42:10.810
by the '60s Yates Pound
Elliot classes were taught

04:42:10.810 --> 04:42:13.470
in virtually every
university of the country.

04:42:13.470 --> 04:42:15.740
Frost was still in
everyone's memory,

04:42:15.740 --> 04:42:19.190
more his persona really
than his poetry.

04:42:19.190 --> 04:42:22.590
Stevens was -- Wallace Stevens was
the most influential unread poet

04:42:22.590 --> 04:42:23.890
since [inaudible].

04:42:23.890 --> 04:42:28.560
Marianne Moore was in Life
Magazine for God's sake.

04:42:28.560 --> 04:42:31.000
She worked on a project
with the Ford Motor Company

04:42:31.000 --> 04:42:32.790
that became the Edsel.

04:42:32.790 --> 04:42:37.210
I -- I once held in my
hands a long playing record

04:42:37.210 --> 04:42:40.450
of Cassius Clay [inaudible]
Muhammad Ali

04:42:40.450 --> 04:42:43.780
with the entire back cover
printing an extended [inaudible]

04:42:43.780 --> 04:42:46.920
by Marianne Moore, wherein she
[inaudible] Clay's couplets

04:42:46.920 --> 04:42:49.160
to Alexander Pope.

04:42:49.160 --> 04:42:51.540
The late '70s and '80s
were a desert.

04:42:51.540 --> 04:42:53.380
Poetry sales plummeted.

04:42:53.380 --> 04:42:57.460 position:56%
More importantly, the poets
themselves withdrew or so it seemed.

04:42:57.460 --> 04:43:00.740
And the decade of greed convinced
the literate audience in America

04:43:00.740 --> 04:43:04.820
to [inaudible] Calvinist
ancestors reading nonfiction;

04:43:04.820 --> 04:43:07.660
reading for profit
became the anthem.

04:43:07.660 --> 04:43:11.700
Small presses disappeared, poetry
sales dropped, so did the sales

04:43:11.700 --> 04:43:15.710
for serious work in translation,
serious experimental fiction

04:43:15.710 --> 04:43:17.730
and first and second novels.

04:43:17.730 --> 04:43:19.540 position:56%
There was, as this library named one

04:43:19.540 --> 04:43:22.710
of its own conferences,
a crisis in publishing.

04:43:22.710 --> 04:43:26.230
The poets who came after,
those of the late '70s

04:43:26.230 --> 04:43:28.360
and '80s were mostly invested

04:43:28.360 --> 04:43:32.550
in either a small minded personal
confession -- confessional poetry,

04:43:32.550 --> 04:43:35.470
sanctioned by the writing programs
that grew up like a cancer all

04:43:35.470 --> 04:43:39.560
over the country, or they veered
off into an opaque experimentalism

04:43:39.560 --> 04:43:42.350 position:56%
that essentially mocked the audience
with an arrogance that was more

04:43:42.350 --> 04:43:46.540
like academic writing than
poetry -- modernist or otherwise.

04:43:46.540 --> 04:43:49.250
It may be that these
matters are all cyclic.

04:43:49.250 --> 04:43:52.850 position:56%
I've begun to wonder what the impact
is of lyrics and popular songs

04:43:52.850 --> 04:43:57.180
on those most vulnerable,
listeners in their 20's.

04:43:57.180 --> 04:44:02.410
Frank Sinatra, Ira Gershwin,
Woody Guthrie, Bob Dylan,

04:44:02.410 --> 04:44:10.260 position:56%
The Jefferson Airplane, The Beatles,
REM, Nirvana, Public Enemy, Dr. Dre,

04:44:10.260 --> 04:44:14.000
Tracy Chapman, Portishead,
Matchbook Twenty --

04:44:14.000 --> 04:44:16.180
each generation seems to
believe that the lyrics

04:44:16.180 --> 04:44:20.430
of their popular songs are
superior or in fact art

04:44:20.430 --> 04:44:23.420
and this leads those 20 something's
perhaps to an appreciation

04:44:23.420 --> 04:44:26.310
of the power of the heightened
language that is poetry.

04:44:26.310 --> 04:44:29.710
Maybe that's a seed,
but however it happened,

04:44:29.710 --> 04:44:32.520
the '90s was a time
of audience expansion.

04:44:32.520 --> 04:44:36.850 position:56%
From sales of poetry books to poetry
slams, the more accessible poets

04:44:36.850 --> 04:44:40.760
in their 40's and 50's and
very early 60's, show sales say

04:44:40.760 --> 04:44:44.510
above 20,000 copies that
their forebears might not have

04:44:44.510 --> 04:44:46.130
dared imagine.

04:44:46.130 --> 04:44:49.440 position:56%
A few of the old guard, Gary Snyder,
Wendell Berry, William Merwin

04:44:49.440 --> 04:44:52.290
and the like can match
the youngsters.

04:44:52.290 --> 04:44:54.340
This very week as we've
already heard,

04:44:54.340 --> 04:44:56.590
we have Seamus Heaney's
translation of <i>Beowulf </i>sitting

04:44:56.590 --> 04:44:58.910
on the New York Times
bestseller list with more

04:44:58.910 --> 04:45:02.770
than 45,000 copies shipped.

04:45:02.770 --> 04:45:06.740
Writing schools are crammed, so
are festivals and conferences,

04:45:06.740 --> 04:45:10.230
even the difficult work coming
out now causes response.

04:45:10.230 --> 04:45:12.700
News magazines will
actually devote articles

04:45:12.700 --> 04:45:15.450
to the difficulty of Jorie Graham.

04:45:15.450 --> 04:45:17.140
We must forgive them in
their apparent belief

04:45:17.140 --> 04:45:19.790
that she is America's
first difficult poet,

04:45:19.790 --> 04:45:23.550 position:56%
but I've actually had meals
interrupted when a poet I was dining

04:45:23.550 --> 04:45:26.170
with was recognized
by fellow diners.

04:45:26.170 --> 04:45:28.330
This is a time on fire.

04:45:28.330 --> 04:45:32.020
But lest we become too complacent,
let's insist on the long view

04:45:32.020 --> 04:45:34.700
and understand that
it was not always so,

04:45:34.700 --> 04:45:38.920
but it has been good before and
it will not always be this way

04:45:38.920 --> 04:45:41.970
and this probably won't
last very long.

04:45:41.970 --> 04:45:45.810
As poets and publishers, we can
enjoy ourselves for this moment.

04:45:45.810 --> 04:45:47.610
Thank you.

04:45:47.610 --> 04:45:54.300
[ Applause ]

