to other larger waters.

05:22:16.410 --> 05:22:21.140
But your epic of triumph and
suffering need this minor book,

05:22:21.140 --> 05:22:26.590
take your pen to a blank
page of scrap, boot up

05:22:26.590 --> 05:22:29.390
and delete my name
from your databank.

05:22:29.390 --> 05:22:33.680
You have others to care for,
without taking care of me.

05:22:33.680 --> 05:22:37.930
Our fates mixed together, makes
more stormy weather and see,

05:22:37.930 --> 05:22:41.000
it's just stopped raining.

05:22:41.000 --> 05:22:46.460
So, step to you balcony and breathe
the new atmosphere thoroughly

05:22:46.460 --> 05:22:47.760
cleaned of me.

05:22:47.760 --> 05:22:51.290
That's life, egging
your heartbeat on.

05:22:51.290 --> 05:22:54.830
I want more of it too than
could ever fill me up,

05:22:54.830 --> 05:22:59.650
before the rain falls again,
this time falling with no end.

05:22:59.650 --> 05:23:04.620
Late seasons flood water,
sweeping out of cherished homes.

05:23:04.620 --> 05:23:06.420
Thanks.

05:23:06.420 --> 05:23:19.010
[ Applause ]

05:23:19.010 --> 05:23:31.570
[ Silence ]

05:23:31.570 --> 05:23:32.870
&gt;&gt; Naomi Shihab Nye: Gratitude

05:23:32.870 --> 05:23:35.600
to all the eloquent stunning
speakers of the last two days.

05:23:35.600 --> 05:23:39.550
I don't know when I've heard
more exhilarating presentations

05:23:39.550 --> 05:23:43.910
and I have conquered my phobia
of panels forever having listened

05:23:43.910 --> 05:23:46.260
to the panels that have
been up here today.

05:23:46.260 --> 05:23:48.240
It's -- it's been a marvelous time.

05:23:48.240 --> 05:23:50.590
I want to thank everybody
who made this --

05:23:50.590 --> 05:23:54.700
this program possible and
special thanks to Robert Pinsky

05:23:54.700 --> 05:24:01.150
and Witter Bynner for this very
unexpected and kind support.

05:24:04.040 --> 05:24:08.650 position:56%
Since the topic is poetry in America
today, I just wanted to say a word

05:24:08.650 --> 05:24:12.810
for where I've been for the last
25 years, which is out in schools

05:24:12.810 --> 05:24:17.160
as an itinerant visiting writer.

05:24:17.160 --> 05:24:22.240
And never have I heard a
teacher say that her teacher --

05:24:22.240 --> 05:24:26.490
her students have spent significant
time with poetry in any way

05:24:26.490 --> 05:24:31.150 position:56%
and gained nothing from it -- never.

05:24:31.150 --> 05:24:35.900
This past season I was asked
at a conference of teachers,

05:24:35.900 --> 05:24:37.750
"But what have you
done over the years

05:24:37.750 --> 05:24:42.490
when the students made fun
of one another's poems."

05:24:42.490 --> 05:24:45.830
And I had think for a long
minute before answering, "Well,

05:24:45.830 --> 05:24:49.160
they never have, not
once have they."

05:24:49.160 --> 05:24:51.700
Once a teacher made
fun of a student,

05:24:51.700 --> 05:24:54.980
but I had never heard students
make fun of one another's poems,

05:24:54.980 --> 05:25:00.000
and how excited I am to think
of them seeing these videos.

05:25:00.000 --> 05:25:01.690 position:56%
How wonderful that will be for them.

05:25:01.690 --> 05:25:04.680
And I just wanted to
read two little stories.

05:25:04.680 --> 05:25:07.840
I've worked as an anthologist
for the past 10 years as well,

05:25:07.840 --> 05:25:14.700 position:56%
trying to create books that would be
friendly to students, bringing poets

05:25:14.700 --> 05:25:17.720
from around the world from
Mexico, from the Middle East,

05:25:17.720 --> 05:25:22.470
voices I wanted to see in more
American classrooms into the hands

05:25:22.470 --> 05:25:23.940
of teachers in this country.

05:25:23.940 --> 05:25:26.080
My most recent anthology
though that's just

05:25:26.080 --> 05:25:28.080
out is called <i>Salting the Ocean,</i>

05:25:28.080 --> 05:25:31.980
<i>100 Poems by Young Poets</i>
from people I've been with.

05:25:31.980 --> 05:25:35.120
And I just wanted to read two
little stories, which we sneaked

05:25:35.120 --> 05:25:39.170
into the index from
classroom experiences.

05:25:40.470 --> 05:25:44.340
And these were stories from
my journal working with them.

05:25:44.340 --> 05:25:46.890
Waiting for the coffee
pot to percolate,

05:25:46.890 --> 05:25:50.180
one teacher in the
lounge speaks to another.

05:25:50.180 --> 05:25:53.540
Does poetry have anything
to do with math?

05:25:53.540 --> 05:25:56.500
Her friend says, "What?"

05:25:56.500 --> 05:25:58.420
"Well," says the first teacher.

05:25:58.420 --> 05:26:00.900
"You know how I told
you about Benjamin

05:26:00.900 --> 05:26:03.330
who never does his assignments?

05:26:03.330 --> 05:26:08.160 position:56%
So then we started this poetry
workshop a month ago, he volunteered

05:26:08.160 --> 05:26:11.970
to read his poems, the
other kids cheered him on.

05:26:11.970 --> 05:26:14.530
Yesterday, he brings
his math homework

05:26:14.530 --> 05:26:19.610
in for the first time all
year and leaves it on my desk.

05:26:19.610 --> 05:26:21.180
I don't get it.

05:26:21.180 --> 05:26:25.030
What does poetry have
to do with math?"

05:26:26.330 --> 05:26:32.380
A fifth grade boy telephones the
poet who visited his class and asks

05:26:32.380 --> 05:26:35.410
if he could dictate a poem to her.

05:26:35.410 --> 05:26:39.940
She says, "Why don't you
just write it down yourself

05:26:39.940 --> 05:26:42.130
and give it to me next week?"

05:26:42.130 --> 05:26:47.130
He says, "I feel I need to
say it into somebody's ear

05:26:47.130 --> 05:26:49.300
or it won't come out right.

05:26:49.300 --> 05:26:52.690
There's nobody at home over here."

05:26:52.690 --> 05:26:55.300
So she writes down what he says.

05:26:55.300 --> 05:26:57.030
It's pretty great.

05:26:57.030 --> 05:27:00.420
She promises to give
him a copy next week.

05:27:00.420 --> 05:27:04.290
Two hours later her
phone rings again,

05:27:04.290 --> 05:27:06.900
"Do you have another
piece of paper?"

05:27:11.160 --> 05:27:16.110
And just one of the poet's voices,

05:27:16.110 --> 05:27:19.220
this was from a fourth
grader, Brenda Burmeister.

05:27:19.220 --> 05:27:23.480 position:56%
I have managed to keep in touch with
her over the years and she does say

05:27:23.480 --> 05:27:25.900
that this -- writing of
this poem, which she wrote

05:27:25.900 --> 05:27:31.140 position:56%
in approximately seven minutes,
staring into a broken compact mirror

05:27:31.140 --> 05:27:33.500
on her desk was very significant

05:27:33.500 --> 05:27:35.560
because it was the
first time she learned

05:27:35.560 --> 05:27:39.570
that you could find something
out while writing a poem.

05:27:39.570 --> 05:27:43.140
You didn't have to
know it in advance.

05:27:44.380 --> 05:27:47.160
Fourth grade, Brenda Burmeister.

05:27:47.160 --> 05:27:52.410
"Alone with my mirror, dreaming
of love, wishing for love,

05:27:52.410 --> 05:27:55.290 position:56%
thinking of my dear old grandmother.

05:27:55.290 --> 05:28:01.340
My eyes represent my grandmother,
my nose represents my grandmother.

05:28:01.340 --> 05:28:06.270
Suddenly my face turns into
my dear old grandmother.

05:28:06.270 --> 05:28:11.790
I start to speak, I hear my voice,
I hear my grandmother's voice.

05:28:11.790 --> 05:28:17.270
I say to myself, that can't be
my grandmother, she is dead.

05:28:17.270 --> 05:28:22.000
She says to me, it
is your grandmother.

05:28:22.000 --> 05:28:24.410
I had trust in my grandmother,

05:28:24.410 --> 05:28:31.400
so I believe my grandmother
lives beyond death in my mirror."

05:28:32.570 --> 05:28:36.450
And then a few from me.

05:28:36.450 --> 05:28:40.120
I wear this poetry advocate button
from poet's house in New York,

05:28:40.120 --> 05:28:44.700
not to announce myself, but to
invite people to tell me stories.

05:28:44.700 --> 05:28:46.000
And they do.

05:28:46.000 --> 05:28:49.680
In an airport two weeks ago,
a woman came up and said, "So,

05:28:49.680 --> 05:28:53.990
can I tell you about the
time a poem saved my life?"

05:28:53.990 --> 05:28:56.850
And she isn't the first
one who's done that.

05:28:56.850 --> 05:28:59.140
They also let you check
into hotels early and things

05:28:59.140 --> 05:29:01.980
if you wear a button
like this, feeling --

05:29:01.980 --> 05:29:04.610
feeling you've probably been
sleeping in lobbies until now.

05:29:04.610 --> 05:29:10.940
But I want to dedicate this
poem to The Library of Congress.

05:29:10.940 --> 05:29:14.360
Remembering my childhood library in
St. Louis and our exquisite library

05:29:14.360 --> 05:29:21.060
in San Antonio, because of
libraries we can say these things.

05:29:21.060 --> 05:29:24.350
She is holding the book close
to her body, carrying it home

05:29:24.350 --> 05:29:27.940
on the cracked sidewalk
down the tangled hill.

05:29:27.940 --> 05:29:33.110
If a dog runs at her again, she
will use the book as a shield.

05:29:33.110 --> 05:29:37.370
She looked hard among the long
lines of books to find this one.

05:29:37.370 --> 05:29:41.550 position:56%
When they start talking about money,
when the day contains such long

05:29:41.550 --> 05:29:44.880
and hot places, she will go inside.

05:29:44.880 --> 05:29:47.110
An orange bed is waiting.

05:29:47.110 --> 05:29:50.550
Story without corners, she
will have two families,

05:29:50.550 --> 05:29:53.620
they will eat at different hours.

05:29:53.620 --> 05:29:57.640
She is carrying a book past the
fire station in the five and dime.

05:29:57.640 --> 05:30:01.600
What this town has not given
her, the book will provide.

05:30:01.600 --> 05:30:05.400
A sheep, a wilderness
of new solutions,

05:30:05.400 --> 05:30:08.790
the book has already lived
through its troubles.

05:30:08.790 --> 05:30:13.510
The book has a calm
cover, a straight spine.

05:30:13.510 --> 05:30:16.830
When the step returns to itself
as the best place for sitting

05:30:16.830 --> 05:30:20.860
and the old men up and down the
street are latching their clippers,

05:30:20.860 --> 05:30:22.570
she will not be alone.

05:30:22.570 --> 05:30:29.860 position:56%
She will have a book to open and
open and open, her life starts here.

05:30:29.860 --> 05:30:37.810
Wedding cake -- once on
a plane, a woman asked me

05:30:37.810 --> 05:30:41.720
to hold her baby and disappear it.

05:30:41.720 --> 05:30:46.090
I figured it was safe, our
being on a plane and all.

05:30:46.090 --> 05:30:50.400
How far could she go?

05:30:50.400 --> 05:30:52.810
She returned one hour later,

05:30:52.810 --> 05:30:58.170
having changed her clothes
and washed her hair.

05:30:58.170 --> 05:31:00.950
I didn't recognize her.

05:31:00.950 --> 05:31:05.110
By this time, the baby and I
had examined each other's necks,

05:31:05.110 --> 05:31:10.160
we had cried a little, I had
a silver bracelet and a watch,

05:31:10.160 --> 05:31:12.940
gold studs glittered
in the baby's ears.

05:31:12.940 --> 05:31:18.610
She wore a tiny white dress, leafed
with layers like a wedding cake.

05:31:18.610 --> 05:31:21.820
I did not want to give her back.

05:31:21.820 --> 05:31:26.800 position:56%
The baby's curls coiled tightly
against her scalp, another alphabet.

05:31:26.800 --> 05:31:31.270
I read new, new, new,
my mother gets tired.

05:31:31.270 --> 05:31:34.120
I'll chew your hand.

05:31:34.120 --> 05:31:38.520
The baby left my skirt
crumpled, my lap aching.

05:31:38.520 --> 05:31:41.800
Now I'm her secret guardian,
that little nub of dream

05:31:41.800 --> 05:31:45.280
that rises slightly but won't
come clear, as she grows,

05:31:45.280 --> 05:31:51.100
as she feels ill at
east, I'll bob my knee.

05:31:51.100 --> 05:31:52.990
What will she forget?

05:31:52.990 --> 05:31:55.480
Whom will she marry?

05:31:55.480 --> 05:31:57.550
He'd better check with me.

05:31:57.550 --> 05:32:02.470
I'll say once she flew dressed
like a cake, between two doilies

05:32:02.470 --> 05:32:07.810
of cloud, she could slip the
card into a pocket, pull it out.

05:32:07.810 --> 05:32:16.450
Already she knew the small finger
was funnier than the whole arm.

05:32:16.450 --> 05:32:20.000
William Merwin and I were
talking at lunch about poems

05:32:20.000 --> 05:32:23.790
which we must write in response
to certain things in the news

05:32:23.790 --> 05:32:27.350
and I'll just read these.

05:32:27.350 --> 05:32:30.920
This is two -- two poems,
part -- one poem, two parts.

05:32:30.920 --> 05:32:37.840
Jerusalem headlines 2000, Holy
Land experiences biggest snowfall

05:32:37.840 --> 05:32:40.010
in 50 years.

05:32:40.010 --> 05:32:41.850
Having been there for
the previous two biggest,

05:32:41.850 --> 05:32:46.760
I felt a lot of images
coming over me.

05:32:46.760 --> 05:32:48.910
If your house is covered,

05:32:48.910 --> 05:32:52.620
if someone's small lemon tree
disappears under a drift,

05:32:52.620 --> 05:32:57.910
if your auto with the blue
license plates, if your goat

05:32:57.910 --> 05:33:01.970
or my aged donkey, if the clay jar
in which your mother hold water

05:33:01.970 --> 05:33:05.240
for 60 years, if the snow piles

05:33:05.240 --> 05:33:10.580
up past everyone's
windows, all of the windows.

05:33:10.580 --> 05:33:17.770 position:56%
Palestinians and Israeli's worked
together in the west bank to rescue.

05:33:17.770 --> 05:33:22.600
A sweeter sentence than
baklava, than all the oranges

05:33:22.600 --> 05:33:27.600
of Jericho offered up to God.

05:33:27.600 --> 05:33:36.190
Second headline, top Israeli
official hints at shared Jerusalem.

05:33:36.190 --> 05:33:39.470
After all this time, just a hint.

05:33:39.470 --> 05:33:44.830
He could sing it loudly,
gent from the top of a wall,

05:33:44.830 --> 05:33:48.030
he's a top official after all.

05:33:48.030 --> 05:33:51.510
Why whisper, why not stand
in the street bursting

05:33:51.510 --> 05:33:54.740
with syllables shocking taxi
drivers and bread sellers,

05:33:54.740 --> 05:33:58.780
why not, why not, why not?

05:33:58.780 --> 05:34:03.160
Does a mother hint that
she loves her child?

05:34:03.160 --> 05:34:09.130
Now, while we are fresh, while the
century is still a wide open page,

05:34:09.130 --> 05:34:15.370
now a new story to be made and
everyone with their fragrant nouns

05:34:15.370 --> 05:34:19.540
and muscular verbs to write it.

05:34:21.690 --> 05:34:25.900
And on behalf of the Internet, I
feel like I keep finding out a lot

05:34:25.900 --> 05:34:29.020
of intriguing things
from the Internet

05:34:29.020 --> 05:34:31.490
that I appreciate knowing about.

05:34:31.490 --> 05:34:37.310
And this was one of them, <i>The
Many Hats of William Yale </i>.

05:34:37.310 --> 05:34:43.380
I love odd collections, cookie
jars, light bulbs toothpaste tubes,

05:34:43.380 --> 05:34:47.390
the man who gathered sugar
packets for 37 years.

05:34:47.390 --> 05:34:52.480
So when I heard about the hats made
from rinds of lemons and limes,

05:34:52.480 --> 05:34:57.740
a century ago decorated
with bits of frill and cloth

05:34:57.740 --> 05:35:01.620
to represent the tribes and
occupations of the time.

05:35:01.620 --> 05:35:08.070
I loved William Yale, the strange
gift for his Jerusalem bride.

05:35:08.070 --> 05:35:12.060
I sent my Boston friends
to see those hats.

05:35:12.060 --> 05:35:13.390
They got lost driving there

05:35:13.390 --> 05:35:17.270
in a wild rainstorm,
more lost coming home.

05:35:17.270 --> 05:35:21.610
But they reported the hats
made by children's hands,

05:35:21.610 --> 05:35:27.430
lined up teeny tiny, displayed
on thimbles and walnuts,

05:35:27.430 --> 05:35:30.470
were withered only a
bit around the edges

05:35:30.470 --> 05:35:35.080
as any rind might be after so long.

05:35:35.080 --> 05:35:37.460
And they felt hypnotized.

05:35:37.460 --> 05:35:43.060
A sudden tangy hopefulness rose up
from those hats, a stunning wish

05:35:43.060 --> 05:35:47.080
for women and men with tinier heads

05:35:47.080 --> 05:35:50.520
to solve Jerusalem's
troubles [laughter].

05:35:52.120 --> 05:35:58.390 position:56%
And back to Poetry in America in the
schools, I'll close with <i>Valentine</i>

05:35:58.390 --> 05:36:04.050
<i>for Ernest Mann </i>for the boy who
stalked up to me in the hallway

05:36:04.050 --> 05:36:07.430
of his junior high school and said,

05:36:07.430 --> 05:36:13.480
"If you are the poet,
write me a poem."

05:36:13.480 --> 05:36:17.960
And it was February 14.

05:36:19.020 --> 05:36:23.120
You can't order a poem
like you order a taco.

05:36:23.120 --> 05:36:26.410
Walk up to the counter
and say, I'll take two,

05:36:26.410 --> 05:36:29.920
and expect it to be
handed on a shiny plate.

05:36:29.920 --> 05:36:32.870
Still, I like your spirit.

05:36:32.870 --> 05:36:38.970
Anyone who says, here's my
address, write me a poem,

05:36:38.970 --> 05:36:41.480
deserves something in reply.

05:36:41.480 --> 05:36:43.750
So I'll tell a secret instead.

05:36:43.750 --> 05:36:48.280
Poems hide, in the bottoms of
our shoes they're sleeping;

05:36:48.280 --> 05:36:49.580
they are the shadows drifting

05:36:49.580 --> 05:36:53.680
across our ceilings the
moment before we wake up.

05:36:53.680 --> 05:36:58.260
What we have to do is live in
a way that lets us find them.

05:36:58.260 --> 05:37:03.420
Once I knew a man who gave his
wife two skunks for a valentine,

05:37:03.420 --> 05:37:06.480
he couldn't understand
why she was crying.

05:37:06.480 --> 05:37:12.860
I thought they had such
beautiful eyes and he was serious.

05:37:12.860 --> 05:37:17.100
He was a serious man who lived in a
serious way; nothing was ugly just

05:37:17.100 --> 05:37:19.860
because the world said so.

05:37:19.860 --> 05:37:22.900
He really liked those skunks.

05:37:22.900 --> 05:37:25.220
So he reinvented them as valentines

05:37:25.220 --> 05:37:29.710
and they became beautiful,
at least to him.

05:37:29.710 --> 05:37:32.670
And the poems that had been
hiding in the eyes of skunks

05:37:32.670 --> 05:37:38.190
for centuries crawled out
and curled up at his feet.

05:37:38.190 --> 05:37:43.700
Maybe if we reinvent whatever
our lives give us, we find poems.

05:37:43.700 --> 05:37:47.860
Check your garage, the
odd sock in your drawer,

05:37:47.860 --> 05:37:54.540
the person you almost like,
but not quite and let me know.

05:37:54.540 --> 05:37:57.000
And I'd have to say to
all of you here today,

05:37:57.000 --> 05:37:58.680
you let us know in a big way.

05:37:58.680 --> 05:38:00.480
Thanks.

05:38:00.480 --> 05:38:16.010
[ Applause ]

05:38:16.010 --> 05:38:19.160
[ Silence ]

05:38:19.160 --> 05:38:21.570
&gt;&gt; Robert Pinsky: I'm going
to try to read the first poem

05:38:21.570 --> 05:38:26.600
and the last poem from my brand
new book called <i>Jersey Rain </i>.

05:38:26.600 --> 05:38:29.800
They are short.

05:38:32.670 --> 05:38:40.110
Samurai song, when I had no
roof, I made audacity my roof.

05:38:40.110 --> 05:38:48.680 position:56%
When I had no supper, my eyes dined.

05:38:48.680 --> 05:38:51.680
When I had no eyes, I listened.

05:38:51.680 --> 05:38:57.010
When I had no ears, I sought.

05:38:57.010 --> 05:39:00.060
When I had no thought, I waited.

05:39:00.060 --> 05:39:06.700
When I had no father,
I made care my father.

05:39:06.700 --> 05:39:12.020
When I had no mother,
I embraced order.

05:39:12.020 --> 05:39:17.880
When I had no friend,
I made quiet my friend.

05:39:17.880 --> 05:39:24.130
When I had no enemy,
I posed my body.

05:39:24.130 --> 05:39:34.200
When I had no temple, I
made my voice my temple.

05:39:34.200 --> 05:39:35.500
[Inaudible] before.

05:39:35.500 --> 05:39:39.240
I have no priest, my
tongue is my choir.

05:39:39.240 --> 05:39:45.210
When I have no means,
fortune is my means.

05:39:45.210 --> 05:39:50.310
When I have nothing,
death will be my fortune.

05:39:50.310 --> 05:39:56.590
Need is my tactic,
detachment is my strategy.

05:39:56.590 --> 05:40:01.930
When I had to lover,
I courted my sleep.

05:40:05.990 --> 05:40:09.350
Last poem is the title
poem, <i>Jersey Rain </i>.

05:40:09.350 --> 05:40:20.310
Now near the end of the middle
of the road, now near the end

05:40:20.310 --> 05:40:25.290
of the middle stretch of
road, what have I learned?

05:40:25.290 --> 05:40:31.970 position:56%
Some earthly wiles that aren't, that
often I cannot tell good fortune

05:40:31.970 --> 05:40:38.860
from bad; they had once
seemed so easy to tell apart.

05:40:38.860 --> 05:40:44.020
The source of art and woe,
a slant in wind, dissolves

05:40:44.020 --> 05:40:47.740
or nourishes everything it touches.

05:40:47.740 --> 05:40:51.220
What [inaudible] doesn't mend;

05:40:51.220 --> 05:40:55.500
it carves the deeper,
boiling pony images.

05:40:55.500 --> 05:41:02.400
It spins itself regardless into
the ocean, it stains and scours

05:41:02.400 --> 05:41:06.350
and makes things dark or bright.

05:41:06.350 --> 05:41:10.670
Sweat of the moon, a
shroud of benediction,

05:41:10.670 --> 05:41:14.650
the chilly liquefaction
of day to night.

05:41:14.650 --> 05:41:20.120
The Jersey rain, my
rain, soaks all as one.

05:41:20.120 --> 05:41:25.550
It smites Metuchen, Rahway,
Saddle River, Fair Haven,

05:41:25.550 --> 05:41:30.250
Newark, Little Silver, Bayonne.

05:41:30.250 --> 05:41:33.620
I feel it churning
even in fair weather

05:41:33.620 --> 05:41:38.870
to craze distinction,
dry the same as wet.

05:41:38.870 --> 05:41:43.130
In ripples of heat, the August
drought still feeds vapors

05:41:43.130 --> 05:41:47.830
in the sky that swell
to drench my state.

05:41:47.830 --> 05:41:54.360 position:56%
The Jersey rain, my rain, in streams
and beads of indissoluble grudge

05:41:54.360 --> 05:42:01.400
and aspiration, original
milk, replenisher of grief.

05:42:01.400 --> 05:42:09.810 position:56%
Descending destroyer, [inaudible]
source of passion, silver and black,

05:42:09.810 --> 05:42:15.510
executioner, source of life.

05:42:15.510 --> 05:42:34.010
[ Applause ]

05:42:34.010 --> 05:42:40.410
[ Silence ]

05:42:40.410 --> 05:42:43.100
&gt;&gt; Rita Dove: I'd really like to
hear another round of applause

05:42:43.100 --> 05:42:47.500
for everything that Robert Pinsky
has done here at the library.

05:42:47.500 --> 05:42:51.110
It's been -- it's been
just a remarkable two days

05:42:51.110 --> 05:42:52.460
and a remarkable three years.

05:42:52.460 --> 05:42:54.260
I want to thank him.

05:42:54.260 --> 05:43:07.930
[ Applause ]

05:43:07.930 --> 05:43:12.000
I'd like to start with a
poem for sentimental reasons.

05:43:12.000 --> 05:43:17.730
It's for my daughter and she
kind of grew up in these halls.

05:43:17.730 --> 05:43:20.580
She knew every elevator
here, between the --

05:43:20.580 --> 05:43:23.960 position:56%
and the tunnels between the Madison
Building and the Jefferson Building.

05:43:23.960 --> 05:43:31.780 position:56%
This poem took a long to write, it's
in my latest book, but it's a poem

05:43:31.780 --> 05:43:34.580
about her birth and now she's 17.

05:43:34.580 --> 05:43:37.030
And she's given me
permission to read it.

05:43:37.030 --> 05:43:41.070
You have to ask at a
certain age [laughter].

05:43:44.360 --> 05:43:47.330
She was born in Phoenix, Arizona

05:43:50.540 --> 05:43:54.580 position:56%
and we weren't sure exactly how this
experiment was going to come out.

05:43:54.580 --> 05:43:58.780
It came out pretty
well, but we took --

05:43:58.780 --> 05:44:01.400
we had a good omen in
our -- in our midwife.

05:44:01.400 --> 05:44:04.600
We did the safe way, we had
midwives in the hospital so that

05:44:04.600 --> 05:44:06.790
in case something goes
wrong, you can pretend

05:44:06.790 --> 05:44:08.610
that you were doing it naturally.

05:44:08.610 --> 05:44:12.140
But our midwife was
a remarkable woman,

05:44:12.140 --> 05:44:16.300
we could not quite
figure out what she was.

05:44:16.300 --> 05:44:18.350
And that'll become
clear in the poem.

05:44:18.350 --> 05:44:24.560
<i>Incarnation in Phoenix </i>--
Into this paradise of pain,

05:44:24.560 --> 05:44:29.230
she strives on the slim
tether of a nurse's bell.

05:44:29.230 --> 05:44:33.100
Her charcoal limbs
emerging from crisp whites,

05:44:33.100 --> 05:44:37.150
unlikely as an envelope
issuing smoke.

05:44:37.150 --> 05:44:42.610
I've rung because my breasts have
risen, [inaudible] I'm not ready

05:44:42.610 --> 05:44:45.300
for this motherhood stuff.

05:44:45.300 --> 05:44:50.340
Her name is Raven and she swoops
across the tiled wilderness,

05:44:50.340 --> 05:44:52.960
hair boiling thunder
over the rampart

05:44:52.960 --> 05:44:56.880
of bobby pins poking
her immaculate cap.

05:44:56.880 --> 05:45:01.490
She dips once for the baby
just waking, fists punching

05:45:01.490 --> 05:45:04.350
in for work, right on schedule.

05:45:04.350 --> 05:45:08.390
Bends again to investigate
what should be natural,

05:45:08.390 --> 05:45:13.880
milk sighing into one
tiny [inaudible] mouth.

05:45:13.880 --> 05:45:19.560
Ah, she whispers, ambrosia,
shaming me instantly.

05:45:19.560 --> 05:45:23.540
But no nectar trickles forth,
no mana descends from the vault

05:45:23.540 --> 05:45:26.960
of Heaven to feed this
pearly syllable,

05:45:26.960 --> 05:45:30.170
this package of leafy
persuasion dropped

05:45:30.170 --> 05:45:33.290
on our doorstep and
ripening before us.

05:45:33.290 --> 05:45:39.810 position:56%
A miniature United Nations just
like me, Raven says, citing the name

05:45:39.810 --> 05:45:42.770
of her mother's village
somewhere in Norway,

05:45:42.770 --> 05:45:46.040
her father a buffalo soldier.

05:45:46.040 --> 05:45:52.650 position:56%
Now of course, we can place her, and
African Valkyrie who takes my breast

05:45:52.650 --> 05:45:56.920
in her fists grunting, this
hurts you more than it does me.

05:45:56.920 --> 05:46:04.000
Then my laugh squeezed to
whimper and the milk running out.

05:46:06.390 --> 05:46:10.850 position:56%
The -- I'd like to read one poem
from the title sequence of the book,

05:46:10.850 --> 05:46:14.010
<i>On The Bus With Rosa Parks</i>
, is the title of the book.

05:46:14.010 --> 05:46:19.260 position:56%
And this poem is about -- not about
Rosa Parks and that historic moment,

05:46:19.260 --> 05:46:22.600
but by about another
woman in a moment

05:46:22.600 --> 05:46:26.400
that by all rights could have
been the historic moment.

05:46:26.400 --> 05:46:32.020 position:56%
There were several women who refused
to give up their seats on the bus --

05:46:32.020 --> 05:46:36.660
on the buses in Montgomery,
Alabama in the year of 1955,

05:46:36.660 --> 05:46:40.060
which was the year that Rosa
Parks made her historic stand.

05:46:40.060 --> 05:46:44.500
And for various reasons, they
were not taken up as the test case

05:46:44.500 --> 05:46:48.000
for the anti -- for
the segregation laws --

05:46:48.000 --> 05:46:50.070
against the segregation laws.

05:46:50.070 --> 05:46:52.580
This woman's name was
-- that I'm reading

05:46:52.580 --> 05:46:56.020
about in this poem
is Claudette Colvin,

05:46:56.020 --> 05:46:59.920
who now works in a
nursing home in New York

05:46:59.920 --> 05:47:03.710
and she has been interviewed

05:47:03.710 --> 05:47:06.390
and people have asked her how
she felt not being Rosa Parks

05:47:06.390 --> 05:47:10.390
and she's truly bewildered
by this question as --

05:47:10.390 --> 05:47:16.100
as if what she is is
not something already.

05:47:16.100 --> 05:47:19.960
There's an epigraph for this
poem from the boycott flier

05:47:19.960 --> 05:47:24.810
that was distributed a few
days after Rose Park's arrest.

05:47:24.810 --> 05:47:29.050
And I quote, "Another Negro woman
has been arrested and thrown

05:47:29.050 --> 05:47:32.820
into jail because she refused to
get up out of her seat on the bus

05:47:32.820 --> 05:47:34.510
and give it to a white person."

05:47:34.510 --> 05:47:37.400
This is the second time since
the Claudette Colvin case,

05:47:37.400 --> 05:47:40.100
this must be stopped.

05:47:40.100 --> 05:47:42.820
Claudette Colvin goes to work.

05:47:44.240 --> 05:47:48.300
Menial twilight sweeps the
storefronts along Lexington,

05:47:48.300 --> 05:47:52.170
as the shadows arrive to take
their places among the scourge

05:47:52.170 --> 05:47:53.600
of the earth.

05:47:53.600 --> 05:47:57.540
Here and there, a fickle
brilliance, light bulbs coming

05:47:57.540 --> 05:48:01.240
on in each narrow residence,
the golden wattage

05:48:01.240 --> 05:48:05.290
of bleak interiors
announcing, anyone home

05:48:05.290 --> 05:48:09.090
or I'm beat, bring me a beer.

05:48:09.090 --> 05:48:15.480
Mostly I say to myself, still
here, lay my keys on the table,

05:48:15.480 --> 05:48:20.190
pack the perishables away
before flipping the switch.

05:48:20.190 --> 05:48:23.610
I like the sugary look
of things in bad light,

05:48:23.610 --> 05:48:26.080
one drop of sweat is
all it would take

05:48:26.080 --> 05:48:31.460
to dissolve an armchair
pillow into brocade residue.

05:48:31.460 --> 05:48:36.650
Sometimes I wait until it's dark
enough for my body to disappear,

05:48:36.650 --> 05:48:39.840
then I know it's time
to start out for work.

05:48:39.840 --> 05:48:44.380
Along the avenue, the cabs
start up heading toward midtown.

05:48:44.380 --> 05:48:49.780
Neon stutters into ecstasy as the
male integers light up their smokes

05:48:49.780 --> 05:48:53.040
and let loose a stream
of brave talk.

05:48:53.040 --> 05:48:58.390
Hey mama, souring quickly to
your mama when there's no answer.

05:48:58.390 --> 05:49:03.210
As if the most injury they can do
is insult the reason you're here

05:49:03.210 --> 05:49:06.970
at all, walking in your
whites down to the stock,

05:49:06.970 --> 05:49:09.100
so you can make a living.

05:49:09.100 --> 05:49:14.390
So ugly, so fat, so dumb,
so greasy, what do we have

05:49:14.390 --> 05:49:17.130
to do to make God love us?

05:49:17.130 --> 05:49:21.290
Mama was a maid, my daddy
mowed lawns like a boy

05:49:21.290 --> 05:49:24.150
and I'm the crazy girl off
the bus, the one who wrote

05:49:24.150 --> 05:49:27.690
in class she was going
to be president.

05:49:27.690 --> 05:49:31.880
I take the number six bus to
the Lexington Avenue train

05:49:31.880 --> 05:49:33.880
and then I'm there all night,

05:49:33.880 --> 05:49:38.100
adjusting the sheets,
emptying the pans.

05:49:38.100 --> 05:49:41.820
And I don't curse or
spit, or kick and scratch

05:49:41.820 --> 05:49:44.480
like they say I did then.

05:49:44.480 --> 05:49:48.090
I help those who can't
help themselves.

05:49:48.090 --> 05:49:50.630
I do what needs to be done.

05:49:50.630 --> 05:49:57.780
And I sleep whenever
sleep comes down on me.

05:49:57.780 --> 05:50:05.150
Two newish poems -- I've been
working a series about the painter,

05:50:05.150 --> 05:50:08.560
Albrecht Durer, for as long
as I think I've been writing.

05:50:08.560 --> 05:50:10.560
I can't seem to finish it.

05:50:10.560 --> 05:50:16.640
He intrigues me I think because he
was on the cusp of the Renaissance

05:50:16.640 --> 05:50:20.900
and it fascinated me to
think of someone who knew

05:50:20.900 --> 05:50:24.320
that something new was happening,
but didn't quite know what it was.

05:50:24.320 --> 05:50:26.330
He was early for his times.

05:50:26.330 --> 05:50:34.060
He wrote a painter's manual, which
is extremely post modern, actually.

05:50:34.060 --> 05:50:36.400 position:56%
I have a quote from it in which just

05:50:36.400 --> 05:50:38.820
to give you an idea of
how his mind worked.

05:50:38.820 --> 05:50:42.290
He said, I [inaudible] my
imagination throw a point high

05:50:42.290 --> 05:50:45.200
up in the air or drop
it into the depths

05:50:45.200 --> 05:50:47.460
where I cannot reach
it with my body.

05:50:47.460 --> 05:50:51.510
But in order to make it plausible,
I must draw it with a pen

05:50:51.510 --> 05:50:58.130 position:56%
and write the word point next to it,
so that the point will mean point.

05:50:58.130 --> 05:51:05.950
This man, I mean, 15th Century was
not for him, but he also thought

05:51:05.950 --> 05:51:09.750
that perhaps you could
quantify human beauty

05:51:09.750 --> 05:51:11.860
if you just measured it enough.

05:51:11.860 --> 05:51:14.460
And this became a lifelong
obsession.

05:51:14.460 --> 05:51:16.910
This poem takes place
right about at the turn

05:51:16.910 --> 05:51:22.320
of his millennium into the 1500s.

05:51:22.320 --> 05:51:25.260
And it's called <i>Weltschmerz</i>
, which is German for --

05:51:25.260 --> 05:51:30.050
well, it means world pain, but
that doesn't -- that's nothing.

05:51:30.050 --> 05:51:32.980
It means really, a longing
that you can't put a finger

05:51:32.980 --> 05:51:34.850
on that's bigger than the world.

05:51:34.850 --> 05:51:40.740
<i>Weltschmerz </i>, You who refer
to your wife as my good Agnes,

05:51:40.740 --> 05:51:44.390
and always in connection with
the maid, a simple girl who cried

05:51:44.390 --> 05:51:48.150
out in the midst of a miracle,
crosses dropped from the sky

05:51:48.150 --> 05:51:51.320
onto the clean white
shirts of her master.

05:51:51.320 --> 05:51:55.210
What could you say to a
creature so devoid of irony,

05:51:55.210 --> 05:52:00.110
she couldn't even laugh when you
yelled, come out of the rain.

05:52:00.110 --> 05:52:06.850 position:56%
Still, the centuries fresh, three
days journey to view a beached whale

05:52:06.850 --> 05:52:11.350
and by the time you arrive, the
whale has been swept to sea again.

05:52:11.350 --> 05:52:15.890 position:56%
You stay awhile anyway, collect
rocks, sketch a [inaudible] so plump

05:52:15.890 --> 05:52:20.410
and shy, she won't lift her
eyes from your hot nailed boots.

05:52:20.410 --> 05:52:23.330
Morosity, you write, is the penalty

05:52:23.330 --> 05:52:27.150
for too much thought
without exercise.

05:52:27.150 --> 05:52:31.660 position:56%
So you dig dame sorrow out of
metal, carve her slouched among orbs

05:52:31.660 --> 05:52:35.570
and compasses, swathed
in grim drapery and yet,

05:52:35.570 --> 05:52:38.110
it is your jaw etched in fury,

05:52:38.110 --> 05:52:44.320
our gaze you find burning
beneath her extravagant curls.

05:52:44.320 --> 05:52:46.560
What goes up, must come down.

05:52:46.560 --> 05:52:49.930
The maid saw that with
her own silly eyes.

05:52:49.930 --> 05:52:55.230
Throw up your hands, put it down
on paper, in ink, what can you say

05:52:55.230 --> 05:53:00.780
to a woman who refuses to pose
nude even for a famous artist?

05:53:00.780 --> 05:53:05.970
Gather up your stones, your crab
carapace's, your smudged equations

05:53:05.970 --> 05:53:10.400
for human perfection and
remember a green broach

05:53:10.400 --> 05:53:13.280
for the melancholy Agnes.

05:53:15.250 --> 05:53:23.260
This poem is -- I kind of date the
new poems as post-fire or pre-fire.

05:53:23.260 --> 05:53:26.400 position:56%
Some of you might know we had a fire
in our house, lightening struck it

05:53:26.400 --> 05:53:28.020
and burned quite a bit of it.

05:53:28.020 --> 05:53:32.100
And it -- contrary -- I
mean it was devastating,

05:53:32.100 --> 05:53:35.730
but contrary to what I always
imagined when I looked at disaster

05:53:35.730 --> 05:53:38.600
on television and you
think how unspeakably sad,

05:53:38.600 --> 05:53:41.250
it has been a process or recovery.

05:53:41.250 --> 05:53:44.150
What you do discover is
that you find things again

05:53:44.150 --> 05:53:48.020
and everything that
you find is a gift.

05:53:48.020 --> 05:53:50.220
As a consequence, I've
started writing poems

05:53:50.220 --> 05:53:53.310
which I guess some critic
will say predictably enough,

05:53:53.310 --> 05:53:58.450
are poems about paradise,
Adam and Eve.

05:53:58.450 --> 05:54:02.190
This is one of Eve's, of
a quote from the Bible,

05:54:02.190 --> 05:54:04.960
I have been a stranger
in a strange land

05:54:04.960 --> 05:54:07.500
and an epigraph from
Emily Dickenson.

05:54:07.500 --> 05:54:12.670
Life's spell is so exquisite,
everything conspires to break it.

05:54:12.670 --> 05:54:18.360
It wasn't bliss, what was
bliss but the ordinary life.

05:54:18.360 --> 05:54:22.690
She's spend hours in patter moving
through whole days touching,

05:54:22.690 --> 05:54:28.230
sniffing, tasting, exquisite
housekeeping in a charmed world.

05:54:28.230 --> 05:54:30.920
And yet there was always
more of the same,

05:54:30.920 --> 05:54:35.500
all that happiness, the
aimless being there.

05:54:35.500 --> 05:54:40.030
So she wandered for awhile,
bush to arbor, linger to look

05:54:40.030 --> 05:54:43.240
through upons rest of mirror.

05:54:43.240 --> 05:54:47.100
He was off cataloguing the universe
probably pretending he could

05:54:47.100 --> 05:54:51.660
organize what was clearly
someone else's chaos.

05:54:51.660 --> 05:54:55.550
That's when she found the tree,
the dark crabbed branches bearing

05:54:55.550 --> 05:54:57.920
up such speechless bounty.

05:54:57.920 --> 05:55:02.200
She knew without being
told, this was forbidden.

05:55:02.200 --> 05:55:06.520
It wasn't a question of
ownership, who could lay claim

05:55:06.520 --> 05:55:09.410
to such maddening perfection.

05:55:09.410 --> 05:55:13.930
And there was no voice in her head,
no whispered intelligence lurking

05:55:13.930 --> 05:55:17.120
in the leaves, just
an ache that grew

05:55:17.120 --> 05:55:22.620
until she knew she'd already
lost everything except desire.

05:55:22.620 --> 05:55:27.140
The red heft of it warming
her outstretched paw.

05:55:27.140 --> 05:55:29.510
Thank you.

05:55:29.510 --> 05:55:34.010
[ Applause ]

05:55:34.010 --> 05:55:36.010
[ Silence ]

05:55:36.010 --> 05:55:37.870
[ Applause ]

05:55:37.870 --> 05:55:42.670
&gt;&gt; Louise Gluck: Now a
foreseeable end, but it --

05:55:42.670 --> 05:55:50.540
it treats the different periods
of a life, youth, adolescence,

05:55:50.540 --> 05:55:58.590
theoretic life, domestic
life and old age.

05:55:58.590 --> 05:56:06.140
As a -- in a kind of swirl
of associative patterns,

05:56:06.140 --> 05:56:09.360
you won't be able to get
that from a smattering,

05:56:09.360 --> 05:56:12.670
but I'll read a few of these poems.

05:56:12.670 --> 05:56:22.210
The sensual world, I call to you
across a monstrous river or chasm

05:56:22.210 --> 05:56:26.330
to caution you, to prepare you.

05:56:26.330 --> 05:56:32.800
Earth will seduce you,
slowly, inperceptibly, subtly,

05:56:32.800 --> 05:56:35.320
not to say with connivance.

05:56:35.320 --> 05:56:42.170
I was not prepared, I stood in
my grandmother's kitchen holding

05:56:42.170 --> 05:56:49.020
out my glass, stewed plums, stewed
apricots, the juice poured off

05:56:49.020 --> 05:56:56.360 position:56%
into the glass of ice and the water
added patiently in small increments,

05:56:56.360 --> 05:57:03.250
the various cousins discriminating,
tasting with each addition.

05:57:03.250 --> 05:57:08.730
Aroma of summer fruit,
intensity of concentration,

05:57:08.730 --> 05:57:13.270
the colored liquid turning
gradually lighter, more radiant,

05:57:13.270 --> 05:57:16.740
more light passing through it.

05:57:16.740 --> 05:57:26.360 position:56%
Delight, then solace, my grandmother
waiting to see if more was wanted,

05:57:26.360 --> 05:57:31.390
solace then deep immersion.

05:57:31.390 --> 05:57:37.420
I loved nothing more, deep
privacy of the sensual life,

05:57:37.420 --> 05:57:42.180
the self disappearing into
it or inseparable from it,

05:57:42.180 --> 05:57:45.140
somehow suspended, floating,

05:57:45.140 --> 05:57:50.500
its needs fully exposed,
awakened, fully alive.

05:57:50.500 --> 05:57:58.330
Deep immersion and with
it, mysterious safety,

05:57:58.330 --> 05:58:02.550
far away the fruit
glowing in its glass bowls,

05:58:02.550 --> 05:58:06.700 position:56%
outside the kitchen the sun setting.

05:58:06.700 --> 05:58:14.200
I was not prepared, sunset, end
of summer, demonstrations of time

05:58:14.200 --> 05:58:20.220
as a continuum as something coming
to an end, not a suspension.

05:58:20.220 --> 05:58:23.990
The senses wouldn't protect me.

05:58:23.990 --> 05:58:27.800
I caution you as I
was never cautioned.

05:58:27.800 --> 05:58:32.400
You will never let go, you
will never be satiated,

05:58:32.400 --> 05:58:37.160
you will be damaged and scarred,
you will continue to hunger.

05:58:37.160 --> 05:58:40.750
Your body will age, you
will continue to need,

05:58:40.750 --> 05:58:48.450
you will want the earth then more
of the earth, sublime, indifferent,

05:58:48.450 --> 05:58:53.910
it is present, it will not
respond, it is encompassing,

05:58:53.910 --> 05:59:00.660
it will not minister, meaning it
will feed you, it will ravish you,

05:59:00.660 --> 05:59:07.630
it will not keep you alive.

05:59:07.630 --> 05:59:16.630
Solstice -- each year on the same
date, the summer solstice comes.

05:59:16.630 --> 05:59:21.590
[Inaudible] light, we plan for
it, the day we tell ourselves

05:59:21.590 --> 05:59:28.800
that time is very long indeed,
nearly infinite and in our reading

05:59:28.800 --> 05:59:36.250
and writing, preference is given
to the celebratory, the ecstatic.

05:59:36.250 --> 05:59:40.760
There is in these rituals
something apart from wonder,

05:59:40.760 --> 05:59:47.060 position:56%
there is also a kind of preening, as
though human genius had participated

05:59:47.060 --> 05:59:53.760
in these arrangements and we
found the results satisfying.

05:59:53.760 --> 05:59:57.020
What follows the light
is what precedes it.

05:59:57.020 --> 06:00:04.010
The moment of balance, of dark
equivalence, but tonight we sit

06:00:04.010 --> 06:00:09.920
in the garden in our canvas
chairs, so late into the evening.

06:00:09.920 --> 06:00:16.080 position:56%
Why should we look either forward
or backward, why should we be forced

06:00:16.080 --> 06:00:21.310
to remember it is in our
blood, this knowledge?

06:00:21.310 --> 06:00:27.960
Shortness of the days, darkness,
coldness of winter it is

06:00:27.960 --> 06:00:33.090
in our blood and bones,
it is in our history,

06:00:33.090 --> 06:00:38.170
it takes genius to
forget these things.

06:00:41.080 --> 06:00:47.780
Stars -- I'm awake,
I am in the world.

06:00:47.780 --> 06:00:55.710
I expect no further assurance,
no protection, no promise.

06:00:55.710 --> 06:01:05.800 position:56%
Solace of the night sky, the hardly
moving face of the clock, I'm alone.

06:01:05.800 --> 06:01:09.170
All my riches surround me.

06:01:09.170 --> 06:01:17.400
I have a bed, a room, I have a
bed, a vase of flowers beside it,

06:01:17.400 --> 06:01:20.950
and a nightlight, a book.

06:01:22.080 --> 06:01:26.270
I'm awake, I am safe.

06:01:26.270 --> 06:01:29.120
The darkness, like a shield.

06:01:29.120 --> 06:01:37.090
The dreams, put off, maybe
vanished forever and the day,

06:01:37.090 --> 06:01:43.650
the unsatisfying morning
that says, I am your future,

06:01:43.650 --> 06:01:47.190
here is your cargo of sorrow.

06:01:47.190 --> 06:01:49.640
Do you reject me?

06:01:49.640 --> 06:01:55.920
Do you mean to send me away
because I am not full in your word,

06:01:55.920 --> 06:02:01.180
because you see the black
shake already implicit.

06:02:01.180 --> 06:02:04.690
I will never be banished.

06:02:04.690 --> 06:02:06.500
I am the light.

06:02:06.500 --> 06:02:10.570
Your personal anguish
and humiliation,

06:02:10.570 --> 06:02:14.160
do you dare send me away
as though you were waiting

06:02:14.160 --> 06:02:17.130
for something better.

06:02:17.130 --> 06:02:23.590
There is no better,
only for a short space,

06:02:23.590 --> 06:02:31.470
the night sky like a quarantine
that sets you apart from your task.

06:02:31.470 --> 06:02:42.260
Only softly, fiercely, the star
is shining, here in the room,

06:02:42.260 --> 06:02:55.310
the bedroom, saying I was brave,
I resisted, I set myself on fire.

06:02:55.310 --> 06:03:03.180
Youth -- my sister and I at
two ends of the sofa reading,

06:03:03.180 --> 06:03:08.430
I suppose English novels,
the television on,

06:03:08.430 --> 06:03:14.670
various schoolbooks open or places
marked with sheets of lined paper.

06:03:14.670 --> 06:03:21.410
Euclid, [inaudible], as though
we had looked into the origin

06:03:21.410 --> 06:03:26.620
of thought and preferred novels.

06:03:26.620 --> 06:03:31.540
Sad sounds of our growing
up, twilight of cellos,

06:03:31.540 --> 06:03:37.950
no trace of a flute, a piccolo
and it seemed at the time,

06:03:37.950 --> 06:03:44.500
almost impossible to conceive of
any of it as evolving or malleable.

06:03:44.500 --> 06:03:52.200
Sad sounds, anecdotes that
were really still lives,

06:03:52.200 --> 06:03:58.990
the pages of the novels turning,
the two dogs snoring quietly

06:03:58.990 --> 06:04:03.940
and from the kitchen,
sounds of our mother,

06:04:03.940 --> 06:04:10.770 position:56%
smell of Rosemary, of lamb roasting.

06:04:10.770 --> 06:04:18.090
A world in process of shifting,
of being made or dissolved and

06:04:18.090 --> 06:04:21.230
yet we didn't live that way.

06:04:21.230 --> 06:04:28.690
All of us lived our lives as the
simultaneous ritualized enactment

06:04:28.690 --> 06:04:33.020
of a great principle, something
felt, but not understood.

06:04:33.020 --> 06:04:39.860
And the remarks we made were
like lines in a play spoken

06:04:39.860 --> 06:04:44.350
with conviction, but
not from choice.

06:04:44.350 --> 06:04:50.280
A principle, a terrifying familial
will that implied opposition

06:04:50.280 --> 06:04:57.030
to change, to variation, a
refusal even to ask questions.

06:04:57.030 --> 06:05:02.720
Now that world begins to
shift and eddy around us.

06:05:02.720 --> 06:05:08.920
Only now when it no longer
exists it has become the present,

06:05:08.920 --> 06:05:12.800
unending and without form.

06:05:12.800 --> 06:05:14.610
I'll read two more short ones.

06:05:14.610 --> 06:05:15.910
[Inaudible].

06:05:15.910 --> 06:05:26.270
I had drawn my chair to the
hotel window to watch the rain.

06:05:26.270 --> 06:05:37.550
I was in a kind of dream or trance,
in love, and yet I wanted nothing.

06:05:37.550 --> 06:05:44.940
It seemed unnecessary to
touch you, to see you again.

06:05:44.940 --> 06:05:50.530
I wanted only this,
the room, the chair,

06:05:50.530 --> 06:05:55.800
the sound of the rain
falling, hour after hour

06:05:55.800 --> 06:06:00.340
in the warmth of the spring night.

06:06:00.340 --> 06:06:02.770
I needed nothing more.

06:06:02.770 --> 06:06:06.470
I was utterly sated.

06:06:06.470 --> 06:06:09.760
My heart had become small.

06:06:09.760 --> 06:06:13.890
It took very little to fill it.

06:06:13.890 --> 06:06:19.450
I watch the rain falling in heavy
sheets over the darkened city.

06:06:19.450 --> 06:06:22.700
You were not concerned.

06:06:22.700 --> 06:06:26.460
I could let you live
as you needed to live.

06:06:26.460 --> 06:06:31.950
At dawn the rain abated.

06:06:31.950 --> 06:06:36.740
I did the things one does in
daylight, I acquitted myself,

06:06:36.740 --> 06:06:40.740
but I moved like a sleepwalker.

06:06:40.740 --> 06:06:46.290
It was enough and it
no longer involved you.

06:06:46.290 --> 06:06:54.310
A few days in the strange city, a
conversation, a touch of a hand,

06:06:54.310 --> 06:07:00.710
and afterward I took
off my wedding ring,

06:07:00.710 --> 06:07:06.170 position:56%
that was what I wanted, to be naked.

06:07:06.170 --> 06:07:15.390
Time, there was too much
always and too little.

06:07:15.390 --> 06:07:19.110
Childhood, sickness.

06:07:19.110 --> 06:07:22.980
By the side of the bed
I had a little bell.

06:07:22.980 --> 06:07:28.520
At the other end of
the bell, my mother.

06:07:28.520 --> 06:07:34.960
Sickness, gray rain, the
dogs slept through it.

06:07:34.960 --> 06:07:37.820
They slept on the bed,
at the end of it,

06:07:37.820 --> 06:07:41.870
and it seemed to me they
understood about childhood,

06:07:41.870 --> 06:07:45.720
best to remain unconscious.

06:07:45.720 --> 06:07:49.870
The rain made gray
slats on the windows.

06:07:49.870 --> 06:07:54.580
I sat with my book, the
little bell beside me.

06:07:54.580 --> 06:08:01.040
Without hearing a voice, I
apprenticed myself to a voice.

06:08:01.040 --> 06:08:04.280
Without seeing any
sign of the spirit,

06:08:04.280 --> 06:08:09.430
I determined to live in the spirit.

06:08:09.430 --> 06:08:12.000
The rain faded in and out.

06:08:12.000 --> 06:08:15.500
Month after month in
the space of a day,

06:08:15.500 --> 06:08:22.170
things became dreams,
dreams became things.

06:08:22.170 --> 06:08:24.010
Then I was well.

06:08:24.010 --> 06:08:27.210
The bell went back to the cupboard.

06:08:27.210 --> 06:08:28.920
The rain ended.

06:08:28.920 --> 06:08:34.280
The dogs stood at the door,
panting to go outside.

06:08:34.280 --> 06:08:41.030
I was well, then I was an
adult and time went on.

06:08:41.030 --> 06:08:45.650
It was like the rain,
so much, so much,

06:08:45.650 --> 06:08:49.010
as though it was a weight
that couldn't be moved.

06:08:49.010 --> 06:08:53.580
I was a child, half sleeping.

06:08:53.580 --> 06:08:55.010
I was sick.

06:08:55.010 --> 06:08:56.310
I was protected.

06:08:56.310 --> 06:09:02.440
And I lived in the world of the
spirit, the world of the gray rain,

06:09:02.440 --> 06:09:08.970
the lost, the remembered, then
suddenly the sun was shining

06:09:08.970 --> 06:09:15.230
and time went on, even when
there was almost none left.

06:09:15.230 --> 06:09:19.470
And the perceived became
the remembered,

06:09:19.470 --> 06:09:22.550
the remembered the perceived.

06:09:22.550 --> 06:09:24.350
Thank you.

06:09:24.350 --> 06:09:43.010
[ Applause ]

06:09:43.010 --> 06:09:52.050
[ Silence ]

06:09:52.050 --> 06:09:57.030
&gt;&gt; W.S. Merwin: I'm going to
begin in a conventional way

06:09:57.030 --> 06:10:01.840
by thanking everyone whose been
responsible for this program

06:10:01.840 --> 06:10:04.160
in every sense of the word.

06:10:04.160 --> 06:10:07.220
This particular program,
and the marvelous things

06:10:07.220 --> 06:10:12.990
that have been said here, Robert's
favorite poetry project program,

06:10:12.990 --> 06:10:21.220
and what they have both shown and
what I believe that [inaudible]

06:10:21.220 --> 06:10:27.500
in the 6th Century, the
poem said of the mules,

06:10:27.500 --> 06:10:31.020
it is natural to love her.

06:10:31.020 --> 06:10:33.430
I believe that this is something
that we're all born with,

06:10:33.430 --> 06:10:36.170
and that we get educated
out of ourselves.

06:10:36.170 --> 06:10:40.730
Why that great [inaudible]
is so important.

06:10:40.730 --> 06:10:46.980
The children naturally love
poetry, and if they don't love it

06:10:46.980 --> 06:10:48.280
by the time they're adolescents,

06:10:48.280 --> 06:10:50.770
it is because something
wrong has happened,

06:10:50.770 --> 06:10:53.270
some derailment has come about.

06:10:53.270 --> 06:10:57.730
And then I wanted to thank
everyone responsible for my being

06:10:57.730 --> 06:11:02.370
on the platform with these
other poets, many dear friends

06:11:02.370 --> 06:11:06.000
and poet's who's work
I've loved for years.

06:11:06.000 --> 06:11:08.290
It's a great pleasure
anytime that anything

06:11:08.290 --> 06:11:10.580
of any chance for that happening.

06:11:10.580 --> 06:11:14.470
I'm going to read a
few poems, beginning --

06:11:14.470 --> 06:11:19.890
they're all short poems,
and they're -- they --

06:11:19.890 --> 06:11:24.420
going back to the book published
several books back called,

06:11:24.420 --> 06:11:28.880
<i>The Vixen </i>, which all of
the poems are in the same form

06:11:28.880 --> 06:11:32.690
and they're all related to the same
place, a different length in time

06:11:32.690 --> 06:11:34.800
and in other various respects.

06:11:34.800 --> 06:11:40.270
But I noticed that the poems that
I've chosen to read this evening,

06:11:40.270 --> 06:11:41.820
many of them have to
do with animals,

06:11:41.820 --> 06:11:43.370
and I suppose that's no accident,

06:11:43.370 --> 06:11:46.030
that's one of the great
sympathies of my life.

06:11:46.030 --> 06:11:50.000 position:56%
And one of the things that one
shares with other poets, by the way,

06:11:50.000 --> 06:11:53.810
is not necessarily animals,
but passion, a passion.

06:11:53.810 --> 06:11:59.260
And a passion that
I realize is a part

06:11:59.260 --> 06:12:02.230
of a lifelong romanticism of mine.

06:12:02.230 --> 06:12:05.490
I suppose I am a romantic
in many respects.

06:12:05.490 --> 06:12:11.920
But I believe that the poets
owe each other generosity,

06:12:11.920 --> 06:12:14.320
as much generosity
as they can muster.

06:12:14.320 --> 06:12:18.880
It's not -- it's never total
and it's [inaudible] sometimes.

06:12:18.880 --> 06:12:24.500
But it's for the rise from the fact
that they recognize in each other

06:12:24.500 --> 06:12:32.410 position:56%
that passion and that -- that
concern and gratitude for being able

06:12:32.410 --> 06:12:38.370 position:56%
to touch something so remarkable and
so beyond our own use of language.

06:12:38.370 --> 06:12:42.400
That's something we also, I
believe, share with many animals.

06:12:42.400 --> 06:12:43.700
Substance.

06:12:43.700 --> 06:12:53.170
I could see that there was a kind
of distance lighted behind the face

06:12:53.170 --> 06:12:57.120
of that time and it's very
days as they appeared to me,

06:12:57.120 --> 06:13:01.250
but I could not think of any words
that spoke of it truly nor point

06:13:01.250 --> 06:13:03.710
to anything except what was there

06:13:03.710 --> 06:13:06.900
at the moment it was
beginning to be gone.

06:13:06.900 --> 06:13:11.560 position:56%
And certainly it could not have
been proven nor held however I might

06:13:11.560 --> 06:13:14.940
reach toward it, touching
the warm likens,

06:13:14.940 --> 06:13:18.660
the features of the stones,
the skin of the river.

06:13:18.660 --> 06:13:22.290
And I could tell then that
it was the animals themselves

06:13:22.290 --> 06:13:26.100
that were the weight and place
of the hour as it happened.

06:13:26.100 --> 06:13:31.130
And that the mass of the cows
neck, the flash of the swallow,

06:13:31.130 --> 06:13:34.680
the trout's flutter were
where it was coming to pass,

06:13:34.680 --> 06:13:38.560
they were bearing the sense
of it without questions

06:13:38.560 --> 06:13:46.270
through the speechless
cloud of light.

06:13:46.270 --> 06:13:56.110
Totally different kind of poem
next is one of several city poems

06:13:56.110 --> 06:13:59.980
in the book that followed <i>The
Vixen </i>, <i>The River Sound </i>,

06:13:59.980 --> 06:14:04.280
a book of short poems that
followed <i>The Vixen </i>.

06:14:04.280 --> 06:14:08.570
This is about an apartment
that I lived in

06:14:08.570 --> 06:14:12.070
and that represented a very
important part of my life

06:14:12.070 --> 06:14:16.330
for a great many years,
and that I lost.

06:14:16.330 --> 06:14:18.620
That's a story in itself.

06:14:18.620 --> 06:14:22.090
Sixth Floor Walk Up.

06:14:22.090 --> 06:14:24.730
I was born in New York City
and this is in New York City.

06:14:24.730 --> 06:14:28.500
New York to me is the
[inaudible] city.

06:14:28.500 --> 06:14:31.180
I mean, to me, it's
the core of history.

06:14:31.180 --> 06:14:34.090
I mean, we're not -- we don't
live entirely in history,

06:14:34.090 --> 06:14:38.620
but nor do I live entirely
in New York [laughter], but.

06:14:38.620 --> 06:14:41.620
And sometimes I felt there was a
friend of mine who was also born

06:14:41.620 --> 06:14:43.870
in New York, said -- someone said,

06:14:43.870 --> 06:14:47.320
"Why if you notice all
these terrible things

06:14:47.320 --> 06:14:49.890
about it all the time, and
complain about it so much,

06:14:49.890 --> 06:14:51.190
why do you keep coming back?"

06:14:51.190 --> 06:14:53.510
And he said, "I hate it
better than anywhere else."

06:14:53.510 --> 06:14:58.730
[ Laughter ]

06:14:58.730 --> 06:15:02.660
Sixth Floor Walk Up.

06:15:02.660 --> 06:15:06.500
Past 4:00 in the afternoon,
the last day here,

06:15:06.500 --> 06:15:10.380
the winter light is draining out of
the sky to the east over the grays

06:15:10.380 --> 06:15:15.740 position:56%
of the roofs, over the tiered bricks
and dark water tanks, clock towers,

06:15:15.740 --> 06:15:19.700
aerials, penthouse
windows, rusted doors,

06:15:19.700 --> 06:15:22.730
bare trees and terrace gardens.

06:15:22.730 --> 06:15:27.500 position:56%
In the distance a plane is coming
in, lit by the slow burn of the sun,

06:15:27.500 --> 06:15:30.540
sinking two weeks before
the Solstice.

06:15:30.540 --> 06:15:35.040
And the lingering perfect autumn
still does not seem to be gone.

06:15:35.040 --> 06:15:40.110
The walls of the apartment and the
long mirrors are becoming shadows.

06:15:40.110 --> 06:15:44.570
The latest telephone already cut
off is huddled against the wall,

06:15:44.570 --> 06:15:46.870
with it's deaf predecessors.

06:15:46.870 --> 06:15:50.440
The movers have not
showed up for what is left.

06:15:50.440 --> 06:15:56.840 position:56%
Bare bed, bare tables, and the sofa,
the piled LP's, the great chair

06:15:56.840 --> 06:16:01.470
from which at this hour once I
called up a friend on Morton Street

06:16:01.470 --> 06:16:04.350
to tell him that all
the windows facing west

06:16:04.350 --> 06:16:08.200
down the avenue were
reflecting a red building flaming

06:16:08.200 --> 06:16:12.430
like a torch somewhere over
near the old post office

06:16:12.430 --> 06:16:14.530
on Christopher Street.

06:16:14.530 --> 06:16:18.560
The sirens were converging,
all the bells clanging,

06:16:18.560 --> 06:16:22.700
and the sky was clear as it is now.

06:16:22.700 --> 06:16:26.380
They're stacking Christmas
trees along the fence again

06:16:26.380 --> 06:16:29.640
down at the corner to
the music of the Subway

06:16:29.640 --> 06:16:33.340
under the avenue, on
it's way to Brooklyn.

06:16:33.340 --> 06:16:43.930
25 years. And then another -- one
other poem from <i>The River Sound </i>,

06:16:43.930 --> 06:16:50.320
and this is -- [inaudible] said
that for a poem to be real,

06:16:50.320 --> 06:16:52.270
this doesn't necessarily
mean it is true,

06:16:52.270 --> 06:16:54.320
but it's very interesting
to think about.

06:16:54.320 --> 06:16:58.370 position:56%
For a poem to be a real poem you had
to know what time of year it was.

06:16:58.370 --> 06:16:59.750
This is called Waves in August,

06:16:59.750 --> 06:17:06.470
so you cheat with the
title, you see [laughter].

06:17:06.470 --> 06:17:08.080
Waves in August.

06:17:08.080 --> 06:17:15.420
There is a war in the distance,
with the distance growing smaller.

06:17:15.420 --> 06:17:20.320
The field glasses lying at hand
are for keeping it far away.

06:17:20.320 --> 06:17:25.670
I thought I was getting better
about that returning childish wish

06:17:25.670 --> 06:17:30.130
to be living somewhere else
that I knew was impossible.

06:17:30.130 --> 06:17:35.930
And now I find myself wishing
to be here, to be alive here,

06:17:35.930 --> 06:17:40.600
and is it possible enough to
still be the wish of a child.

06:17:41.830 --> 06:17:45.430
In youth I hid a [inaudible]
under the bushes beside the water,

06:17:45.430 --> 06:17:51.540
knowing I want it later, and come
back and would find it there.

06:17:51.540 --> 06:17:56.870
Someone else took it and left me
instead the sound of the water

06:17:56.870 --> 06:18:00.880
with it's whisper of
vertigo, terror,

06:18:00.880 --> 06:18:05.620
reassurance, and old, old sadness.

06:18:05.620 --> 06:18:10.590
It would seem we knew
enough always about parting.

06:18:10.590 --> 06:18:15.960
But we have to go on learning
as long as there's anything.

06:18:17.950 --> 06:18:25.270
The rest of the poems that
I want to read are all

06:18:25.270 --> 06:18:29.490
from a new manuscript that's
just gone to the publisher.

06:18:29.490 --> 06:18:38.710
And there are a number -- quite
a few poems in the early part

06:18:38.710 --> 06:18:44.590
of that poem that have to do with
the night sky and day and night,

06:18:44.590 --> 06:18:46.690
light and darkness, time.

06:18:46.690 --> 06:18:54.970
And I want to read a short one
of those called Glassy Sea.

06:19:01.200 --> 06:19:04.920
As you see each of
the stars has a voice,

06:19:04.920 --> 06:19:09.470
and at least one long syllable
before words as we know them

06:19:09.470 --> 06:19:14.800
and can recall them later one by
one with their company around them.

06:19:14.800 --> 06:19:18.090
After the sound of them
has gone from its moment,

06:19:18.090 --> 06:19:21.110
even though we may say
it again and again,

06:19:21.110 --> 06:19:25.210
it is gone again, far
into our knowledge.

06:19:25.210 --> 06:19:30.230
There were words as we know for
whatever does not die with us,

06:19:30.230 --> 06:19:34.990
but the sound of those words
lasts no longer than the others.

06:19:34.990 --> 06:19:37.710
It is heard only for
part of the length

06:19:37.710 --> 06:19:42.510
of a breath among those
clear syllables never heard

06:19:42.510 --> 06:19:46.540
from which the words were
made in another time.

06:19:46.540 --> 06:19:50.650
And the syllables themselves
are not there forever.

06:19:50.650 --> 06:20:00.650
Some may go all the way to the
beginning, but not beyond it.

06:20:00.650 --> 06:20:08.770
I want to read a difficult
kind of poem.

06:20:08.770 --> 06:20:19.810
This evening Robert and I were
going to, but Robert is indisposed,

06:20:19.810 --> 06:20:23.760
his voice has left him, and
I'm going to have to do it.

06:20:23.760 --> 06:20:26.960
I'm going to have to
read [inaudible].

06:20:26.960 --> 06:20:33.420
And I think probably
the hardest subject --

06:20:33.420 --> 06:20:37.820
one of the hardest subjects to
get into poetry, to write about,

06:20:37.820 --> 06:20:42.730
properly and make a
poem of is anger.

06:20:42.730 --> 06:20:48.470
Dante [assumed spelling] was a
person who traveled through life

06:20:48.470 --> 06:20:53.550
with terrible anger, a great deal
of anger, and he dealt with it

06:20:53.550 --> 06:20:59.150
in various ways, some of them we
would think quite successfully

06:20:59.150 --> 06:21:00.450
in the [inaudible].

06:21:00.450 --> 06:21:05.890 position:56%
He dealt with it both in the inferno

06:21:05.890 --> 06:21:10.870
and in the purgatorial
quite differently.

06:21:10.870 --> 06:21:14.750 position:56%
He dealt with -- he was dealing
with his own anger at the same time.

06:21:14.750 --> 06:21:17.760
I will deal with mine as
well as I can in a minute

06:21:17.760 --> 06:21:19.560
if I can possibly find his poem

06:21:19.560 --> 06:21:23.700
[ Laughter ]

06:21:23.700 --> 06:21:25.830
I thought I knew where
it was, but --

06:21:25.830 --> 06:21:27.130
[ Inaudible Speaker ]

06:21:27.130 --> 06:21:31.130
No, I'm not, but [laughter]
I'm getting desperate.

06:21:31.130 --> 06:21:32.500
I know it's here.

06:21:32.500 --> 06:21:38.030
And I've said all I
wanted to say about it,

06:21:38.030 --> 06:21:40.950
so you'll [laughter]
have to bear with me.

06:21:40.950 --> 06:21:44.920
I'll just end up by reading
something else instead.

06:21:44.920 --> 06:21:47.440
I do want to read this one.

06:22:02.080 --> 06:22:04.980
It's a poem about something
that's actually happening,

06:22:04.980 --> 06:22:07.000
and I'll tell you a little
bit about it, because --

06:22:07.000 --> 06:22:09.900
and the reason I want
to read it here is

06:22:09.900 --> 06:22:15.020
because I think it
concerns all poets.

06:22:15.020 --> 06:22:20.390
However you may care or
not care about animals,

06:22:20.390 --> 06:22:25.330
poets and the marginal aspect, I've
been hearing about the mainstream

06:22:25.330 --> 06:22:28.400
and about computers and so on in
all this time and I've never felt

06:22:28.400 --> 06:22:32.660
that I belonged to the
mainstream in a lot of ways.

06:22:32.660 --> 06:22:35.520
I felt that my life was
marginal and there's a part --

06:22:35.520 --> 06:22:37.450
there's a thing about poets

06:22:37.450 --> 06:22:42.440
that is deliberately
marginal and always has been.

06:22:42.440 --> 06:22:45.720
We speak from the edges
of things and that's

06:22:45.720 --> 06:22:49.710
where we recognize a place there.

06:22:49.710 --> 06:22:57.860
When poets -- when -- in the
beginning of the romantic period

06:22:57.860 --> 06:23:06.340
from which Dante came, the line
between those who wrote poems

06:23:06.340 --> 06:23:12.320 position:56%
and those who recited them in public
was vague and it kept dissolving.

06:23:12.320 --> 06:23:19.050 position:56%
And the [inaudible] were -- the
[inaudible] were the people who used

06:23:19.050 --> 06:23:26.720
to sing the poems -- this
poem has just disappeared.

06:23:26.720 --> 06:23:30.830
The [inaudible] were associated
with people who did all sorts

06:23:30.830 --> 06:23:37.420
of juggler acts and dancing
acts, and with people

06:23:37.420 --> 06:23:42.880
who had dancing bears, dancing
bears, a strange figure.

06:23:42.880 --> 06:23:49.680
Bears sometimes have been
taught to dance kindly,

06:23:49.680 --> 06:23:51.280
but that's been seldom the case.

06:23:51.280 --> 06:23:56.130
Bears don't generally want
to perform for human beings,

06:23:56.130 --> 06:23:58.190 position:56%
unless they've been taught to do it,

06:23:58.190 --> 06:24:01.630
and usually they've been
taught in terrible ways.

06:24:01.630 --> 06:24:04.800
Well that's what's been going on
in Pakistan and is still going

06:24:04.800 --> 06:24:07.810
on in Pakistan, and it's been
going on until quite recently

06:24:07.810 --> 06:24:12.090
in northern India, Greece, Turkey.

06:24:12.090 --> 06:24:16.520
One -- I won't -- I'll spare
you some of the horrible details

06:24:16.520 --> 06:24:23.400 position:56%
about how they're been trained to do
-- well, this is very embarrassing.

06:24:23.400 --> 06:24:25.510
Here we are.

06:24:25.510 --> 06:24:26.810
Here we are.

06:24:26.810 --> 06:24:32.440
Sooner or later, you see, patience,
your patience, not mine [laughter].

06:24:32.440 --> 06:24:36.970
Founded. This will tell you why
I think poets should concern

06:24:36.970 --> 06:24:39.200 position:56%
themselves with this terrible thing.

06:24:39.200 --> 06:24:41.960
There's an association
called the World Society

06:24:41.960 --> 06:24:43.270
for the Protection of Animals.

06:24:43.270 --> 06:24:46.190
You can look that up
if you get concerned

06:24:46.190 --> 06:24:50.530
about what I've been telling
you, and what I'm going to read,

06:24:50.530 --> 06:24:57.020
this poem, which is an angry poem
called Fieste [assumed spelling].

06:24:57.020 --> 06:25:00.630
Almost at the end of the
Century, this is the time

06:25:00.630 --> 06:25:03.250
of the pain of the bears.

06:25:03.250 --> 06:25:06.310
They're agony goes on at
this moment for the amusement

06:25:06.310 --> 06:25:10.250
of the wedding guests, though the
bears are harder to find by now

06:25:10.250 --> 06:25:13.270 position:56%
in the mountain forests of Pakistan.

06:25:13.270 --> 06:25:18.220
They cost more then they used to,
which makes it all the more lavish.

06:25:18.220 --> 06:25:21.190
And once they are caught,
their teeth are pulled out,

06:25:21.190 --> 06:25:23.120
and their claws pulled out.

06:25:23.120 --> 06:25:26.510
And among the entertainments after
the wedding, one of them is hauled

06:25:26.510 --> 06:25:32.520 position:56%
in now and chained to a post and the
dogs let loose to hang on it's nose

06:25:32.520 --> 06:25:36.830
so that the guests laugh at
the way it waves and dances.

06:25:36.830 --> 06:25:41.210
And those old enough to have
watched this many times compare it

06:25:41.210 --> 06:25:44.270
with other performances,
saying they can tell

06:25:44.270 --> 06:25:48.400
from the way the bear screams,
something about the children

06:25:48.400 --> 06:25:52.400
to be born of the couple
sitting there, smiling.

06:25:52.400 --> 06:25:56.760
You may not believe
it, but the bear does.

06:25:59.530 --> 06:26:05.180
And I want to read
one small, very small,

06:26:05.180 --> 06:26:15.940
another animal poem called The
Name of the Air, about a dog.

06:26:15.940 --> 06:26:20.350
It could be like that, then, the
beloved old dog finding it harder

06:26:20.350 --> 06:26:23.800
and hard to breathe, and
understanding but coming

06:26:23.800 --> 06:26:27.710
to ask whether there is something
that can be done about it.

06:26:27.710 --> 06:26:32.680
Coming again to ask and then
standing there without asking.

06:26:32.680 --> 06:26:42.290
I'll read two more poems, and
one of them is also about dogs.

06:26:42.290 --> 06:26:50.780 position:56%
When the great South African writer,
one of the greatest writers alive,

06:26:50.780 --> 06:26:57.120 position:56%
in my opinion, [inaudible], was
invited to give a series of lectures

06:26:57.120 --> 06:27:00.320
at Princeton recently
on any subject he chose.

06:27:00.320 --> 06:27:03.230 position:56%
He said he would like to do it about
[inaudible] in the form of fiction,

06:27:03.230 --> 06:27:05.730
and they said that
would be all right.

06:27:05.730 --> 06:27:10.550
[Inaudible] is an Australian
woman novelist of some age,

06:27:10.550 --> 06:27:13.350 position:56%
[inaudible] invited by the
American university to give a series

06:27:13.350 --> 06:27:18.510 position:56%
of lectures on any subject she
chooses, and she chooses not to give

06:27:18.510 --> 06:27:21.550
on the topic of literature, but
on the human treatment of animals,

06:27:21.550 --> 06:27:23.290
which is a taboo subject.

06:27:23.290 --> 06:27:26.070
You don't mention that
in polite company.

06:27:26.070 --> 06:27:29.000
It's a very interesting book
called, <i>The Lives of Animals </i>,

06:27:29.000 --> 06:27:33.140
this [inaudible] most recent book.

06:27:33.140 --> 06:27:36.820
Why are taboo subjects
taboo subjects?

06:27:37.830 --> 06:27:39.230
Home Tundra.

06:27:39.230 --> 06:27:46.440
It may be that the hour is
snow, seeming never to settle,

06:27:46.440 --> 06:27:51.440
not even to be cold now,
slipping away from underneath it.

06:27:51.440 --> 06:27:54.400
Past, slip -- sorry.

06:27:54.400 --> 06:27:56.900
Slipping away from
underneath into the past

06:27:56.900 --> 06:27:59.960
from which no sounds follow.

06:27:59.960 --> 06:28:03.900
What I hear is the dogs breathing
ahead of me in the shadow.

06:28:03.900 --> 06:28:10.830
Two of them have already gone far
on into the dark of closed pages,

06:28:10.830 --> 06:28:13.460
out of sight and hearing.

06:28:13.460 --> 06:28:19.160
Two of them are old already,
one cannot hear, one cannot see.

06:28:19.160 --> 06:28:24.940
Even in sleep they are running,
drawing me with them on their way,

06:28:24.940 --> 06:28:28.630
wrapped in a day I found today.

06:28:28.630 --> 06:28:33.770
We know where we are because
we are together here, together,

06:28:33.770 --> 06:28:36.570
leaving no footprints in the hour.

06:28:36.570 --> 06:28:46.200
Whatever the diary's say, nobody
ever found the [inaudible].

06:28:46.200 --> 06:28:51.800
Past stream, the chipped lake, gold
strokes on the high clawed hollows

06:28:51.800 --> 06:28:53.620
where you never set foot.

06:28:53.620 --> 06:28:57.320
What would you see from there?

06:28:57.320 --> 06:29:04.820
Not the past, which is fiction,
nor the present, which is the past.

06:29:04.820 --> 06:29:09.070
You would stand there shaken in
the presence of Vertigo, the God,

06:29:09.070 --> 06:29:16.350
clutching the air, hearing that
one note you keep forgetting.

06:29:16.350 --> 06:29:18.150
Thank you.

